<FIRST>u w AM-DownedJet     04-28 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Downed Jet,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Iraq Downed Egyptian Jet By Mistake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iraqi soldier shot down an Egyptian jet
fighter by mistake last week as it descended to land in Baghdad for
an air show, a published report here said.
   The two Egyptian fliers ejected safely before the plane crashed,
The Washington Post reported in Friday's editions.
   The Iraqi government had invited Egypt to fly its home-built
Alpha fighter-bomber to Baghdad for the air show, but apparently
word of the invitation had not reached the soldier who, armed with
shoulder-fired missile, downed the unfamiliar jet, the Post said.
   The newspaper cited secret intelligence reports making the
rounds of U.S. government offices here as the source of the story.
   The Alpha jet was developed by French and German aircraft firms.
Egypt has purchased Alpha kits from France and assembles the
fighter-bomber in a plant south of Cairo. The jet has a top speed
of 600 mph.
   Two years ago, in another case of mistaken identity, an Iraqi
pilot in a Mirage F1 bomber shot two Exocet missiles into the USS
Stark, killing 37 sailors aboard the U.S. frigate in the Persian
Gulf. Iraqi officials said the pilot mistook the U.S. ship for an
Iranian vessel.
   Also, the USS Vincennes downed an Iranian Airbus on July 3,
1988, killing 290 people, as it flew over the Persian Gulf where
U.S. ships were protecting neutral ships during the Iran-Iraq war.
The United States said it attempted repeatedly to contact the plane
for identification, and when it got no response, the Vincennes
destroyed the plane with a surface-to-air missile.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
