<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0046EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e PM-APonTV-MisterRogers     04-28 0852</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Mister Rogers,0871</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miniseries Making Neighborhood Debut</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PG5 Sent April 26.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The miniseries comes to ``Mister Rogers'
Neighborhood'' next week, and the show's cardigan-clad creator
promises a message as gentle and reassuring as ever.
   The three-part musical, titled ``Josephine the Short-Neck
Giraffe,'' tells the story of a young giraffe who yearns for a
long, graceful neck like all the other giraffes. She eventually
grows, Fred Rogers confided, ``not on the outside, but on the
important side.''
   ``It's very much like the usual message of the Neighborhood,
that you can be acceptable as you are,'' he said, smiling. ``It's
not so much the outsides of us that are important.''
   A song sung by Josephine and her friend Hazel the elephant sums
it up best, according to Rogers.
   ``You're much more than a neck, Josephine. And you're much more
than a trunk, Hazel. A chicken's more than a peck, and there's more
than a smell to a skunk,'' Rogers quietly sang during an interview
at Pittsburgh's WQED-TV, home to his children's programs for the
past 35 years.
   The special week of new programs gets under way Monday on Public
Broadcasting Service stations with a trip to the San Diego Wild
Animal Park, where viewers are introduced to real-life giraffes and
elephants. On Tuesday, Rogers visits a film processing lab to have
his animal photographs developed.
   The miniseries, which features a cast of 15, elaborate animal
costumes and five sets, runs Wednesday through Friday. Rogers
gently guides his young audience from one day to the next,
summarizing the main events and hinting at what might lie ahead for
Josephine.
   In the Neighborhood of Make-Believe, where animals sing, dance
and play the trombone, Josephine is befriended by J.R., a shy
giraffe who overcomes his problems by helping Josephine conquer
hers. He accomplishes that with help from Hazel the elephant, who
advises him to ``just let your heart speak.''
   ``There isn't a time that I see the scene in which J.R. talks
and sings with Josephine ... that I haven't gotten chills up my
spine,'' Rogers said, tapping his right hand against his back.
``And this is something I've worked with for years. There's
something so redemptive about someone who is trying so hard to help
somebody else.''
   Rogers, 61, wrote ``Josephine the Short-Neck Giraffe'' for a
French class assignment at Florida's Rollins College in 1950. He
named J.R. the giraffe after fraternity brother John Reardon, who
went on to sing with the Metropolitan Opera and was a frequent
guest on ``Mister Rogers Neighborhood.'' Reardon died a year ago,
and the miniseries is dedicated to him.
   Rogers set the story to music in the late 1950s, and about 1,000
records were pressed. Writer Barry Head transformed ``Josephine the
Short-Neck Giraffe'' into a poem for children in 1975.
   For years, Rogers tried to have the musical produced on stage or
as an animated film.
   ``I still think it would be great for animation and a stage
production,'' he said. ``But I thought unless we get it out on the
air, I don't think anybody's going to know about it.''
   The story Rogers wrote 39 years ago is vastly different from the
musical airing next week. It is the Neighborhood's 13th musical.
   ``At the end of the (original) story, when people are telling
Josephine that they like her just the way she is, she raises her
head to look at them because she hasn't really heard this message
before and her neck starts to grow. And it grows and grows and
grows until her neck is as tall as everybody else's,'' Rogers said.
   In the musical, Josephine's neck remains short.
   ``I think it shows how much we've grown,'' Rogers said. ``You
know, you don't have to look like everybody else to be acceptable
and to feel acceptable. And wishes don't always come true.
   ``Because for a year and a day I've been wishing, she sang. That
was one of her first songs. Her wish was for a longer neck, she
thought. But really her wish was to have people like her exactly as
she is. So often what we say we're wishing for isn't necessarily
what is behind the wish. This is very philosophical.''
   Will pre-schoolers be able to grasp such a serious message, even
in such a light-hearted setting?
   ``Maybe not in words, but let their hearts speak to them the way
Hazel said to J.R., `Just let your heart speak,''' Rogers said. ``I
think that that's the way an awful lot of communication takes
place.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   REAL-LIFE DRAMAS _ ABC has scheduled the made-for-TV movie about
the real-life rescue of little Jessica McClure from a Texas well
for May 21. Beau Bridges, Pat Hingle, Roxana Zal and Patty Duke
star. ... Production is set to begin on ``The Preppy Murder,'' a
two-hour ``docudrama'' for ABC about the case of Robert Chambers
who was convicted in the death of Jennifer Levin following what he
said was an accident during ``rough sex'' in Central Park. The
movie will air sometime later this season.
</TEXT>
