<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0122EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Entrepreneurs     04-28 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Entrepreneurs,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>What Makes a Successful Entreprenuer? MIT Just Might Know</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What makes a successful entreprenuer? A
recent Massachusetts Institute of Technology survey reports that
many are immigrants, the offspring of self-employed parents and
hold advanced degrees.
   The survey of 99 MIT graduates who will be honored by the
university Saturday night provides some insight into the men and
women who give upthe security of a salary to take a chance on their
own business.
   As part of the institute's 128th anniversary, it will honor the
99 sociology consultants, financial managers and computer
technicians for their ``hard work, foresight and courage.''
   Collectively, they have created 100,000 jobs in the state and
250,000 worldwide in fields that range from women's apparel to
geotechnical engineering. The cumulative sales of their companies
total $25 billion annually.
   According to the survey, 73 percent earned an educational degree
above the bachelor level, and 33 percent went on to doctorate or
post-doctorate work.
   Sixteen percent founded their companies while they were still at
school, 34 percent set up shop within five years of graduating and
23 percent opened for business between six years and 10 years after
graduation. Two percent founded their companies more than 20 years
after graduation.
   The survey said more than half were the children of parents who
founded their own companies.
   Many of the companies had inauspicious beginnings in basements
or rough neighborhoods with minimal staff and equipment. But some
of the entrepreneurs had more colorful starts.
   Clark Abt, founder of the social sciences consulting firm Abt
Associates, built ship models and sold them to Saks Fifth Avenue
when he was only 12. Harold ``Doc'' Edgerton, whom the institute
called ``the father of flash photography,'' attempted to market his
first strobe equipment through General Electric Co., but GE wasn't
interested.
   The three most important lessons the entrepreneurs said MIT
taught them were problem solving, the importance of hard work,
confidence and the belief that anything is possible.
   And when these busy people take the time to relax and enjoy
success, most said they enjoyed tennis, skiing, sailing, music and
art and reading.
   In the advice department, the entrepreneurs recommend that
aspiring business adventurers begin by identifying a market
opportunity and matching it with an appropriate technology, select
partners with talents that complement their own and remember that
the success of the enterprise rests with the performance of its
employees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
