<DOCNO> AP890428-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0159EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Politics-Glance     04-28 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Politics-Glance,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Government Structure At A Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Politics, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is an outline of the structure of the Soviet
Communist Party and government:
   PARTY STRUCTURE:
   The Communist Party holds political power in the Soviet Union,
but President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has proposed changes that allow
some contested elections to form a legislature that may exercise
significant political power.
   The Communist Party's power is centered in the Politburo and the
Secretariat of the party's Central Committee.
   The Communist Party Congress, which has 5,000 elected members,
is supposed to be the party's supreme organ, and ordinarily meets
every five years. The congress elects the Central Committee, made
up of 250 to 300 of the country's top leaders. It now has 251
members.
   The Central Committee normally meets about twice a year to
approve policies and formally elects the members of the Politburo
and the Secretariat, the two highest party bodies.
   Since March 11, 1985, Gorbachev been general secretary of the
Communist Party, head of the Secretariat and leading member of the
Politburo. Since Oct. 1, 1988, Gorbachev also has been the nation's
president, holding top party and government jobs.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Secretariat:
   This Communist Party body is responsible for running social and
economic spheres as well as party personnel and ideology, and
wields tremendous power over implementation of policy. Politburo
membership and a seat on the secretariat traditionally have been
considered necessary to gain the top party job. There are now 10
secretaries, including Gorbachev.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Politburo:
   Gorbachev runs meetings of the Politburo, the party's most
powerful body. It now has 12 full members and eight candidate, or
non-voting, members. The Politburo normally meets every week.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   GOVERNMENT STRUCTURE:
   The Supreme Soviet:
   The 1,500 members are elected from a single slate of approved
candidates and theoretically make up the top government body in the
Soviet Union. But it has traditionally met only twice a year to
ratify policy set by the Communist Party.
   Under a reform pushed through by Gorbachev, the Supreme Soviet
will become a smaller body _ with about 500 members _ that meets
several months a year. Gorbachev says he wants it to be more
active, handling operational questions the party apparatus has
assumed over the years and leaving the party to decide policy
questions. But the Supreme Soviet has not met under the new format,
and the extent of its powers is uncertain.
   The Presidium of the Supreme Soviet:
   The presidium, which has 37 members, is the collective
presidency that Gorbachev leads as chairman. Presidents of each of
the 15 Soviet republics are members. The presidium has the power to
issue government decrees when the Supreme Soviet, or parliament, is
not in session. But the presence of Politburo and regional party
leaders in its membership ensures its actions have prior top-level
approval.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Council of Ministers:
   The council, the Soviet Union's Cabinet, is responsible for
day-to-day operation of government ministries such as agriculture
or transportation. It is headed by Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov, a
full member of the Politburo.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   CONGRESS OF PEOPLES DEPUTIES:
   The Congress of Peoples Deputies is a new 2,250-member body
consisting of 1,500 deputies elected from geographical
organizations and 750 elected from the party and its affiliates,
social, professional and trade union organizations.
   The congress, which was elected in the first multicandidate
balloting, is empowered to choose the president and the Supreme
Soviet from among its members, amend the constitution, and review
the president's choice for premier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
