<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0201EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Afghanistan'sMan Bjt   04-28 0741</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan's Man, Bjt,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Loneliest Diplomat in Town?</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ostracized by the State Department, confined
to the city limits, Afghanistan's top diplomat in Washington leads
a frustrating existence.
   Miagol _ the first, last and only name of Afghanistan's charge
d'affaires _ is hoping the recent pullout of 115,000 Soviet troops
from his country will ease some of the isolation imposed on him by
the United States. But he is also realistic.
   The Soviet-educated economist invited Secretary of State James
A. Baker III to his embassy's reception Thursday evening marking
the 11th anniversary of the revolution that brought to power a
Marxist-oriented government and resulted in the 1979 Soviet
invasion.
   ``They said he couldn't come, unfortunately,'' Miagol said with
a skeptical laugh.
   Very few Americans attended the reception, which drew mostly
diplomats from Soviet bloc and other communist and socialist
countries.
   For a man who has to ask permission every time he wants to leave
the city _ and is usually turned down _ Miagol was remarkably
cheerful at an interview in the resplendent red-brick mansion which
doubles as residence and embassy.
   ``Physically our life is good,'' he said, ``but morale is
difficult.''
   Miagol, one of 15 children, does not know how old he is but
estimates his age at about 40. ``My mother said there was snow on
the ground, but she didn't know in what year,'' he said.
   Miagol arrived here 10 months ago with his Russian wife and two
children. When he asked to travel to New York by car to attend the
General Assembly meetings of the U.N. last fall, he was told to go
by plane.
   When he asked permission to drive to the Soviet Embassy's
recreation compound outside Washington, he was denied. ``They said
it was too far. But people from other socialist embassies also have
25-mile limit, and they are allowed to go,'' Miagol said.
   The United States and other countries impose 25-mile travel
limits on diplomats from countries deemed unfriendly.
   ``This makes me nervous,'' Miagol said. He spends his days
reading messages received by telex from Kabul, dealing with
administrative matters relating to his three-man embassy and
keeping in touch with the extensive community of Afghan exiles in
Washington.
   His only contact with the State Department is through Richard
Gookin, head of the Protocol Department, whom he sees about twice a
month. ``I give him my opinions,'' Miagol said.
   Gookin listens politely _ ``he's a very nice man'' _ and conveys
Miagol's views to State Department experts. But Gookin refused to
accept a written message from Afghanistan's leader Najibullah
congratulating George Bush on his inauguration as president and
expressing his hopes for improved relations, Miagol said.
   ``They told me to put the envelope in a window for letters'' at
the State Department, he said. Miagol said he used the same window
to deliver a second message several weeks ago asking the United
States to stop arming the Mujahedeen rebels.
   The rebels, backed by the United States and Pakistan, fought the
Soviet occupation for nine years and are now locked in a civil war
with Najibullah's Soviet-backed government.
   The United States continues to view Najibullah as a hardline
Marxist and fails to see that he is gaining acceptance by Afghans
as the only viable choice for leading the war-wracked country,
Miagol said.
   ``They must learn from the mistakes of the Soviets, who didn't
understand the Afghan people,'' Miagol said.
   Neither the Soviets nor the Americans understand that Afghans
cannot embrace Marxism, he said. ``It is not right with our
culture, with our religion,'' said the Soviet-educated Moslem.
   The United States withheld recognition from Afghanistan's
government after the Soviets invaded, contending it was not elected
democratically and does not represent the Afghan people. However,
the U.S. Embassy continued to function in Kabul, serving as a
listening post in the Soviet-run country.
   ``The United States recognizes many governments that are not
democratic, that are fascist dictatorships,'' Miagol said. At least
Najibullah was elected to office _ ``maybe not like American
elections,'' but in accordance with Afghanistan's constitution, he
said.
   Once, the Soviets were considered the bad guys in Afghanistan
and the Americans were the good guys, Miagol said. Now, the Soviet
tanks and troops have left and they are sending wheat, flour and
oil, while the Americans send missiles to the Mujahedeen.
   ``If the U.S. continues this, Afghanistan will of course be
pro-Soviet,'' Miagol said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
