<DOCNO> AP890428-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Soviet-Military     04-28 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Military,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kremlin Will Publish Defense and Space Spending Data, Scientist Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kremlin will publish long-promised figures
on the Soviet defense and space budgets by the end of the year,
says Roald Sagdeyev, a leading Russian rocket scientist who is
prominent in the reform movement.
   Soviet military spending is being cut 1.5 percent this year, far
short of the 14.2 percent cut announced by Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev in January, said Sagdeyev, who is a member of the Supreme
Soviet, or parliament.
   Defense spending will go down another 7 percent in 1990, and the
cuts will reach 14.2 percent the following year, he said, although
the total amount of the cuts remained unclear.
   ``We have promised that the absolute figure would be given in
the fall,'' Sagdeyev told a group of reporters Thursday. Sagdeyev
declined to specify how he knew that military spending figures
would be disclosed by year end, but he is thought to be part of a
group of scientists and intellectuals who advise Gorbachev on
foreign policy.
   Sagdeyev was also elected in balloting March 26 to represent the
Soviet Academy of Sciences in the newly created Congress of
Peoples' Deputies, which will have the twin functions of electing a
Soviet president _ almost certainly voting Gorbachev a new
five-year term _ and selecting a new smaller parliament.
   The issue of Soviet military spending is murky. For years,
Western analysts have complained that figures for Soviet defense
spending were distorted because prices are set by the state, and
the cost of expensive armaments could be vastly underestimated in
official statistics.
   An indefinite delay in implementing price deregulation has led
Western analysts to say that even more complete disclosure of
Soviet military spending cannot be accurate, since Soviet leaders
themselves do not know the true cost of weapons.
   A study released last weekend by the Central Intelligence Agency
and the Pentagon's Defense Intelligence Agency said that Soviet
military spending had risen by 3 percent in 1988.
   The CIA found strong evidence, however, that last year
``Gorbachev took several actions that evidently were intended to
lay the groundwork for future military cuts.''
   Furthermore, the CIA concluded, the 14.2 percent cut in military
spending announced by Gorbachev last January probably will lead to
much larger cuts than the 500,000 troop reduction he announced at
the United Nations last December.
   Sagdeyev's description of the 14.2 percent defense cuts as
gradual suggested that Gorbachev wants to make them as part of arms
control agreements with the United States.
   Sagdeyev, in a wide-ranging discussion, also released the text
of a hitherto undisclosed resolution he said was passed by the
Academy of Sciences last week describing the deaths of 20
demonstrators in Soviet Georgia as a ``criminal act'' that
endangered to Kremlin reforms.
   Sagdeyev was one of three members of the Soviet academy, along
with human rights activist Andrei D. Sakharov and Russian historian
Dmitri S. Likhachev, appointed to a parliamentary investigating
panel.
   ``The tragic events in Tbilisi (capital of Soviet Georgia)
confirm the sad fact that perestroika is in danger,'' said the
resolution, using the Russian name for Gorbachev's reforms.
   Special uniformed troops under the Soviet Interior Ministry, or
MVD, were responsible for using poisonous chemicals, shovels and
clubs to suppress the demonstrations in Tbilisi on April 9, killing
20 people, the statement said.
   ``This unusually cruel act has evoked the deep indignation and
outrage of our entire society,'' said the resolution, which
Sagdeyev said was passed at a meeting of the entire Academy of
Sciences April 21.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890428-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0246EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Shuttle-GraphicLaunch     04-28 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shuttle-Graphic Launch,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atlantis Astronauts Rely on New Graphics-Oriented Monitors</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA, designing systems in which
three or four seconds ``is forever,'' has developed a
graphics-oriented computer program to help flight controllers react
to launch emergencies.
   Atlantis, with five astronauts aboard, was scheduled to launch
at midafternoon today.
   In the seconds and minutes after liftoff, NASA is to make its
most extensive use of a flight control system which highlights
potential hazards with colorful displays.
   Past mission managers had to sort through mind-numbing columns
of data on black-and-white monitors that date back to the Gemini
era of the 1960s.
   The new system, inaugurated at Mission Control after the 1986
Challenger disaster, gives NASA controllers three or four more
seconds to order a shuttle into an emergency landing in case of a
sudden failure after liftoff.
   ``Three to four seconds in a lot of different failure modes is
forever,'' says senior NASA controller John F. Muratore.
   From typewriter-style keyboards, controllers can now punch up
graphics that trace the shuttle trajectory, duplicate cockpit
instrument displays and even mimic the horizon as the astronauts
see it from inside their rising space ship.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration is designing
artificial intelligence programs to help plug its ``brain drain''
as thousands of experienced Apollo era employees retire. The
generic name for such programs is ``expert systems.''
   NASA has begun implementing its expert system at the Mission
Control center in Houston as part of a multimillion-dollar
improvement program scheduled for completion in 1991. Muratore is
in charge of developing the system.
   NASA hopes expert systems can capture the knowledge of veteran
employees to help younger workers do various jobs. Muratore
predicted his system will cut months off the minimum time of two
years that controllers must spend in training before being assigned
to a flight.
   ``They have to make a mental picture of what's going on with the
shuttle,'' Muratore explained. ``We took some senior controllers
and learned how they built their mental models, then programmed the
computer to do that for them.''
   When shuttles returned to flight in September, NASA installed
the expert system to help engineers pinpoint trouble in the
orbiter's three main engines. It ran in tandem with the traditional
system.
   ``We were prepared to take actions'' based on the new program,
Muratore said. ``I don't know of any other case where somebody has
built an expert system and then put life and property on the line
that way.''
   Since then, Muratore said, the system has become a ``primary
tool'' for four controllers who monitor communications, engines,
mechanical systems, and guidance and navigation.
   With the system NASA is phasing out, controllers decipher
multiple pages of data displayed on their computer screens, all
while monitoring dozens of blinking console lights _ each of which
can signal two or more safe or unsafe conditions.
   In the old system, flight information is stored in two computers
and displayed on every controller's console. By comparison,
Muratore's system divides the data among individual consoles,
shaving precious seconds off the processing.
</TEXT>
