<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0244EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-S&amp;Ls     04-28 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Wants S&amp;L Owners to Put up More Money</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Banking Committee members who want
savings and loan owners to put up more of their own money when they
make loans will be fighting to preserve a legislative victory when
they resume work next week on President Bush's bailout proposal.
   After hours of debate, the panel voted 36-15 Thursday to require
S&amp;L owners by January 1995 to risk $3 of ``tangible'' or ``real
money'' capital for every $100 they lend.
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady praised the action in a
statement released after the vote, even though the deadline is 3{
years later than the June 1991 date sought by the administration.
   ``Requiring S&amp;Ls to put their own capital at risk ahead of the
taxpayers' money is the only way to prevent in the future the
unsound business practices that contributed to the current
crisis,'' Brady said.
   Bush is proposing to spend at least $157 billion over 10 years,
the bulk of it from taxpayers, to close or merge failed S&amp;Ls. He
also wants to restructure the regulatory system, spend $50 million
a year to investigate and prosecute fraud in S&amp;Ls and boost capital
requirements.
   Assistant Treasury Secretary David Mullins said the panel's
adoption of a 3 percent layer of protection between S&amp;L loans that
could go sour and federal insurance funds was more important than
the timetable for achieving it.
   However, consumer groups are worried about a subsequent
amendment, sponsored by Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla., that would
permit thrift institutions to continue to risk depositors' funds in
subsidiaries involved in high-risk investments such as junk bonds
and commercial real estate.
   ``It's a pretty critical loophole,'' said Peggy Miller, a
lobbyist for the Consumer Federation of America. ``It erodes what
was just passed.''
   The administration had proposed that institutions raise extra
capital to back those subsidiaries and the committee chairman, Rep.
Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas, had attempted to compromise by giving
institutions five years to come up with the money.
   However, the committee voted 26-24 to adopt McCollum's measure.
He argued that without it many institutions now operating safely
and profitably with subsidiaries would not be able to raise the
extra capital.
   Another amendment, sponsored by Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass.,
would permit federal regulators to count mortgage servicing
contracts as capital. Such contracts, which pay institutions to
collect monthly payments from homeowners on behalf of investors who
own the mortgages, provide a steady source of income and can be
sold if an institution is closed.
   The overall capital measure has a series of interim targets,
beginning June 1, 1990, when the tangible capital standard would
become 1.5 percent. It would move to 2 percent in January 1992,
2.25 percent in January 1993 and 2.625 percent in January 1994
before reaching the full 3 percent a year later.
   The House committee's standard is substantially stricter than
the bill passed last week by the Senate, which would require 1.5
percent tangible capital by June 1991.
   Current law provides for a 3 percent standard, but contains many
accounting loopholes that count intangible assets such as
``goodwill'' as capital.
   At the end of last year, more than a third of the solvent S&amp;Ls'
$60 billion in listed capital was composed of goodwill, which
represents the value an institution's customer loyalty and name
recognition. Critics argue that goodwill evaporates when an
institution fails and thus provides no protection to government
deposit insurance funds.
   According to the Treasury Department, about two-thirds of the
nation's 3,000 S&amp;Ls can meet the 3 percent tangible standard. Some
of those that do not should be able to raise the money, but about
245 may have to seek merger partners, it said.
   Institutions failing to meet the standard would be subject to
growth restrictions and closer regulatory supervision.
   Rep. Floyd Flake, D-N.Y., said he intends to offer an amendment
Monday that would provide more favorable treatment of goodwill. He
and others, including the powerful chairman of the House Rules
Committee, Rep. Claude Pepper, D-Fla., argue that it is unfair to
wipe out the goodwill because during the early 1980s regulators
permitted the accounting break to otherwise healthy institutions in
exchange for taking over ailing thrifts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890428-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0243EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-BaldnessDrug     04-28 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baldness Drug,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Baldness Drug Works on Growth Genes, Researchers Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Researchers for a Michigan pharmaceutical
company say the anti-baldness drug minoxidil appears to stimulate
the genes that make hair grow.
   Minoxidil ``not only affects growing cells, but affects cells
that make hair-shaft protein,'' Vincent Groppi Jr., a research with
the Upjohn Co. of Kalamazoo, Mich., said Wednesday. ``Minoxidil
affects gene activity that affects the growth of the (hair) shaft.''
   Knowledge gained from study of minoxidil's effects on genes
could have implications for research into genetically based
diseases, such as sickle-cell anemia, said Allen Buhl, also an
Upjohn researcher.
   Marketed by Upjohn under the trade-name Rogaine, minoxidil was
originally developed for use internally to control blood pressure.
The Food and Drug Administration last year approved the drug for
use externally as a treatment for baldness.
   Although the drug is approved for sale, scientists haven't
clearly understood why minoxidil promotes hair growth. Upjohn
researchers had theorized that the drug improved the flow of blood
to the hair roots, thereby stimulating growth.
   However, the Upjohn research, released at the annual meeting of
the Society for Investigational Dermatology, suggested the drug had
a more basic effect on hair growth.
   Groppi said he believes minoxidil's effect on the genes is
particularly strong. ``I can't think of (a drug) offhand that has
such a potent effect on gene expression,'' he said.
   Another scientist, however, was skeptical that the Upjohn
finding represented a significant advance.
   ``It could well be that it does affect those genes, but there
are very many stimulants on the cells that control genes,'' said
Robert Weinberg, biology professor at the Massachusetts Institute
of Technology in Cambridge, Mass. ``That does not set minoxidil
apart.''
   Although the drug may affect hair follicles, there is no reason
to believe that the drug would have similar effects on other types
of cells, Weinberg said.
   Weinberg said the research would have been more convincing had
it identified a specific gene or group of genes affected by the
drug. Upjohn spokeswoman Kaye Bennett said the researchers hadn't
identified a specific gene.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
