<FIRST>r a PM-PlaneDoorHearing     04-28 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Plane Door Hearing,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>United Did Not Fully Inspect Ill-Fated Cargo Door</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hearing on why a cargo door tore off a United
Airlines 747, killing nine passengers, ended without conclusive
evidence on the cause of the February accident southwest of Hawaii.
   The National Transportation Safety Board listened for three days
to a list of missteps by United Airlines and the Federal Aviation
Administration, and grilled aircraft designers from The Boeing Co.,
but no culprit emerged.
   ``The hearings here were extremely helpful,'' Lee Dickinson,
chairman of the NTSB investigation, said Thursday. ``We gained a
lot of good information.''
   He declined to make any conclusions, but said the information
will be analyzed for several months before the NTSB issues a final
report identifying the probable cause of the accident, Dickinson
said.
   The cargo door and part of the fuselage tore off United Flight
811 as the Boeing 747 was climbing to 23,000 feet on Feb. 24. Nine
passengers were sucked out of the plane over the Pacific Ocean, 85
miles southwest of Honolulu as the plane headed for Australia via
New Zealand.
   Speculation has focused on a possible malfunction in the locking
mechanism of the cargo door, which remains on the bottom of the
Pacific Ocean. The NTSB has not decided whether to retrieve the
door.
   On Thursday, United Airlines officials said they failed to fully
inspect a cargo door after electrical repairs were made two months
before the accident.
   A United executive said mechanics made a partial inspection of
the cargo door after it was repaired Dec. 23 in Chicago. That was a
coincidence, because the company has testified it was unaware it
was under federal regulations to do a full inspection of the doors.
   ``I am convinced the check ... verified that the door was
working,'' said Robert Doll, United vice president for technical
services.
   He added, however, that the inspection was not as thorough as
the Federal Aviation Administration required.
   In other testimony, an FAA inspector who oversees United's
31-plane 747 fleet said he was not aware of the problems with the
800-pound cargo door.
   The inspector, George Batiza, also said the FAA had failed to
ensure that United complied with a federal rule that took effect
July 1, requiring airlines to inspect cargo doors after they were
manually operated because of electrical problems.
   Batiza testified that he had not found any deficiencies in
United's maintenance program recently, even though United officials
have acknowledged they were unaware of the FAA rule on cargo door
inspections and were not in compliance for about nine months.
</TEXT>
