<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0239EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Budget     04-28 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Sends $1.17 Trillion Budget to Floor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leading lawmakers predict that a $1.17
trillion budget for 1990, thrashed out in days of often contentious
closed-door meetings by the House Budget Committee, will be
approved by the House next week.
   The panel approved the spending plan on a bipartisan 18-6 vote
on Thursday, edging the budget deal completed two weeks ago between
President Bush and congressional leaders closer to enactment.
   The proposal claims a deficit of $99.4 billion, just within the
$100 billion ceiling required by the Gramm-Rudman balanced budget
law. It would hold defense spending below the rate of inflation and
give big boosts to education, science and health programs, while
cutting agriculture, environment and energy spending.
   As they finished their work on the document, committee members
echoed remarks made frequently in recent days about the direction
this year's budget seems to be headed.
   ``I assume it will pass because there is no alternative,'' said
Rep. Martin Olav Sabo, D-Minn., who voted against the proposal in
committee.
   Rep. Harold Rogers, R-Ky., who also opposed the plan, said he
believed that the deficit reduction it claimed was largely phony,
but that the proposal would be approved anyway.
   ``With the head of steam it's got from the budget summit and
from the Democratic and Republican leadership, it will be hard to
overcome,'' he said.
   House Majority Leader Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., who is on the
committee, also predicted the measure would clear the chamber,
saying he expected little trouble from conservatives over the
defense expenditures it permits.
   ``Do you think people will look at the defense money in this
bill, with its being blessed by Bush and Cheney, and say it's not
enough?'' Foley said.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney has said he believes the cuts in
the defense budget will be difficult but are manageable.
   Because the budget pact between Bush and congressional leaders
set overall spending limits for defense, domestic programs and
foreign aid, those figures are identical in the House and Senate
versions of the budget. The main differences between the two
chambers is in how they distribute domestic funds.
   Energy programs would get $3.8 billion in the House plan and
$4.2 billion in the Senate. Health spending would reach $56.2
billion under the House proposal and $55.7 billion under the
Senate. Education would get $39.1 billion under the House budget
and $38.7 billion under the Senate.
   The House budget writers set aside enough money to pay for a
Democratic initiative on children, with $1.8 billion for child care
and more money for Head Start; an increase to $1.9 billion for AIDS
research and treatment; full-inflation increases in programs for
the poor; and a 3.6 percent cost-of-living raise for military and
civilian federal workers.
   Before holding a brief public meeting at which they approved the
spending plan, the budget committee met behind closed doors this
week, arguing over spending priorities and working out a bipartisan
deal.
   According to meeting participants who asked to not be
identified, those sessions resulted in money being transferred to
space and science programs, and to veterans programs, from other
domestic initiatives.
   There were also attempts by liberals to slash the defense budget
and distribute the money to domestic programs, such as Medicare,
AIDS research, low-income programs, veterans health, and anti-drug
efforts.
   The Senate Budget Committee passed its version of the budget on
April 19. That chamber also expects to complete work next week on
its spending blueprint.
</TEXT>
