<FIRST>r w PM-Jesuits-Nicaragua     04-28 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jesuits-Nicaragua,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jesuit Publicly Disobeys Orders to Stop Work for Nicaraguans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic priest who is defying orders
from his Jesuit superior in the United States to leave a group that
provides aid to rural Nicaraguans has appealed his case to the
Vatican.
   The Rev. Bill Callahan, co-director of the Quixote Center in Mt.
Rainier, Md., held a news conference Thursday to declare his
defiance. Callahan, a Jesuit for 40 of his 57 years, is also under
orders to dissociate himself from a progressive Catholic group and
one that supports the ordination of women as priests.
   Callahan's order, for its part, refused to make the controversy
any more public than it already was.
   ``Dealings ...between a religious and his superior are very much
a confidential matter, and superiors find themselves in the
position of having to protect that confidentiality,'' the Rev. Paul
Kenney, press officer of the New England province of the Society of
Jesus, said by telephone from Boston.
   The Rev. Robert E. Manning, Jesuit provincial in Boston, has
twice ordered Callahan, on pain of dismissal from the society, to
leave the center and join a Jesuit community in Boston within 15
days.
   Callahan appealed the order to the Rev. Peter Kolvenbach, Jesuit
general in Rome, saying, ``To leave at this time would be a serious
betrayal of my responsibility toward the people of Nicaragua.''
   Callahan said Mannings's orders would make it impossible for him
to carry on the work of Quest for Peace, an organization which he
coordinates from the Quixote Center's headquarters.
   In his letter to Kolvenbach, he said Quest for Peace was formed
``to match U.S. military aid to the counter-revolutionaries
attacking Nicaragua with an equivalent value in donated
humanitarian aid for the people of Nicaragua.''
   He said he had coordinated campaigns which raised $227 million
over a three-year period in donated aid and contributed services.
   Earlier, Manning had told Callahan that in order to remain a
member of the society he must dissociate himself from ``Catholics
Speak Out,'' an organization of Progressive Catholics, and
``Priests for Equality,'' which favors the ordination of women as
priests.
   In a letter on April 3, after Callahan said he was willing to
work toward ``an acceptable compromise to alleviate the
situation,'' Manning told Callahan, ``In fact, this is not a
question of `compromise.' It is, to repeat, a matter of obedience.''
   Callahan said the second deadline for him to report in Boston
was April 2. He said he had heard nothing further about his
dismissal.
   Manning also wrote to Callahan that he must ``make no public
statements critical of the church or its leadership without my
prior knowledge and consent'' and not ``add any projects to the
mission I have given you without my prior consent.''
</TEXT>
