<FIRST>r w PM-TeamstersAppointment     04-28 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Teamsters Appointment,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Detroit Teamsters Official with two Convictions Named International
VP</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Detroit-area Teamsters official with two
convictions for union-related offenses has been named an
international vice president of the nation's largest union, raising
questions about its pledge to improve its image.
   The selection of George Vitale by Teamsters President William J.
McCarthy, though not announced by the union, was confirmed Thursday
by Teamsters sources. A Teamsters spokesman did not return
telephone calls seeking comment.
   The selection comes in the wake of the settlement of a
racketeering suit against the Teamsters and a pledge by its leaders
to back election reforms and refurbish the union's image.
   ``McCarthy surely could have done better than to go out and
appoint a guy who has been convicted of taking payoffs both from
employers and stealing the union members' money,'' said Ken Paff of
Teamsters for a Democratic Union, a dissident union group based in
Detroit.
   Vitale, president of Teamsters Local 283 in Wyandotte, Mich.,
was convicted twice in the early 1970s, for accepting an illegal
payment from a Teamsters employer and for illegal use of union
funds in a plan to buy his wife a car. He received fines and
probation for both convictions but was allowed to keep his union
job.
   The prosecutor who handled the racketeering case raised the
possibility that a court-appointed administrator agreed to as part
of the settlement could review the Vitale appointment.
   ``The court-appointed administrator will have the authority to
review the appointment and to discipline any Teamster officials,''
said assistant U.S. attorney Randy Mastro. ``There is no statute of
limitations on the right to discipline.''
   The appointment of an administrator is expected to be made in
the next two weeks. That is one of three court-appointed monitoring
positions agreed to as part of the settlement of the racketeering
suit, which alleged widespread organized crime influence on the
Teamsters.
   Critics within the union characterized the Vitale appointment as
a slap at former Teamsters Vice President Robert Holmes Sr. of
Detroit. Holmes resigned in January in return for being dropped as
a defendant in the suit.
   Holmes opposed McCarthy's election to succeed the late Jackie
Presser as Teamsters president. Vitale reportedly had a falling out
with Holmes in recent years.
   McCarthy under Teamsters bylaws can fill vacancies on the
union's General Executive Board _ which consists of the president,
secretary-treasurer and 16 international vice presidents _ subject
to board approval. He has a solid majority on the board because of
recent turnover and has two vacancies still to fill.
</TEXT>
