<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0334EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-100Days-ForeignPolicy     04-28 0751</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-100 Days-Foreign Policy,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: No Polemics, No Bold Initiatives So far</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After only 100 days, it's hard to tell if
President Bush's foreign policy is intentionally uninspiring or if
he is simply taking his time coming to conclusions about America's
role in the world.
   He has pulled back from the polemics of his predecessor, Ronald
Reagan, and in a few as yet inconclusive ways, such as a toughening
stand toward Israel, indicated that he just might adopt a foreign
policy that is substantively different from the one he inherited.
   On the other hand, these changes are so slight it could turn out
that Bush has no bold initiatives in mind, and that like President
Gerald R. Ford in the mid-1970s he intends mostly to mark time in
the foreign field.
   An overseas crisis could intervene, forcing Bush to improvise a
response that could lead to a dramatic shift in U.S. policy. The
rise to power in Moscow in 1985 of Mikhail S. Gorbachev, for
instance, impelled Reagan to drop his denunciations of the Soviet
Union as an evil empire. The result was a series of negotiations
that produced a lessening of tensions and the banning of U.S. and
Soviet intermediate-range nuclear missiles.
   So far, international events have not conspired to draw Bush
into major decisions. A political scandal in Japan and growing West
German distaste for nuclear weapons could produce severe strains,
but Bush has given no sign of a shift in U.S. support for Japan or
U.S. determination to modernize Lance missiles in Europe.
   Bush has worked out a temporary deal with Congress to supply the
Nicaraguan rebels with $49.8 million in non-military aid and he has
endorsed an Israeli proposal for elections among Palestinian Arabs
to implement self-rule on the West Bank and in Gaza.
   Both are stopgap measures. They beg the question whether Bush
will pursue the Reagan policy of trying to topple the Marxist
government in Nicaragua or is willing to live with it, and whether
he will try to force Israel and the Arabs into a lasting agreement.
   The Contra aid package, the product of a March 24 agreement
between the administration and the Democratic-led Congress, is good
only until the Fall. Nicaragua could make enough political
concessions by then to get Uncle Sam off its back _ and spare Bush
a difficult decision.
   Less likely is that Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's
election plan will induce the Palestinians and their supporters to
adopt a gradual and peaceful approach to settling the West Bank and
Gaza problem. Bush has already declared himself opposed to Israeli
``occupation'' of sovereignty over the territories.
   This could be a sign that he intends to pressure Israel to yield
control. But there is no hint of a U.S. peace plan, of shuttle
diplomacy by Secretary of State James A. Baker III, or that Bush
will summon Arab and Israeli leaders to Camp David, as President
Jimmy Carter did in 1978 to help squeeze out the peace treaty
between Israel and Egypt a year later.
   Bush and Baker evidently are committed to the proposition that
direct negotiations between Israel and Palestinians offer the best
hope for an agreement that would hold up. High-profile U.S.
diplomacy is not part of the picture at this point.
   In the important sphere of U.S.-Soviet relations, Gorbachev's
troop and missile reduction initiatives are receiving a skeptical
response. But NATO and the Warsaw Pact opened negotiations in
Vienna in March to trim tank and artillery units, and Baker
probably will set a date for the resumption of U.S.-Soviet talks on
long-range nuclear weapons when he goes to Moscow May 11.
   Gorbachev has the implicit support of the U.S. administration as
he consolidates his powers.
   This week, for instance, the State Department described his
purge of 74 Central Committee voting members and the promotion of
several proteges as dramatic. It expressed hope that ``whatever
changes occur, their effect is to strengthen and promote the reform
process in the Soviet Union toward greater democratization and
openness.''
   Bush, meanwhile, is encouraging reform in Poland with a series
of moves that could ease the Soviet ally's $39 billion foreign
debt. `'Liberty is an idea whose time has come in Eastern Europe,''
he said in a speech last week.
   He probably will visit Poland and Hungary this summer to
maintain U.S. support for change.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Barry Schweid covers foreign affairs for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
