<FIRST>r w PM-BoarderBabies     04-28 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boarder Babies,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abandoned Babies Filling Hospitals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many babies born to mothers who use drugs are
becoming ``boarders'' who strain staffs and facilities in urban
hospitals after being abandoned by their parents, a hospital
director told Congress.
   ``The problem that my hospital and hospitals in cities around
the country are facing daily is caring for those newborn babies
abandoned by drug abusing mothers,'' said Haynes Rice, director of
Howard University Hospital.
   Rice on Thursday told the House Select Committee on Children,
Youth and Families that the overcrowding caused by these ``boarder
babies'' has become so acute one day he was unable to locate an
empty bed anywhere between Philadelphia and Richmond for an acutely
ill infant.
   Boarder babies are children who remain in hospitals after birth
even though they are medically ready for discharge, he said.
   The problem is being exacerbated in the nation's capital by the
rising cross-generational family use of crack cocaine, said Rice.
   ``Now we are seeing 28- and 35-year-old grandmothers who are
themselves substance abusers and who cannot readily step in to
provide the social support as in the past.''
   An internal study found the average stay for 27 of the 45 babies
being boarded at Howard between August and December 1988 was 42.3
days. The average expected hospital stay for a newborn is three
days.
   ``The longest-stay infant had been in the hospital for 245 days
at a cost in excess of $250,000,'' said Rice, noting the Medicaid
payment received by the hospital was set at $6,100 regardless of
the length of stay or extent of services the child received while
there.
   Rice recommended streamlining foster care and adoption
procedures to speed the placement of boarder babies into stable
homes.
   This is not a new phenomenon, he said, explaining that 20 years
ago ``when I worked in New York City, the public hospitals there
had about 200 babies on a daily basis who had been abandoned at the
hospitals by heroin addicted mothers.''
   Wendy Chavkin, a New York City doctor, said a recent report by
the city comptroller shows the problem has not abated, indicating
maternal drug use was the reason for the boarder status of 49
percent of the more than 300 children under age 2 in city hospitals.
   Chavkin said the lack of drug treatment facilities for women in
general and pregnant women specifically also contributes to the
problem.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
