<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0351EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TankerSpill-Mate     04-28 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill-Mate,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Mystery Man On The Bridge Could Be Star of NTSB Hearing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   He is the mystery man of the nation's
worst oil spill, the third mate who was on watch when the Exxon
Valdez ran aground and dumped more than 10 million gallons of crude
in Prince William Sound.
   Little has been seen of Gregory Cousins since the March 24
accident, and federal officials don't expect him to surface until
the May 16-19 hearings in Anchorage to assess what happened and how
to prevent a recurrence.
   Capt. Joseph Hazelwood, who the Coast Guard says was the only
person aboard authorized to navigate the tanker through the sound,
blamed his third mate when the Coast Guard radioed his ship an hour
after the wreck.
   ``Joe Hazelwood here,'' the skipper answered when Coast Guard
Cmdr. Steve McCall in Valdez asked for a damage report.
   ``A little problem here with the third mate, but we're working
our way off the reef,'' said Hazelwood, who tried to rock the ship
free before shutting down the engines and waiting for help.
   Cousins had signed on with Exxon as a third mate, although he
had obtained his second mate's certification Jan. 12.
   ``That's not unusual,'' said Coast Guard Lt. Cmdr. Gary Kaminski
in Washington, D.C. ``With fewer positions available, people set
sail at positions lower than their license.''
   A second mate is the navigator and is in charge of maps and
charts. The third mate is in charge of maintenance and the
inventory of firefighting equipment. They and the chief mate, who's
in charge of the cargo, alternate four-hour watches on the bridge.
   Hazelwood turned the 987-foot tanker and its 42 million gallons
of oil destined for Long Beach, Calif., over to Cousins sometime
after a state pilot with federal pilot authority left the ship at
Rocky Point.
   Bligh Reef was seven miles away.
   ``At that time the master (Hazelwood) was in the wheelhouse,''
said Coast Guard Cmdr. Darryle Waldron. ``The master had federal
pilotage (authority) for Prince William Sound through the entrance.
The mates didn't have the necessary endorsements on their
licenses.''
   The pilots used to navigate ships out of the sound to the Gulf
of Alaska until the 1980s when a smaller ship taking a pilot back
to Valdez capsized in rough seas. The pilot nearly died, and the
rules were eased.
   Cousins, reportedly a resident of Tampa, Fla., was licensed out
of New Orleans and obtained his third mate's license March 19,
1986. Coast Guard records in Washington, D.C., showed he had no
record of disciplinary action.
   Cousins is still employed by Exxon, said spokesman Joe Tucker,
but the oil company refused to say where he is working or living.
Hazelwood was dismissed after he tested at .06 on a blood-alcohol
test nine hours after the wreck. The legal limit on blood-alcohol
tests for ship captains is .04.
   Alan Pollock of the National Transportation Safety Board said he
doubted Hazelwood would attend the NTSB's hearing in Anchorage.
   ``If a witness is simply going to sit on the stand and take the
Fifth (Amendment right against self-incrimination) all day ... We'd
rather have people give us information. That looks like the case
with Hazelwood,'' Pollock said.
   Hazelwood faces three misdemeanor charges stemming from the
accident, including operating a vessel while under the influence.
   Cousins was a more likely participant in the NTSB hearing, said
Pollock. Other NTSB officials confirmed the agency has talked with
Cousins and hopes to have a longer interview before the May hearing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890428-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0418EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Tattoos     04-28 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tattoos,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Laser Erases Tattoos Without Scars or Pain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new laser technique erases tattoos but spares
the skin, providing the first way to get rid of battleships,
hearts, old lovers' names or other such decorations without causing
scars, researchers say.
   The treatment uses an intense beam of light called a ruby laser
to blast away the colors beneath the skin.
   ``I think this is the first truly non-scarring therapy for
tattoos,'' said Dr. R. Rox Anderson of Massachusetts General
Hospital.
   Dr. Charles Taylor, a member of Anderson's research team,
planned to present the results of the laser treatment today at a
meeting of the Society for Investigative Dermatology in Washington.
   Doctors said the laser is almost painless, too. It produces a
sensation something like a loosely snapped rubber band.
   Lasers are already widely used for removing tattoos, but current
models burn them off, leaving permanent scars. The new technique
also produces high heat, but its effects are much more selective.
   It uses brief, 100 million-watt flashes of red light, which is
absorbed by the tattoo pigment. The heat shatters the bits of
pigment imbedded in the skin as well as the cells that hold them.
But it does not harm blood vessels or ordinary cells.
   ``There is clearly a difference between this and other therapies
that are used,'' Anderson said.
   Anderson said the procedure could become the standard treatment
for removing tattoos after it is approved by the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration, perhaps within two years.
   Dr. Kenneth Arndt of Beth Israel Hospital in Boston agreed.
   ``When the ruby laser works well, which looks to be a good deal
of the time, the skin remains normal,'' he said. ``That's
extraordinary, and it's bringing fancy technology to the level
where it can be useful for patient care.''
   Anderson said that in testing so far on 13 people, the laser
completely erased about half of the tattoos and faded the rest.
   However, he said the initial study was intended to find the
proper intensity of laser light, and some patients received
relatively low doses. Results may be better when higher levels are
used routinely.
   Of 41 tatoos treated, only one small patch of skin measuring
less than a square inch became scarred.
   The laser will not remove red pigment because it does not absorb
the red light. Amateur tattoos come off more easily than
professionally drawn tattoos, which contain more color.
   Anderson said that after his team began experimenting with the
ruby laser, they discovered that a group of doctors in Glasgow,
Scotland, had worked on the same approach and published preliminary
results in a British journal.
   Unless burned or removed surgically, tattoos are permanent. The
Boston researchers said that most of the people they have treated
so far got them while drunk.
   One woman had her boyfriend's initials tattooed when she was a
teen-ager. The next day she regretted it, and always kept the
tattoo covered with a bandage.
   Tattoos are drawn by puncturing the skin, usually with needles,
and inserting pigment that remains after the wound heals over.
   The variety of laser used in the new treatment was once widely
tested for medical purposes, but none of them seemed to work and it
was abandoned. The ruby laser is used largely for welding.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890428-0032 </DOCNO>
