<HEAD>Pope Departs For Madagascar To Begin 9-Day African Tour</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II left Friday on his fifth African
tour for Madagascar, where violent protests against the government
of President Didier Ratsiraka the last week have left five people
dead.
   The pontiff's special Alitalia Boeing 747 left Rome's Leonardo
da Vinci Airport at 8 a.m. for a nine-hour flight to Madagascar's
capital, Antananarivo.
   It is the first stop on a nine-day trip that also will take the
pope to the French island of Reunion in the Indian Ocean, and to
Zambia and Malawi. It is the 41st foreign pilgrimage of John Paul's
10{-year papacy.
   In all, the pope will deliver 36 speeches and travel 13,500
miles during his trip. He is scheduled to return to Rome on May 6.
   Africa is the continent where Roman Catholicism is growing
fastest. The Vatican says it has 75 million followers in Africa.
