<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     04-28 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>New AIDS Drug to be Tested in Humans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration is allowing a
potentially promising new AIDS drug to be tested on people infected
with the deadly virus.
   Researchers say the drug, known as GLQ223, is unique because it
appears to kill only those immune system cells that are infected
with the AIDS virus, leaving non-infected cells alone. However,
they caution the drug so far has been tested only in the laboratory
and has not been used on AIDS patients.
   Dr. Michael McGrath of the University of California in San
Francisco and San Francisco General Hospital led a team of
scientists from UCSF, the Chinese University of Hong Kong and
Genelabs of Redwood City, Calif., that developed GLQ223.
   ``I'm very optimistic because of the test tube results, but
there's always the possibility it could have unpredictable side
effects or when given to humans the drug may not be able to get to
all the infected cells,'' McGrath said of Thursday's announcement.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Brady Rejects Proposal to Reduce Medicare Catastrophic Surtax</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady is rejecting
a proposal to reduce Medicare ``catastrophic'' health insurance
premiums that congressional analysts expect to generate a bigger
surplus than is needed.
   Brady, in a letter to Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas that was
released Thursday, said the insurance program ``is literally in its
first few months of life'' and the administration wants to be sure
it is not left with insufficient reserves.
   The new insurance program, approved by Congress last year,
provides extended coverage for the costs of hospital and medical
care and drug benefits. It is financed through a surtax paid by
Social Security recipients.
   Bentsen, chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, last week
said he would move to reduce the surtax if the Treasury Department
agreed with new congressional estimates that the surtax will yield
a $9.1 billion surplus over a five-year period.
   Brady, however, said the administration expects the premiums to
yield ``contingency reserves'' of $6.2 billion and finds no reason
to revise that estimate or to allow for a smaller surplus.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Coach Says He Met With Alleged Drug Dealer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgetown University basketball coach John
Thompson revealed he met with an alleged drug kingpin and asked him
to steer clear of his players after learning that several members
of his team were frequenting a bar where drug trafficking is common.
   Thompson, appearing on an ABC-TV program on the violent drug
problem in Washington, said Thursday he spoke with 24-year-old
Rayful Edmond III, after learning that Georgetown players were
socializing at Chapter III, a nightclub where both college students
and alleged drug dealers regularly gather.
   Thompson describes the result as ``almost like a tacit
agreement: `Do me a favor: If you see anything going on out there,
use whatever resources you have to stop it from happening.'''
   Thompson, who coached the U.S. basketball team in the 1988
Olympics in Seoul, said he met with Edmond in February. On April
15, Edmond and 15 others were arrested and charged with running a
massive transcontinental cocaine ring.
