<FIRST>r a PM-TechnoBandit     04-28 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Techno Bandit,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Techno-Bandit Sentenced To 30 Months For Escape Attempt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A West German described by U.S.
authorities as ``the world's top techno-bandit'' was sentenced to
an additional 2{ years in prison and fined $40,000 for a daring
helicopter prison escape attempt.
   U.S. District Judge William Stafford sentenced Werner
Bruchhausen, 49, to 30-month concurrent sentences Thursday on each
of two counts of conspiracy to escape. The term will be tacked onto
a 15-year term Bruchhausen received in 1987 for sales of classified
technology to Soviet bloc countries.
   Stafford criticized letters he got on behalf of Bruchhausen
which were critical of the U.S. judicial system, saying, ``I
thought I ought to let you know this system has provided you with a
fair trial.''
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Steve Dobson urged the judge to exceed
sentencing guidelines, which called for a maximum prison term of 30
months. He discounted the defense contention that Bruchhausen was
entrapped.
   ``He was the person who initiated the plan,'' said Dobson.
   Defense attorney Bruce Culpepper, who asked the judge to stay
within the guidelines, said no decision had been made on an appeal.
   Authorities foiled Bruchhausen's escape by setting up a U.S.
Customs helicopter as the escape aircraft. He had reportedly
offered to pay up to $250,000 for assistance.
   Bruchhausen was taken into custody by an FBI agent and four
prison officers as he started toward the aircraft that had swooped
down over the softball field in the prison recreation yard last
August. He was later transferred to the federal penitentiary in
Atlanta.
   The West German citizen began serving his sentence at the
Tallahassee prison in May 1987.
   Bruchhausen and three others were indicted in August 1981 in Los
Angeles on charges of conspiracy and violating the Export
Administration Act, the Arms Export and Control Act and federal
income tax laws.
   The 60-count indictment charged that from January 1977 through
June 5, 1980, Bruchhausen and the others ``conspired to export from
the United States various high technology commodities'' to East
Germany and elsewhere without export licenses from the State and
Commerce departments.
   At that time, U.S. Customs Commissioner William von Rabb called
Bruchhausen ``one of the world's top techno-bandits.''
   He was arrested on May 8, 1985, in London, extradited the
following year and convicted of wire fraud in 1987.
   Bruchhausen allegedly smuggled a microwave receiver system,
semiconductor manufacturing equipment, a computer system and other
military and scientific items to the Soviet bloc through dummy
corporations in California and West Germany.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
