<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     04-28 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up As Nikkei Gains 212 Points To Hit High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose against the Japanese yen
Friday, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange hit yet
another high.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
65.90 points for a 33,500.83-point record close Thursday, gained
another 212.52 points, or 0.63 percent, to finish the week at
33,713.35.
   The dollar closed at 132.49 yen, up 0.44 yen from the previous
day's close of 132.05 yen. It started at 132.20 yen and ranged from
132.20 to 132.60 yen.
   Currency dealers said the dollar's surge came as concern briefly
subsided about an immediate increase in Japan's official discount
rate following the release of April's Tokyo-area consumer price
report.
   Consumer prices for April in Tokyo rose 2.6 percent from a year
earlier and 1.4 percent from the prior month, according to a
government report released Friday.
   ``The figures were largely within that of an anticipated range
... but many investors were still taking a cautious position on a
possible interest rate hike,'' said a dealer with the Bank of
Tokyo, who spoke anonymously.
   Finance Minister Tatsuo Murayama told a news conference Friday
that the nation's central bank is worried about price stability and
high oil prices. But the tone of his remarks also suggested there
will not be an immediate change in monetary policy based on the
price data.
   Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita said Thursday the central
bank would act swiftly, if necessary, to sustain price stability.
   The major national newspaper Mainichi Shimbun reported Friday
that the Bank of Japan is likely to hike its official interest
rate, now standing at a historic low of 2.5 percent, to 3.0 percent
as early as mid-May to alleviate inflationary pressure.
   On the stock exchange, the market's main barometer started on a
strong note following a 29.88-point rise in the Dow Jones
Industrial Average in New York overnight, dealers said.
   They said the stock market also welcomed the fact that April's
Tokyo-area consumer index was well below an originally expected
increase of 3-3.5 percent, helping to temporarily ease the
inflationary concern.
</TEXT>
