<DOCNO> AP890428-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0629EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AccidentAnniversary     04-28 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Accident Anniversary,0676</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aloha Airlines Accident Changed Industry Philosophy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the year since the roof ripped off an Aloha
Airlines jet and a flight attendant plunged to her death,
widespread changes have occurred in the industry that once believed
a maintained aircraft could fly forever.
   The Boeing 737 involved had rolled off the assembly line in 1969
and had 89,000 cycles _ takeoffs and landings _ in a corrosive
salt-air environment.
   The industry and the Federal Aviation Administration had
believed that metal fatigue in older airplanes, especially cracking
around rivets and corrosion, could be discovered in regular visual
inspections.
   However, in the Aloha case, investigators think dozens of minute
cracks _ invisible to the human eye _ connected and allowed a piece
of fuselage to blow out in an explosive decompression at 24,000
feet, followed by a whole section of the plane.
   The images from the April 28, 1988, accident were unforgettable:
the jet, with a 18-foot chunk of its upper fuselage gone, sitting
on the runway of Kahului Airport on the Hawaiian Island of Maui;
stunned passengers milling around while flight attendants tried to
comfort them; passengers shaking the hands of the pilot and
co-pilot who somehow landed the crippled jet safely.
   Officials were stunned there was only one fatality, although 61
passengers were injured.
   Quickly the headlines changed from ``Terror in Paradise,'' to
``Miracle Over Maui.'' Experts marveled at the skill of the
captain, Robert Schornstheimer, and the co-pilot, Madeline ``Mimi''
Tompkins, since promoted to captain, and praised them for averting
a much worse disaster. And they wondered, of course, what could
cause the 19-year-old jet to break apart.
   ``I saw the original hole, the smaller one before the whole
thing ripped open,'' said passenger Arlo Clippinger, 51, of Tucson,
Ariz. ``I still dream about that hole.''
   After the accident, a task force of aviation industry and
government safety experts recommended mandatory structural
overhauls on older airliners. The average age of the nearly 3,000
U.S. airliners is about 13 years, with many planes more than 15
years old.
   The National Transportation Safety Board report on the
``in-flight roof separation'' is not due until next month.
   ``The accident caused everyone to question the industry folklore
that a plane could fly forever,'' said A. Maurice Myers, president
of Aloha Airlines.
   ``Now it's believed that airplanes can fly indefinitely with the
proper life-extending programs, but that's not just daily
maintenance, it's overall, complete structural inspections,'' he
said.
   Since the Aloha accident, nine people died Feb. 24 when the
cargo door and a chunk of fuselage tore off an United Airlines
Boeing 747 on a flight from Hawaii. Cargo door failure is suspected
to be the cause of that mishap.
   ``Those two accidents (United and Aloha) were similar only in
what you saw on TV, a jet with a hole,'' said FAA spokesman Fred
Farrar. ``The best poll of public confidence remains the fact that
we have something like 16,000 airline flights every day in the
country and they're pretty much full of passengers.''
   Meanwhile, Boeing Co. this week predicted record sales for 1989,
with Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Frank Shrontz saying
``concern about aging aircraft is bound to be a significant
factor'' in the company's sales outlook.
   Myers said that despite spending $60 million for two new 737s,
defending the company against 19 lawsuits stemming from the
accident and spending millions to refurbish older aircraft, the
company turned a $5.8 million profit in 1988, up $200,000 from the
previous year's profit.
   The jet involved in the accident was scrapped, and the airline
no longer lists a Flight 243 in its schedule.
   The airline's insurance company is paying settlements to those
who did not sue, Myers said, but declined to release the average
payment.
   ``In 43 years of flying we've had one accident,'' Myers said.
``It happened to be one that affected the whole industry and caused
widespread changes.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890428-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0629EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DesegLawsuit     04-28 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deseg Lawsuit,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawsuit Seeks Desegregation of City, Suburban Schools</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER VILES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Civil rights leaders are suing the state
of Connecticut contending its schools make it impossible for poor,
minority students to get the same education as their white,
suburban counterparts.
   The desegregation lawsuit was filed Thursday in Hartford
Superior Court on behalf of a black Hartford fourth-grader and 16
other children and teen-agers, arguing that racial imbalance in
Hartford area schools violates the state constitution's guarantee
against racial discrimination.
   The lawsuit contends that black and Hispanic inner-city children
and white suburban children are all suffering under greater
Hartford's racially divided school systems.
   ``Black children going to black schools and white children going
to white schools is inherently unequal,'' said Wesley Horton, one
of 10 lawyers who will argue the case. ``It's got to be stopped.''
   The lead plaintiff in the lawsuit, 10-year-old Milo Sheff,
attends Hartford's Annie Fisher School, where 99 percent of the
students are black or Hispanic.
   Six of the 17 plaintiffs in the lawsuit are white, including two
children from West Hartford, an affluent suburb where schools are
84 percent white. In Hartford, where the other 15 plaintiffs live,
schools are 91 percent black or Hispanic.
   The lawsuit contends that the concentration of poor children,
children from one-parent families, and non-English speaking
children places severe burdens on the Hartford school system,
making it unable to provide education comparable to that offered in
nearby suburbs.
   The lawsuit also alleges that white children in suburban school
districts surrounding Hartford ``are deprived of the opportunity to
associate with, and learn from, the minority children attending
school within the Hartford school district.''
   The lawsuit does not ask for any specific remedy to desegregate
the schools, and the lawyers who will argue the case seemed
hesitant to suggest one.
   ``What we envision is a system whereby Puerto Ricans and blacks
and whites are educated together,'' said William Olds, executive
director of the Connecticut Civil Liberties Union, which is
providing two lawyers to the plaintiffs.
   A court-ordered solution could focus on redrawing school
district boundaries, busing students from one district to another,
or creating interdistrict ``magnet'' schools.
   State Education Commissioner Gerald H. Tirozzi, one of 10 state
officials named as defendants, has proposed voluntary, incremental
steps such as magnet schools to desegregate Connecticut schools.
But the Legislature has not acted on Tirozzi's suggestions, and
civil rights leaders maintain the Legislature won't deal with the
issue without pressure from the courts.
   Also named as defendants are Gov. William A. O'Neill, the six
current members of the state Board of Education, state Treasurer
Francisco L. Borges _ the state's highest black official _ and
state Comptroller J. Edward Caldwell.
   O'Neill's legal advisor, Howard G. Rifkin, said Thursday the
governor would have no comment on the lawsuit until he has had a
chance to review it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890428-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0535EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Quayle 1stLd-Writethru a0457 04-28 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0457,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush and Quayle Discuss Circumstances for Possible Transfer of Power</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS one graf after 6th graf pvs, bgng He said, with Quayle
no comment; SUBS last 3 grafs, bgng Fitzwater said, to include source denying
report on Marilyn Quayle; no pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush and Vice President Dan Quayle
held a meeting last week to discuss how to handle a transfer of
presidential power if Bush were incapacitated, White House press
secretary Marlin Fitzwater says.
   Fitzwater called the unannounced session April 18 ``just a
routine meeting, just a process meeting, how the process would
work.''
   The 25th Amendment to the Constitution prescribes circumstances
under which the vice president would assume power from the
president, and Bush temporarily took over from former President
Ronald Reagan when he had colon cancer surgery on July 13, 1985.
   Fitzwater said Thursday that ``precise guidelines'' were adopted
during the Reagan administration for implementing the Amendment.
   ``I don't know that there's anything (more) to decide,'' he
said. ``It's all very routine. The processes were worked out in the
last administration.''
   He said he did not recall that that process had ever been made
public. On the other hand, Fitzwater said he recalled talking about
the process when Reagan was undergoing periodic cancer checkups.
   Quayle, who was traveling in Australia, said of the report
today, ``I have absolutely no comment on that. I have no comment.''
   The Washington Post, quoting an anonymous White House source,
reported today that the meeting was kept secret because of
sensitivity to previous Democratic charges that Quayle lacked
experience to handle the job of president.
   Fitzwater said he did not know who participated in the meeting
but said it was a private session.
   The Post reported that Barbara Bush and Marilyn Quayle as well
as White House physician Burton Lee II and White House counsel C.
Boyden Gray also attended the meeting. According to the Post,
Quayle remained silent while his wife and the Bushes questioned the
White House staff members on the issue.
   A source familiar with the meeting who spoke on condition of
anonymity told The Associated Press, however, that Mrs. Quayle did
not attend the session.
   During the meeting, it was determined that the 25th Amendment
would be invoked under certain circumstances but not in others, but
the details of what was decided could not be immediately
determined, the Post said.
</TEXT>
