<DOCNO> AP890428-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0553EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Derailment     04-28 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Derailment,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigator: Dispatcher's Mistake Caused Derailment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mistake by a CSX Corp. dispatcher with 23
years experience caused the April 6 derailment of Amtrak's Silver
Star near Emporia, a federal investigator said.
   Gordon J. Inglis of the National Transportation Safety Board
said Thursday that the dispatcher, based at CSX's new central
dispatch center in Jacksonville, Fla., had radioed the engineer
that the Silver Star would be switching tracks in Emporia _ four
miles beyond the point where the switch had been set. Emporia is
about 50 miles south of Richmond.
   The engineer failed to slow for the switch because he didn't
expect it so soon, Inglis said.
   The train plowed into the switch at its normal cruising speed of
59 mph instead of the recommended crossover speed of 15 mph.
   Both engines and the first eight cars of the 18-car train jumped
the track, causing minor injuries to 34 of the train's 519
passengers and $1.8 million in damage.
   Inglis said tests found no evidence of drug or alcohol use by
anyone involved in the train's routing or operation.
   He said the dispatcher had a perfect work record before the
derailment. The man is still at his post and likely will keep his
job, the investigator said.
   The safety board's final report on the accident, due in June,
probably will recommend changes in operating procedures at the
dispatch center, Inglis said.
   CSX has about 19,000 miles of track in 20 states plus
Washington, D.C., and Ontario, Canada.
</TEXT>
