<FIRST>r a PM-WashingtonBicentennial     04-28 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington Bicentennial,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Plans Big Party For 200th Anniversary Of Washington's Inauguration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Red, white and blue will be the rage this
weekend as the 200th anniversary of George Washington's
inauguration is celebrated with a flotilla of ships, a fireworks
display and a parade led by President Bush.
   Washington's swearing-in as the first president was watched by
some 20,000, just 10,000 fewer than the city's population in 1789.
More than 2 million are expected to gather to watch the
bicentennial events.
   The highlight will be the inaugural commemoration at Federal
Hall on Sunday, marking the moment when Washington put his hand to
the Bible and swore to ``faithfully execute the office of president
of the United States.''
   Bush will speak at the ceremony _ which falls on his 101st day
in office. And a white-haired Philadelphian, William Sommerfield,
will play the part of Washington and deliver part of the first
president's inaugural address.
   The city kicks off the festivities Saturday with a flotilla in
New York Harbor. Thirteen U.S. Navy and Coast Guard ships
representing the original states will be joined by 50 commercial
and civilian vessels coming down the Hudson River.
   At night, a fireworks spectacular called ``Hail to the Chief,''
narrated by Walter Cronkite, will emblazon the sky. Scenes of
pyrotechnics will tell the history of the presidency.
   Prior to Sunday's commemoration, Bush and other dignitaries will
attend an ecumenical service at St. Paul's Chapel, where Washington
prayed after his inauguration.
   After the ceremony, Bush will lead a parade that will include
the official bands of the Army, Navy, Marines and Air Force.
</TEXT>
