<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Bombs     04-28 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa-Bombs,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Limpet Mines Explode In Johannesburg, No One Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two limpet mines exploded in
trash cans in downtown Johannesburg early today, shattering store
windows but causing no injuries, police said.
   The first explosion shortly after noon blew up a trash bin at
the entrance of a local department store. It occurred across from a
building housing several American and British news organizations,
including The Associated Press, CBS-TV, The New York Times and The
Times of London.
   The second explosion occurred two hours later in front of a
furnishing store seven blocks away.
   Bombings had dropped off sharply since a protest campaign last
October against the racially separate nationwide municipal
elections. While there had been no bombs in Johannesburg in months,
several were reported in the Cape area and in the Xhosa tribal
homelands of Ciskei and Transkei. Sixteen people have been injured
by about 20 bombs this year.
   Police named no suspect for today's bombings, although they
usually blame the outlawed African National Congress, the largest
guerrilla organization waging a sabotage campaign to end apartheid
and rule by a white-dominated government.
   The ANC seldom comments on individual bombings, but they
sometimes occur after an event considered significant to the
organization. Three ANC guerrillas were sentenced to death
Thursday, and a fourth received a 25-year prison sentence in
connection with four killings and two bombings that injured 17
people in 1986. The trial was in Delmas, a farm town northeast of
Johannesburg.
</TEXT>
