<HEAD>Man Pleads Quilty But Mentally Ill In School Slayings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM STRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENWOOD, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge must now decide the fate of a man
after accepting his plea of guilty but mentally ill in the killings
of two 8-year-olds during a shooting at an elementary school last
fall.
   James Wilson, depicted as a man plagued by imaginary voices and
obsessed with violence, also was found guilty but mentally ill
Thursday of wounding seven other children and two teachers at
Greenwood's Oakland Elementary School.
   Wilson walked into the school on Sept. 26, 1988, and opened fire
with a handgun in a cafeteria and classroom.
   During a hearing after the judge accepted the pleas, prosecutors
asked that Wilson be sentenced to the electric chair, and the
defense asked for life in prison with proper psychiatric care.
   Circuit Judge James Moore delayed sentencing Wilson until May 9.
   Moore accepted the pleas from Wilson, 20, after 3{ days of
testimony from witnesses to the shooting and from psychiatrists who
had examined him. Earlier this week, Moore found Wilson competent
to stand trial.
   Wilson, who has a history of mental illness, offered a plea of
guilty but mentally ill to the charges on Monday. But Moore refused
to immediately accept the pleas, saying he wanted to hear testimony
on the defendant's state of mind.
   Psychiatrists testified that Wilson was a man obsessed by the
film, ``Psycho,'' which Wilson claimed to have seen 500 times,
fascinated by mass murderers and how they carried out their crimes,
and plagued by the voice of his dead grandfather.
   Psychiatrists called by the defense this week testified that
Wilson suffered from a borderline personality disorder, which
involves a potential for violence, low self-esteem, paranoia,
inability to develop interpersonal relationships and suicidal
tendencies.
   Prosecutors tried to dispel testimony that supported Wilson's
contention he was mentally ill at the time of the shootings in an
effort to send the case to a jury trial.
