<HEAD>Strong Quake Jolts Greece, No Damage Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VOLOS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake jolted central Greece
today but no damage or injuries were reported.
   The Athens Seismological Institute said the quake, which
occurred at 7:02 a.m., measured 5.0 on the Richter scale and was
centered in the Aegean Sea, about 85 miles north of the capital.
   ``We felt the quake but we had no reports of damage or
injuries,'' said a police officer in the central Greek port of
Volos.
   The officer, who spoke on condition of anonymity in accordance
with Greek practice, said, ``We have many Easter visitors here and
at the nearby islands and fortunately there was no panic.''
   More than 1 million Athenians have left the capital to spend the
weekend of the Greek Orthodox Easter in the countryside, police
said.
   A quake measuring 5.0 can cause considerable damage if its
epicenter is in a populated area. The Richter scale is a gauge of
the energy released by an earthquake, as measured by the ground
motion recorded on a seismograph. Every increase of one number
means the ground motion is 10 times greater.
