<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0559EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Australia-Bounty     04-28 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Australia-Bounty,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bounty Mutiny Re-enacted In South Seas On 200th Anniversary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD BILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of history's most notorious naval
revolts, the mutiny on the Bounty, was re-enacted today in the
South Seas by descendants of Capt. William Bligh and his rebellious
first officer, Fletcher Christian.
   ``It was a wonderful moment, the ghosts of Bligh and Christian
were with us today,'' said Capt. Ronald Bligh-Ware, whose
great-great-great-grandfather was set adrift off the Pacific island
nation of Tonga on April 28, 1789.
   ``Today was probably the most jovial mutiny in history,'' the
62-year-old Bligh-Ware added. ``We popped champagne corks and it
was fun.''
   Bligh-Ware's had only to circumnavigate his ship _ a replica of
the Bounty built from British admiralty charts _ in a long boat.
   His famous ancestor, forced from his ship, was joined by 18
loyal crewmen who sailed a 23-foot open boat about 4,200 miles in
47 days to Timor, Indonesia, in what is still regarded as a
remarkable feat.
   Christian sailed the Bounty back to Tahiti and then spent months
searching the South Pacific for a haven, knowing he would be hanged
if caught. The mutineers eventually settled on Pitcairn Island, one
of the world's most remote settlements.
   There they burned the ship. Their descendants moved to Norfolk
Island, off the east coast of Australia, in the 1850s. Some later
returned to Pitcairn and the populations of both islands to this
day are predominantly of mutineer ancestry.
   Ken Rosebery, owner of the replica Bounty, organized the
re-enactment about 2,100 miles east of Australia. He said that six
of the 36 passengers and crew were direct descendants of the
mutineers.
   The passengers paid an average of $4,800 for the month-long
voyage from Sydney to Tahiti and Tonga. They adopted the names of
mutineers for the re-enactment.
   The replica ship, built in New Zealand in 1979, was used in the
1984 movie ``The Bounty,'' starring Australian actor Mel Gibson and
Britain's Anthony Hopkins.
   ``Bligh-Ware, like his father and grandfather, is a qualified
captain in the Australian merchant navy,'' said Rosebery. ``He also
bears a remarkable resemblance to the 18th century Bligh while
Fletcher Christian's great-great-great-grandson, Gerald Christian,
has the rank of lieutenant commander in the Australian Navy. The
sea seems to run in their families' blood.''
   Commemorative stamps that went on sale today in Tonga depict
Bligh, the Bounty, a navigational compass he used and the small
boat on which Bligh and his men were abandoned.
   In London, where Bligh died, the British navy captain's
reputation is being reassessed. Long regarded as the villain of the
mutiny, he now has almost heroic stature.
   ``The old view of Bligh as a bully is largely legend and I'm
afraid that Hollywood, Charles Laughton, Trevor Howard, Clark Gable
and Marlon Brando have a lot to do with it,'' said Baron Terence
Lewin, a retired British Navy admiral.
   The 68-year-old admiral spoke to The Associated Press in London
at the opening of an exhibition marking the 200th anniversary of
the mutiny.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890428-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0612EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RitualSlayings-Extortion     04-28 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ritual Slayings-Extortion,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jail Inmates, Others Arrested For Extortion Attempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALVESTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two inmates and three other people tried
to extort $10,000 from the parents of a college student whose
mutilated body later was found in a mass grave in Mexico,
authorities said.
   The Galveston County Jail inmates were arrested Thursday and
accused of using jail telephones to call Mark Kilroy's parents in
nearby Santa Fe, Texas, where they were awaiting word on the
whereabouts of their son, who vanished in Matamoros, Mexico.
   Santa Fe Police Chief Mike Barry said a caller vowed to cut off
the missing student's fingers and mail them to the family if police
arrested or followed people to whom the Kilroys delivered ransom
money.
   The body of the University of Texas junior was found in a
shallow grave near Matamoros, Mexico, on April 11, one week after
the extortion attempt allegedly began. The body had been mutilated
in a human sacrifice ritual by Mexican drug smugglers, police said.
   Police said the inmates and the other three people were not
believed to be involved with the cult, but had heard Kilroy was
missing and were trying to cash in on it. The inmates were being
held on burglary charges at the time of the alleged extortion plot,
officers said.
   ``We were absolutely shocked that people who are in prison for a
good reason are able to call out and terrorize innocent people,''
said Helen Kilroy. ``We were really shocked that people can be
terrorized from inside our jails.''
   The other three people also were arrested, and all five were
charged with attempted robbery and ordered held in lieu of $20,000
bail.
   Kilroy's mother apparently tried to pay the initial $2,000 the
group sought, but the payoff was not made, Barry said.
   Galveston Deputy Gean Leonard said the inmates had telephones in
their cells to be used to contact family members or their
attorneys. The telephones allow the inmate to make collect calls
only, he said.
</TEXT>
