<FIRST>r a PM-BushGraded     04-28 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush Graded,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poll Gives President Bush A `C' Grade For First 100 Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If the White House can be compared to a
schoolhouse, President Bush earned a ``C'' during his first 100
days, according to a poll published today.
   Bush's predecessor, President Reagan, got a ``B'' in a similar
poll the Los Angeles Times conducted after his first 100 days in
office.
   However, the newspaper noted Reagan's popularity was bolstered
by an assassination attempt 70 days after he entered the Oval
Office.
   The poll also found that 47 percent of those interviewed
``approve of the way George Bush is handling his job as
president.'' Eighteen percent said they disapprove, and 35 percent
said they have no opinion.
   The newspaper said that at the same juncture in Reagan's
presidency, 80 percent of those surveyed approved of the former
president's job performance.
   When people were asked, ``What kind of a grade would you give
President Bush?'' the result was a ``C'' average.
   The survey, conducted by Times pollster I.A. Lewis, interviewed
a random sample of 2,160 people nationwide for four days, ending
last Tuesday. The newspaper said the margin of error was 3
percentage points in either direction.
   Sixty-seven percent of those polled have a positive impression
of Bush, 20 percent unfavorable and 13 percent unsure. One hundred
days into Reagan's first term in 1981, 83 percent of those surveyed
said they had an overall positive impression of him.
   The poll found that 52 percent of those surveyed disapproved of
Bush's handling of the Alaskan oil spill, 25 percent voiced
approval and the remainder were unsure.
   On other issues, 34 percent approved of Bush's steps to control
semiautomatic weapons, and 26 percent disapproved; 24 percent
approved of his handling of the savings and loan crisis, and 27
percent disapproved.
   The total added up to more than 100 percent because of multiple
responses.
</TEXT>
