<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia-China     04-28 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia-China,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Renew Pledge To Halt Aid To Rebels In Cambodia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Chinese official has renewed
pledges to halt military aid to guerrillas in Cambodia after the
total pullout of Vietnamese troops, Vietnam's foreign minister said
today.
   Meanwhile, exiled Cambodian resistance leader Prince Norodom
Sihanouk today rejected proposals for general elections following
the Sept. 30 withdrawal of the estimated 50,000-70,000 Vietnamese
troops from his country as ``illegal and absolutely unacceptable.''
   Sihanouk, in a written statement, said Hanoi's plan to have all
troops leave Cambodia by the end of September was a ``farce,''
because the Vietnamese-backed government of Premier Hun Sen remains
in power.
   Vietnamese forces invaded Cambodia in late 1978, ousting the
pro-Chinese Khmer Rouge regime that massacred hundreds of thousands
of Cambodians. Sihanouk, toppled from power in a 1970 coup, now
heads a coalition of three resistance groups that includes the
Khmer Rouge.
   Hun Sen's government has reportedly said it will hold general
elections within three months after the Vietnamese withdrawal.
   Sihanouk, who will meet Hun Sen in Jakarta May 2-3, discounted
the validity of any the elections.
   Hun Sen's government is ``nothing but a creation and creature of
Vietnam'' that ``has no right to to organize 'general elections,'''
he said.
   Sihanouk has said the Vietnamese withdrawal from Cambodia should
be supervised by the United Nations and that Hun Sen's government
should be dissolved prior to a general election, demands the
Cambodian premier has rejected.
   Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach said a Chinese vice foreign
minister made the pledge to halt military aid when he received a
copy of Vietnam's April 5 declaration of a total withdrawal. Thach
did not name the vice minister.
   ``They say they will stop once the Vietnamese are all withdrawn,
then they will stop their military aid,'' Thach said, adding he was
confident the pledge would be kept.
   Thach also said Vietnam's Deputy Foreign Minister Dinh Nho Liem
will go to Beijing for a second round of talks to try to resolve
differences over Cambodia. The talks are to be held May 8-10.
   The first round, held in January, was the first high-level
meeting between the two countries in more than nine years.
   Sino-Vietnamese relations have been strained since the 1970s
over border conflicts, Vietnam's ties with the Soviet Union, and
the Cambodian conflict. China is the main supplier of arms to a
guerrilla coalition fighting Vietnamese troops that invaded
Cambodia in late 1978.
   Thach spoke with reporters while attending a symposium in
Bangkok on turning Southeast Asia into a peaceful trading zone once
the conflict over Cambodia is resolved.
</TEXT>
