<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0644EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TankerSpill     04-28 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill,0640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Residents Don't Buy Exxon's Perception Of Cleanup Progress</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Tanker Spill-Mate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hours after Exxon showed off its
beach-cleaning effort to reporters, an oil company executive got an
earful when he tried to convince a fishing community that things
were looking better.
   Exxon got good reviews from a state geologist who watched Smith
Island being prepared for pregnant seals. But citizens of Cordova
let Exxon vice president Luyesse LeGrange know they don't see the
same progress.
   Michele O'Leary, one of 300 people at Cordova High School's gym
Thursday night to talk with LeGrange and others coordinating the
spill cleanup, disputed Exxon's claims about the number of skimmers
it operates.
   When Exxon said 19 were working in the sound, an overflight by
pilots for the Cordova United Fishermen Union found only three, she
said. Another occasion Exxon said it had 45 skimmers at work and
the union found only five.
   ``When can we expect to see the situation improve?'' asked
O'Leary, a member of the fishermen's union.
   ``I hardly think that's the case with all the equipment we have
out there,'' LeGrange said. ``I'd be most suprised if we have
equipment not working.''
   After a slow start with officials questioning each other, the
two-hour meeting began to get lively as the audience was allowed to
join the inquiry.
   Dennis Kelso, the state's chief environmentalist, said, ``There
has been a long pattern of claims by Exxon that don't bear out when
people go look at what's happening.''
   Kelso said he wasn't accusing LeGrange of lying, but that
``nobody believes'' the company's recent announcement that the
shoreline cleanup was ahead of schedule _ a mention that drew
laughs from the audience.
   ``I can tell you this is not a technical issue, not a biological
issue or an economic issue,'' Kelso continued. ``It's a moral
issue. Until Exxon steps up to their moral responsibility and stops
trying to shift blame to somebody else we're going to have problems
getting the kind of performance we all expect, whether it's in the
water or on the shore.''
   LeGrange denied there was any shifting of blame.
   ``But perhaps there's some sharing that needs to be
considered,'' he said. ``In the end, the truth will come out in
hearings, in court rooms where people are testifying under oath and
subject to cross examination.''
   National Transportation Safety Board hearings on the accident
and the emergency response have been set for May 16-19 in Anchorage.
   The tone of the town meeting was sharp but polite, a contrast to
the first meeting of Exxon officials and Cordova residents
dependent on fishing in Prince William Sound for their livelihood.
   At the earlier meeting, speakers were interrupted and there was
considerable shouting. The confrontation occurred shortly after the
Exxon Valdez wrecked on Bligh Reef and put more than 10 millions of
oil into the sound.
   The newly arrived USS Juneau sent its first crews to beaches on
Smith Island Thursday, with reporters on hand to watch water hoses
turned on the thick, black goop coating the rocks. Standing on the
beach was difficult.
   A shoreline three football fields long should take about three
days to clean, said Bert Hartley, a field manager for the cleanup.
But a worker struggling to maintain his footing on the beach's
oil-slickened rocks disagreed.
   It takes 10 or 15 minutes of high-pressure spraying to wash the
oil off a rubber work suit, said Harold Jones of Cordova, who
joined the cleanup crew for nearly $17 an hour after his work as a
fishermen was imperiled by the spill.
   ``And they say they're going to have this beach cleaned in three
days,'' Jones said. ``I'd call that extremely optimistic.''
</TEXT>
