<FIRST>r i PM-China-Workers     04-28 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Workers,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers Take Part in March, Support Students</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At the Xidan intersection near the city's center,
workers and unemployed youths broke through a line of about 200
police to help students maintain their pro-democracy march to
Tiananmen Square.
   ``We're opening a road for them,'' said one worker, carrying one
of his shoes, which had fallen off during the scuffle. ``The people
outnumber the students now.''
   Just west of the central square, hundreds of workers surrounded
the final line of security forces.
   ``Give way to the students!'' they shouted, their voices
bouncing off the red-brick walls of the Forbidden City.
   As the officers' ranks folded, the crowd broke out cheering.
   Defying threats that they might lose their jobs, thousands of
workers on Thursday took part in the 20-mile student march,
swelling the number of participants to 150,000.
   ``If China's children have the courage to come out, then its
fathers do, too,'' said a middle-aged electrician as he marched
with his colleagues. ``We're all taking sick days.''
   Scores of workers at the Beijing Light Automobile Co. handed
marchers dumplings and drinks. At a construction site nearby, work
stopped temporarily and workers waved from atop a 15-story building.
   Workers packed every corner, sitting atop buildings, billoards
and subway entrances. ``Long live students! Struggle till the
end!'' they chanted as the crowd moved by.
   The spontaneous action was an indication of widespread
opposition to the government. It also bore testimony to student
efforts earlier this week to bring their case to the people.
   ``The government should not stop people from speaking,'' said an
elderly dentist. ``I'm too old to push soldiers, but I can still
walk with them.''
   ``My factory may fire me but I don't care,'' said a foreman at a
bus plant, as he walked near the head of the protest. ``These kids
need help, and I'm here to provide it.''
   Student protests began last week following the April 15 death of
ousted Communist Party leader Hu Yaobang.
   Workers did not start appearing in the throngs until Saturday,
when 150,000 students and their supporters occupied Tiananmen
Square during Hu's funeral, calling for a free press and an end to
corruption in the Communist Party. But they did not start actively
participating until Thursday.
   Since the Saturday protest, bands of student activists on street
corners have given speeches and collected money for their protest.
   Workers said they agreed with student opposition to corruption,
nepotism and special privileges. Many senior officials in state-run
factories engage in corruption, making huge profits while their
employees live on fixed salaries.
   ``I read one of their leaflets and it made sense,'' said a young
driver. ``I know the party leader in my company is corrupt and the
students want a clean government.''
   Some workers said they would keep on supporting the students,
but it was unclear to what extent.
   ``Do you know what this is?'' one worker asked. ``It is China
standing up.''
</TEXT>
