<DOCNO> AP890428-0064 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0818EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon     04-28 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cease-Fire Takes Effect In Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven weeks of fierce fighting between
Christian and Moslem forces stopped today under a cease-fire called
by the Arab League.
   But an apparent disagreement over a key provision of the truce
regarding blockades of the country's ports threatened to undermine
the cease-fire.
   The latest round of fighting in Lebanon's 14-year civil war
began on March 8 and has killed 273 people and wounded 993,
according to police.
   The 22-member Arab League worked out the cease-fire plan
Thursday during a meeting in Tunisia and promised to dispatch Arab
observers to monitor the truce. Three previous cease-fires
sponsored by the league have collapsed.
   Earlier today, Beirut was shaken by several rocket and artillery
blasts as Christian army units under Gen. Michel Aoun battled with
Syrians and their Druse Moslem militia allies along the Green Line
that slices Beirut into Christian and Moslem sectors. No casualties
were reported, police said.
   Aoun, who heads a three-man Christian cabinet, said he welcomed
the ``lifting of blockades imposed on legal ports besieged by the
Syrian forces.''
   He said in a statement that maritime agencies should ``instruct
their ships to head to legal ports,'' apparently meaning that Aoun
still did not intend to end his blockade of illegal ports runs by
Moslem militias south of Beirut.
   The latest round of fighting began when Auon ordered his forces
to blockade those ports on March 6 in an effort to restore
government authority.
   The Druse Moslems responded by opening fire on the Beirut Port,
which Aoun's forces control. The Syrians then joined in shelling
and besieged Christian east Beirut and a 310-square-mile Christian
enclave to the north.
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, who heads a mainly Moslem
cabinet that is at odds with Aoun's government, also pledged to
observe the cease-fire.
   In Damascus, Syria, the official news agency SANA said the
government of President Hafez Assad was ``satisified with
resolutions announced by the Arab League on Lebanon.'' Syria
initially sent its 40,000 troops into Lebanon in 1976 on a
peacekeeping mandate from the Arab League.
   Aoun for weeks had rejected any settlement that did not include
a timetable for Syria's withdrawal from Lebanon.
   An aide, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Aoun agreed to
the Arab League cease-fire because it included the Arab observers,
whose presence could curb Syria's influence.
   ``This, of course, is not enough. However, it is a good step in
the march toward stripping Syria of its total control over
Lebanon,'' the spokesman said.
   The Beirut daily newspaper An-Nahar said the main achievement of
the Arab League decision is that Syria ``no longer is the sole
power in Lebanon.''
   The Arab League's final statement did not say how many observers
would be sent to Lebanon.
   Newspapers and Arab League sources have said a special committee
it formed in January proposed dispatching 312 observers under a
Kuwaiti commander. Kuwait heads the committee, which also includes
the foreign ministers of Jordan, Sudan, Tunis, Algeria and the
United Arab Emirates.
   Beirut International Airport, the country's only air transport
facility located on the southern edge of the Moslem sector, has
been closed since March 12, when it became a target of Christian
gunners.
   Aoun said today it could reopen. But a source close to Hoss said
the airport would remain closed until the Hoss cabinet decides to
reopen it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
