<DOCNO> AP890428-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0820EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-IranBooks     04-28 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran Books,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>McGraw-Hill Withdraws From Iran Book Fair</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McGraw-Hill Inc. says it will not participate in
a book fair next month in Iran because of the ``unfolding
politicalization'' of the event.
   The company announced its decision Thursday, one day after
another U.S. publisher that had planned to exhibit its books at the
fair, John Wiley &amp; Sons, a major producer of technical and
scientific books, announced it would pull out of the event.
   The two publishers were criticized by the Authors' Guild and by
the publisher of Salman Rushdie. Iran's leader, Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini, issued his death threat against the British author,
saying Rushdie's novel ``Satanic Verses'' is blasphemous.
   McGraw-Hill Inc. had planned to participate through its company
in England, McGraw-Hill Book Co. (UK) Ltd., but said in a statement
it had directed the subsidiary to ``withdraw completely'' from the
book fair.
   ``The unfolding politicalization of the book fair indicates
participation serves no constructive purpose,'' McGraw-Hill said.
   The biennial fair, scheduled for May 7-19 in Tehran, is
conducted by the Iran Ministry of Islamic Culture and generally
concentrates on scientific, medical and technical books.
   McGraw-Hill said its original decision to show its books in Iran
was based on the belief that ``there should be no sanctions on
knowledge'' and that ``some good would be served by making medical,
scientific and technical publications available to Iranian
students.''
   Neither McGraw-Hill nor Wiley had planned to send anyone to
Tehran.
</TEXT>
