<DOCNO> AP890428-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0822EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Hamadi     04-28 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hamadi,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Ask For Life Sentence for Hamadi</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors today demanded a life
sentence for Mohammed Ali Hamadi for his role in the hijacking of a
TWA plane and the slaying of a U.S. sailor.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, is charged with murder and air
piracy in the June 1985 hijacking. He admitted taking part in the
hijacking but denies killing Navy diver Robert Stethem.
   In closing arguments, chief prosecutor Achim Thiel said although
it could not be proved Hamadi pulled the trigger of the gun that
killed Stethem, ``it was a clear case, at a minimum, of felony
murder.''
   Peter Korneck, the assistant prosecutor in the trial, which
opened July 5, 1988, said: ``It was an attack against the
foundations of civilization.''
   ``There was no excuse for what happened. It cannot be justified
or excused,'' Korneck said, referring to the hijacking, Stethem's
murder and the brutal beatings of passengers.
   ``There was nothing in the evidence presented that would justify
a milder sentence,'' Korneck said.
   Thirty-nine Americans were held hostage 17 days after the jet
was commandeered while on a flight from Athens to Rome.
   A verdict is not expected until the second half of May. Life
imprisonment is the maximum penalty for murder and air piracy in
West Germany.
   Under West German law, an accomplice can be convicted of murder
even if he did not pull the trigger.
   ``It cannot be proved that Hamadi killed Stethem with his own
hands. But he is at a minimum equally guilty,'' Thiel said.
   Hamadi has blamed his fugitive accomplice, Hassan Ezzeddine, for
Stethem's murder. None of the witnesses who testified during the
trial, including dozens of former hostages and crew members of the
hijacked plane, saw the slaying.
   In their closing arguments, the prosecutors referred repeatedly
to the beatings of passengers described by witnesses.
   ``Hamadi beat Robert Stethem and Clinton Suggs (another U.S.
Navy diver) when they were totally defenseless,'' Thiel said.
``They were beaten without reason. He did it out of hate.''
   ``He beat Suggs until the skin on his back popped open,'' the
chief prosecutor said. ``The sadistic beating of Kurt Carlson
(another U.S. passenger) until he was unconscious was verified by
other witnesses. They believed that Carlson was dead.''
   ``We demand life imprisonment for murder and three cases of
grave bodily harm. The murder, the brutal beatings of Stethem,
Suggs and Carlson call for a life sentence,'' Korneck said.
   Both prosecutors described Hamadi as the leader of the
hijacking. Hamadi has denied being the leader.
   The prosecutors also argued that Hamadi should be treated and
sentenced as an adult. According to evidence obtained by the
prosecutors, Hamadi turned 21 the day before the hijacking began on
June 14, 1985.
   Hamadi has claimed that he is one or two years younger but has
not given a precise date of birth. Under West German law, the age
issue could influence the length of sentence.
   Stethem's parents, Richard and Patricia, and their other two
sons, Kenneth and Patrick, listened closely to the proceedings.
   Hamadi was arrested in January 1988 at Frankfurt's airport when
customs officials found explosives in his luggage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
