<FIRST>r a PM-ReprintingDecision     04-28 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Reprinting Decision,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judges Challenge Right Of Historians To Reprint Letters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a little-noticed decision, a federal appeals
court challenged the right of historians and biographers to reprint
letters, diaries and other unpublished primary source material
without permission.
   The ruling last week upheld on a technicality Henry Holt &amp; Co.'s
right to print an unflattering book about L. Ron Hubbard, the
founder of the Church of Scientology.
   A Danish corporation related to the church maintained that use
of a Hubbard letter constituted copyright infringement and sought
to bar the book, ``Bare-Faced Messiah'' by Russell Miller.
   The three-judge panel of the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
in New York ruled unanimously April 19 that the plaintiffs had sued
too late.
   The opinion signed by Judges Roger J. Miner and Frank X.
Altimari read: ``The District Court denied an injunction for
several reasons, one being the existence of special circumstances
in which free speech interests were said to outweigh the interests
of the copyright owner. We are not persuaded, however, that any
First Amendment concerns not accommodated by the Copyright Act are
implicated in that action.
   ``An author's expression of an idea, as distinguished from the
idea itself, is not considered subject to the public's `right to
know.'''
   Floyd Abrams, a lawyer who specializes in First Amendment cases,
said of the decision, ``What they do is reject totally the notion
that the First Amendment has any role to play in deciding whether
to issue an injunction in a copyright case.''
   In a separate opinion, Chief Judge James L. Oakes sided with the
trial judge, Pierre N. Laval, who also denied an injunction in U.S.
District Court in August but said the courts should consider the
free-speech rights of an author as well as the copyright interests
of the plaintiff, especially if the material quoted is essential to
demonstrate the point of a criticism.
   Oakes said his colleagues' opinion ``tends to cast in concrete''
the language Miner used to decide a similar case involving a
biography of author J.D. Salinger.
   In October 1987, the U.S. Supreme Court let stand the 2nd
Circuit's decision barring Random House from publishing the
biography by Ian Hamilton unless brief quotations from and
paraphrases of Salinger's letters were deleted.
   The appeals court ruled that the letters, which had been donated
to libraries and were open to scholarly perusal, still belonged to
the writer.
</TEXT>
