<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0827EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Poland     04-28 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Debuts On State Radio</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With a mixture of political commentary,
music and snippets of history, Solidarity debuted on state radio
today under an agreement that gives the trade union limited access
to mass media.
   ``We return to the air after long years,'' said one of the three
hosts, all Solidarity activists.
   The taped program began with religious and union songs
interspersed with fragments from historical events, including the
sound of cheers that greeted an April 17 court ruling making
Solidarity legal again after a seven-year ban.
   It also had man-in-the-street interviews about the return of
Solidarity and political commentary by opposition theorist Jacek
Kuron.
   It ended with an appeal by another opposition politician,
Wojciech Lamentowicz, asking people not to boycott June
parliamentary elections in which opposition candidates are to
participate for the first time since 1947.
   ``We will elect in June. Yes, elect,'' he said. ``For the first
time in many years we will elect and not just vote. So the
conclusion that a boycott serves any cause makes no sense at all.''
   Kuron discussed the opposition's program in the election
campaign.
   ``The goal ... is sovereignty of the nation, independence and
improvement of the republic,'' he said.
   He stressed that the opposition's agreement with authorities
that guarantees the Communist Party and its allies a 65 percent
majority in the Sejm, the existing parliament chamber, applied only
to this year's vote.
   ``The next elections should be free,'' he declared.
   The radio show was broadcast at 11 a.m. on Radio One, the main
channel of state radio. Another broadcast was planned Tuesday on
another channel and a third was scheduled for May 12.
   The melody at the opening of the program was composed especially
for Solidarity by well-known composer Wlodzimierz Korcz, an
announcer said.
   Access to the mass media was guaranteed the opposition under the
accord reached April 5 between communist authorities and the
Solidarity-led opposition. The agreement contains political and
social reforms aimed primarily at reviving the country's declining
economy.
   In addition to a half-hour weekly on radio, there is to be a
half-hour weekly television broadcast. Printing of the first
opposition mass-circulation daily newspaper is planned next week.
   All the opposition broadcasts and publications will be subject
to the same state censorship as the government media.
   Four months after martial law was imposed in December 1981 to
crush the union, the Solidarity underground began organizing brief
clandestine radio broadcasts from time to time at various FM
frequencies using hidden transmitters. Sometimes they even would
broadcast on state television during the news. However, the
broadcast range was limited, and officials soon learned how to jam
the transmissions with loud disco music.
</TEXT>
