<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--BloodBank     04-28 0139</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Blood Bank,0141</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Rules for Blood Bank in AIDS Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who was infected with the AIDS
virus through a blood transfusion will not get any damages from the
blood bank that handled it, a jury has ruled.
   The jury found Thursday that the Irwin Memorial Blood Bank was
not negligent in its method of screening donors before the spring
of 1985, when blood banks nationwide began using a test for the HIV
infection.
   Betty Dale, 59, underwent heart bypass surgery in February 1984
and received blood from Irwin Memorial. She was found to have AIDS
two years later.
   The verdict was returned following a three-week trial. It was
the first case tried against Irwin since the San Francisco blood
bank suffered the industry's first-ever loss in an AIDS case last
December.
</TEXT>
