<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica     04-28 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Banned From Chinese Restaurant In South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOKSBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The town council has banned
Chinese people from a Chinese restaurant leased by a Chinese woman
in the city's whites-only park, legislators said today.
   ``I feel like I'm on another planet. It's hard to believe,''
said Issy Kramer, a legislator who voted against the ban. The
council, dominated by the right-wing Conservative Party, passed the
law 10-7 Thursday night.
   Other non-whites had already been prohibited from entering the
resaurant.
   The Conservatives won control of this town east of Johannesburg
last year. They declared Boksburg Lake Park a whites-only area,
except for the black maintenance men who clean it. Other municipal
facilities also were declared off-limits to all but whites.
   The lease for the Golden Lake Restaurant, run by a Chinese
woman, is due to expire May 31, and an item on Thursday's meeting
agenda called for the lease to be granted to another Chinese woman,
S.Y. Yip.
   ``But a paragraph in the agreement says only white people may
enter the restaurant,'' said Kramer. ``I said, `I know you people
are forbidding blacks, coloreds and Indians from entering the park
and lake, but Chinese must be allowed to use the restaurant.'''
   The Conservatives said Mrs. Yip's family may go to the
restaurant if they receive special permission.
   Earlier in the week, Nationalists teamed up with Conservatives
in the nearby town of Benoni to allow blacks to use the reference
section of the municipal library, but not the lending section.
   The issue had come up when two private schools, which have
non-white pupils, applied for permission to use the library.
   Arguing that the whole library should be reserved for whites,
Conservative Party member Willie Koen said white taxpayers had
built the library. ``The more blacks are educated the greater the
influx will be. Whites will find it difficult to read peacefully or
study in the library,'' he said.
   The Conservative Party motion was defeated 13-6. Then the
Conservatives and Nationalists agreed to open the reference section
to non-whites on a vote of 13-5, with one abstention.
</TEXT>
