<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru a0490 04-28 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0490,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Shares Hit Record High</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `On the...', to add Nikkei average close. A version
moved on financial wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar moved higher today against the
Japanese yen, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange closed
at another high.
   The dollar finished the week at 132.49 yen, up 0.44 yen from
Thursday's closing of 132.05 yen. After opening higher at 132.20
yen, the U.S. currency ranged from 132.20 to 132.60 yen during the
day.
   Currency dealers said participants purchased the dollar because
today was the last trading day of the month and because of a
lower-than-expected rise in Tokyo-area consumer prices.
   Consumer prices in the capital area in April were 2.6 percent
higher than a year earlier and 1.4 percent higher than the previous
month, reducing concern over a possible tightening of credit by the
Bank of Japan, said Shinichiro Maruyama of the Industrial Bank of
Japan.
   A 3 percent sales tax went into effect April 1.
   In a news conference today, Finance Minister Tatsuo Murayama
said the nation's central bank was worried about price stability
and high oil prices. But the tone of his remarks suggested there
would not be an immediate change in monetary policy, traders said.
   Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita said Thursday the central
bank would act swiftly, if necessary, to sustain price stability.
   On the stock exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, which gained 65.90 points Thursday, added an additional
212.52 points, or 0.63 percent. That brought the average as the
week closed to a record 33,713.35. The rise followed a 29.88-point
rise in the Dow Jones industrial average in New York overnight.
   ``Shares were bought on a broad front, because of prospects for
a continuing rise in prices,'' said a stock analyst with Daiwa
Securities, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   He said the stock market had already taken into account a
possible 0.5 percentage point rise in the discount rate, the rate
the central bank charges on loans to commercial banks.
   The discount rate has a strong impact on other interest rates.
Higher interest rates tend to make a country's currency more
attractive to investors.
</TEXT>
