<FIRST>r a PM-LouisianaTaxes     04-28 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Louisiana Taxes,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor Says Louisiana's Future Rides On Tax Referendum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The future of a state that masks its
poverty with an image of fun, food and crooked politics rides on a
Saturday referendum to give Louisiana the power to change its tax
system, Gov. Buddy Roemer said.
   Roemer's plan shifts the tax base, putting more of a load on
consumers and giving businesses incentives to move into the state
and expand.
   The plan also includes a $1.4 billion program to improve
highways, airports and shipping ports. The transportation portion
would be funded by a gasoline tax increase of 4 cents a gallon.
   If the referendum is defeated, the Legislature would have to cut
more than $600 million from an already tight budget, which Roemer
said is impossible.
   Roemer has touted the plan as a way of creating jobs in a state
that has the nation's highest unemployment rate and ending
Louisiana's dependence on the petroleum industry.
   The governor, who took office 13 months ago with a pledge to
erase what lawmakers have called the state's banana republic image,
won't predict victory.
   ``What frightens me are those who might not look at the plan at
all and be persuaded by something else in Louisiana politics _ old
wars, old wounds, old alliances, business as usual,'' Roemer said
Thursday.
   He said he also feared that opponents he did not name might
spread ``street money,'' a term for vote buying, but he wouldn't
elaborate.
   Two polls conducted over the past week vary in their results.
   One poll showed 48 percent of 812 voters questioned backing the
plan, with 28 percent opposed and 25 percent undecided, with
numbers rounded and a margin of error of plus or minus 3.5 points.
A second poll says it's too close to call: Of 750 voters
questioned, 40 percent were for the plan, 38 percent against, and
22 percent undecided, with a 3.6-point margin of error.
   Secretary of State Fox McKeithen said he expects more than 40
percent of the state's 2 million registered voters to cast ballots
on the proposed constitutional amendment giving the Legislature the
power to change the tax system.
   The plan, promoted by businesses and other proponents in a $1
million blitz of television and radio spots, newspaper ads and
mailed circulars, would cost an extra $126 million over the current
tax load.
   Opponents, however, point out that as of July 1, the tax load
increase is $526 million.
   Last summer, the Legislature approved a one-year sales tax
increase of $500 million to avoid government bankruptcy. The
increase, in the form of canceling longtime exemptions on purchases
of food and utilities, will expire July 1.
   Roemer's package keeps about $400 million of that tax on a
permanent basis.
   ``White man speak with forked tongue,'' state Rep. David Duke
said of Roemer. ``He says the plan is (almost) tax neutral without
the gas tax but if it doesn't pass, he says we'll have a $600
million deficit. He can't have it both ways.''
   Duke, a former Ku Klux Klan leader, was elected to the
Legislature in February and became the most vocal of the tax
opponents, who have raised about $60,000 to fight the plan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
