<HEAD>Arab Car Explodes Near Police Station; 11 Reported Wounded in Clashes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 16 grafs to UPDATE with 11 woundings reported. Pickup
21st graf pvs, `The violence...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car driven by a Palestinian blew up today on
a busy shopping street near Jerusalem's police headquarters, and
authorities said the explosion may have been a terrorist attack
that failed.
   The driver was badly burned, but no other injuries were reported.
   In the West Bank, masked attackers shot and killed a Palestinian
in the crowded main square in Nablus. Arab reports said the victim
was accused of collaborating with Israel.
   Eleven other Palestinians were shot and wounded in clashes with
army troops and Jewish settlers in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip, according to the Arab reports.
   The army confirmed the incident in Nablus but said it was
investigating the circumstances. Military spokesmen said the army
was checking reports of other injuries.
   Police spokesman Uzi Sandori said police believe the sedan that
burst into flames and blew up was to have been used in a car bomb
attack but went off prematurely. The driver was holding a
detonator, and there were six tins of kerosene and two cooking gas
canisters in the trunk, Sandori said.
   ``We believe it might be a terrorist act that failed because of
the things we found in the car,'' the spokesman said.
   Sandori said the driver, identified only as a Palestinian from
Arab east Jerusalem, has a criminal record for disturbing the
peace. He was reported in serious condition in Hadassah Hospital.
   Officials said the fire that preceded the blast apparently was
caused by cooking gas leaking from the canisters in the trunk, but
Sandori said the fire began in the gas tank.
   A witness said the blast occurred as the driver switched on the
ignition.
   ``Exactly as he switched it the car exploded. It wasn't a loud
explosion. The whole car went up in flames,'' Aryeh Shapira, who
was passing the area on his motorcycle, said on Israel radio.
   In the West Bank, the center of the city of Hebron was declared
a closed military area after clashes between soldiers and
stone-throwing Palestinians, Israel radio said.
   Two Palestinians were wounded when soldiers opened fire on
stone-throwers, the radio said.
   Arab reporters said Jewish settlers in Hebron shot a 14-year-old
boy in the head. The victim, Nader Mohammed Abu Hamdia, was
reported in serious condition at Jerusalem's Mukassed Hospital.
   In Nablus, masked attackers shot 38-year-old Kamel Abu Samt in
the head and in the mouth, Arab reports said. He died later in
Ittihad Hospital. The reports said Abu Samt was accused of
collaborating with Israeli authorities.
   A Palestinian was wounded in a clash with soldiers in Nablus,
and seven residents of the Gaza Strip were shot and wounded in
other confrontations with troops, Arab reports said.
   The violence broke out as Arabs in Gaza launched a three-day
commercial strike to protest the death of a 16-year-old killed
Wednesday in Gaza City's Sabra quarter.
   The slain youth was a member of the underground of the Moslem
fundamentalist movement Hamas, or ``Zeal,'' Arab reports said.
   At least 455 Palestinians have been reported killed in the
uprising against Israeli occupation. Eighteeen Israelis have died.
   Israel radio said, meanwhile, that an army investigation of a
deadly raid by troops in an Arab village April 13 showed that
border patrol troops used ``exaggerated'' gunfire to quell Arab
resistance.
   Five Palestinians were shot to death and at least 15 were
wounded in what was one of the worst clashes of the uprising.
   The report on the West Bank village of Nahalin, given to Chief
of Staff Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron on Thursday, showed the 25
paramilitary police fired 150 live bullets during the clash, the
radio said.
</TEXT>
