<FIRST>r a PM-ChristExhibit     04-28 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Christ Exhibit,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minister Gets Apology In Furor Over Controversial Christ Art</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note language in 4th graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON HARRIST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A minister has withdrawn a boycott threat
against an insurance company because it has apologized for its role
in sponsoring an award for an artist whose work includes a
depiction of Christ submerged in urine.
   ``I have received a statement from Richard H. Jenrette, chairman
of the Equitable Life Assurance Society of the United States,
apologizing for their part in this matter and it is a genuine
apology,'' the Rev. Donald Wildmon, a United Methodist minister who
heads the Tupelo-based American Family Association, said Thursday.
   Wildmon had threatened earlier this week to urge supporters to
boycott the company for helping fund a $15,000 award to Andres
Serrano in the Awards in the Visual Arts program. The award is
funded by the Equitable Foundation, a division of the insurance
company, the Rockefeller Foundation and the National Endowment for
the arts.
   As winner of the award, the artist selects a work for a national
tour. The 38-year-old New York artist said he had selected his
``Piss Christ'' photograph for the tour because it best reflected
his style. He uses fluids to affect photographic images.
   Wildmon said he had sought apologies from the sponsoring
organizations.
   Jenrette, in a statement confirmed by his office in New York,
said his society was ``deeply upset by the pain that has been
caused by the work by Andres Serrano that was included in the 1988
exhibit of the Awards in the Visual Arts program.
   ``As one of the sponsors of the program last year, Equitable is
very sorry to have had its name associated with an offensive piece
of work,'' Jenrette wrote. ``Please be assured that you have our
sincere apologies and our commitment to take every precaution
against such a situation in the future.''
   Although Wildmon said his association had not heard directly
from the Rockefeller Foundation, the organization's president,
Peter Goldmark, said earlier in New York that he respected ``the
right of any individual to object to a work of art, and the
parallel right of artists to express themselves and of exhibitors
to show works that they deem interesting and meritorious
artistically.''
   Joseph Slye, a spokesman for The National Endowment for the
Arts, said Tuesday that the endowment is ``expressly forbidden in
its authorizing legislation from interfering with the artistic
choices made by its grantees.''
   Serrano, who described himself as religious, said in a telephone
interview from New York on Tuesday that when individuals such as
Wildmon ``attack a work of art to such a great extent, they imbue
it with a far greater power than when they ignore it and, in that,
I'm flattered that they think it deserves such attention.''
</TEXT>
