<HEAD>Letter to Christiani Alleges Violence Against Churches</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling to Cristiani sted Christiani throughout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-two members of Congress are asking El
Salvador's president-elect for action to halt the alleged
persecution of churches by members of his right-wing political
party and by the Salvadoran armed forces.
   The letter Thursday to President-elect Alfredo Cristiani
denounced the ``dramatic escalation of violence committed by
factions from both the right and left'' over the past few weeks.''
   But it singled out for attention recent ``verbal and physical
attacks'' allegedly committed by members of Cristiani's right-wing
ARENA Party against Salvadoran church groups.
   The letter, drafted by Rep. Pete Stark, D-Calif., and signed by
him and 31 of his House colleagues, said it is believed that
violence against church groups is believed to be connected to their
demands for a negotiated political solution to the war, their
defense of human rights, their demand for an end to war-related aid
to El Salvador and their efforts to relive the suffering of
refugees and displaced people.
   Citing a list of incidents since March 27, the House members
said a teacher in a Baptist school was assassinated, a Lutheran
church worker was abducted, and the offices of church groups broken
into and ransacked by officers of the Treasury police.
   They also complained that ARENA Party members and troops of the
Salvadoran armed forces have threatened the legal aid office of the
Roman Catholic Church in El Salvador for issuing a report ``which
was critical of the rise of death-squad-related violence.''
   ``We urge you to stop the persecution of the churches of El
Salvador and the communities they serve,'' the House members told
Cristiani.
   ``We support action to end human rights violations and we look
for a negotiated solution to the conflict within your country,''
they said.
</TEXT>
