<FIRST>u i PM-Japan 1stLd-Writethru   04-28 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0515,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>Takeshita's Governing Party Forces Budget Through Lower House</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Takeshita, Ito comments. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing party forced the budget through the
lower house of Parliament today over an opposition boycott, opening
the way for Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita to step down as
promised because of a scandal.
   It was the first time since World War II that the governing
Liberal Democratic Party bucked the Japanese tradition of consensus
and used its majority to pass a budget despite a boycott.
   Chairwoman Takako Doi of the Japan Socialist Party, the largest
opposition group, said the move was ``an outrage ... and a serious
challenge to the people.''
   She demanded the government resign and let the opposition govern.
   ``We are determined to continue to fight until we win the
dissolution of the Diet (parliament) and get new elections
called,'' she said.
   The deputy speaker of the lower house, Shinnen Hatagaya, said he
would resign to protest the handling of the budget. An independent
lawmaker, Yukio Aoshima, told reporters he was quitting the upper
house in a similar protest.
   Ms. Doi and the chairman of the Democratic Socialist Party,
Eiichi Nagasue, said the government was trying to cover up the
influence-peddling scandal. Nagasue accused the government of an
``unjustifiable debasement of parliamentary democracy.''
   Opposition politicians blocked the hall outside the house
chamber in an attempt to halt the vote, but guards pushed them
aside to get Speaker Kenzaburo Hara into the 512-seat chamber.
   After the 281-1 vote _ one independent cast a ``no'' ballot _
Takeshita bowed to the chamber, which was nearly a third empty. He
promised on Tuesday that we would resign after the budget has been
enacted.
   ``To be honest, I am feeling relief, but the budget still has to
go through the upper house and I hope it will be passed quickly,''
he told reporters later. Asked if he intends to stay in office
until the passage, Takeshita said, ``You can take it that way.''
   Under the constitution, the $455 billion budget automatically
takes effect May 27 if the less powerful upper house does not act
on it.
   Takeshita said he would step down to take responsibility for a
bribery and stock-profiteering scandal that has deeply shaken the
public's trust in government. The scandal involving Recruit Co., an
information and publishing conglomerate, has dominated Japanese
politics since it surfaced in June.
   Prosecutors say Recruit sold unlisted stocks at bargain prices
to about 160 political and business figures. The buyers profited
handsomely when the stock went public, authorities say.
   The only remaining hurdle to Takeshita's resignation is
selection of a successor.
   Takeshita planned a weeklong visit to Southeast Asian countries
beginning Saturday, and observers believe he will leave office
shortly afterward.
   The apparent top choice of party leaders, former Foreign
Minister Masayoshi Ito, 75, has refused suggestions he take the
job. He said again today the job is too heavy a burden for him
because of his age and poor health.
   Ito is known as ``Mr. Clean'' because of his humble political
style. He suffers from diabetes, and government officials say his
doctor has recommended he work no more than three hours a day.
   Earlier today, Takeshita attended the funeral of Ihei Aoki, his
top aide and fund controller, who committed suicide Wednesday. Aoki
resigned last year after it was disclosed he had purchased
bargain-priced stock from Recruit.
   This week, Takeshita admitted Recruit loaned $384,000 to his
campaign in Aoki's name.
</TEXT>
