<FIRST>u i PM-US-Australia     04-28 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Australia,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Australians Angry at Quayle Trade Remarks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Quayle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD BILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Visiting Vice President Dan Quayle has
angered the government with his insistence that U.S. wheat
subsidies are not hurting Australia, prompting one newspaper today
to say: ``Read our lips Mr. Quayle, Australians are not happy.''
   Senior government sources, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said Prime Minister Bob Hawke was exasperated at Quayle's
intransigence and that he became agitated and tense during their
talks on Wednesday.
   Quayle, at a news conference Thursday, bluntly refused to accept
Hawke's assertion that Australia had a declining share of the world
wheat market because of U.S. subsidies, known as the Export
Enhancement Program.
   ``It is still my belief that U.S. trade policy isn't hurting
Australia,'' Quayle said, adding that the subsidies were directed
against the European Community and ``not targeted at Australia.''
   But Hawke told reporters later: ``If a bullet hits you in the
head, it hurts just as much if it was not aimed at you as if it was
aimed.''
   Quayle argued that U.S. trade subsidies were designed to counter
EC subsidies while Hawke said they affected Australia's wheat sales
to China, the Soviet Union, Egypt, Iraq, Mexico, Sri Lanka and
Yemen. He said Australia had suffered a ``very significant'' loss
of exports to those countries.
   He cited a 91 percent loss in exports to the Soviet Union and a
21 percent loss in sales to China. Overall, Australian wheat sales
have fallen from an annual high of 18.6 million tons to 12.5
million tons since the U.S. subsidy program took effect.
   ``Now these sorts of things are not figments of our imagination.
They are cold, hard and brutally hurtful economic statistics which
have adversely affected our farmers, our wheat farmers,'' Hawke
said.
   Trade Negotiations Minister Michael Duffy was more direct,
saying: ``If Mr. Quayle, after a fulsome briefing by the prime
minister, can't grasp the situation (then) there is little hope for
him.''
   The country's main nationally circulated newspaper, The
Australian, said in its editorial today: ``Who do you think you are
kidding, Mr. Quayle? Read our lips, Mr. Quayle. Australians are not
happy.''
   Quayle arrived Wednesday on the first leg of a four-nation tour
of the Pacific and the Far East. He is visiting Australia through
Sunday to attend celebrations marking the 47th anniversary of the
Battle of the Coral Sea.
   Officials said trade was the ``single most important'' issue
that Australia had to raise with the vice president. Hawke and
Quayle met for 90 minutes on Wednesday.
   Hawke is to visit the United States in June and the sources said
he would raise trade issues in his talks with President Bush.
</TEXT>
