<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Medvedev     04-28 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Medvedev,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chronicler of Stalin's Crimes Restored to Party</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to ADD Medvedev comments, details on his book. No
pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party has restored membership to
dissident historian Roy A. Medvedev, whose writings about the
personality cult of dictator Josef Stalin prompted his expulsion in
1969, Tass said today.
   Medvedev asked that the party's Central Committee Control
Committee restore him as a member, and the request was approved,
the official news agency said. It did not say when this occurred.
   In a telephone interview, the 63-year-old writer said he reacted
``positively'' to the news. Asked if his restoration was a result
of President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms, he said: ``I didn't
change my views. A turnabout occurred in the party, the Central
Committee. They stopped discriminating against me. I have been
published here.''
   He added that he never considered asking to be restored as a
party member during the rule of President Leonid I. Brezhnev
because, ``That was another epoch.'' Brezhnev died in 1982.
   Medvedev said party officials asked him several months ago if he
wanted to become a member again. ``They asked me how I would react,
and I said I would not object.''
   Like many Soviets who had fallen out of official favor, Medvedev
has been restored gradually to good graces. He has appeared at
several officially sponsored news conference and was elected April
9 as a deputy to the new Soviet parliament, the Congress of
People's Deputies.
   Tass said it was Medvedev's book ``Let History Judge,'' about
Stalin's crimes, that prompted his expulsion from the party but
that the control committee determined that action was ``unfounded''
and restored his membership.
   ``Let History Judge,'' which Medvedev started writing in 1962,
was published first abroad, in the United States in 1971. It didn't
appear in the Soviet Union until this year, when the literary
journal Znamya published the first part of the book in January.
   The entire book, an indictment of Stalin's dictatorial rule, is
scheduled to be put out by the Soviet Union's Progress Publishers.
   Under President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or
openness, it is no longer considered dissent to condemn Stalin or
report his crimes. In fact, the Soviet press is full of articles
about Stalin's personality cult.
   Medvedev has estimated that 40 million Soviets were either
killed, arrested or otherwise repressed under Stalin, and his
figure _ along with his remarks about Stalin _ has appeared in the
Soviet press.
</TEXT>
