<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military shot and
critically wounded two people today who drove a stolen car through
a security checkpoint, knocking down a soldier, police said.
   The two males, aged 17 and 20, were in critical condition, and
the soldier suffered minor injuries, said a spokesman for the Royal
Ulster Constabulary, the police force for this British province.
   An undetermined number of other people in the car were believed
to have escaped, said the spokesman, speaking anonymously in
keeping with British custom.
   He said in a statement that the incident occurred just after 1
a.m. in West Belfast ``when a stolen car in which the men were
traveling drove through a joint police-army vehicle checkpoint.''
   The car ``mounted the footpath, knocking down a soldier,
slightly injuring him, before being fired on by the military.''
   The spokesman refused to comment on the motive or identity of
the men, or other details.
   Northern Ireland has been plagued by political and sectarian
violence since August 1969 and more than 2,700 people have been
killed.
