<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 1145EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-US     04-28 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-US,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports: Japan May Compromise On Jet Fighter Project</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government indicated today it may soften its
stand on a controversial plan to jointly develop its next fighter
jet with the United States, news reports said.
   The Defense Agency has decided to retract its demand that more
than 50 percent of engine production work be given to Japan and
that Japan receive all computer software for flight control of the
U.S. F-16, which is the basis for the new FSX jet, Asahi Shimbun
newspaper reported.
   The Defense Agency chief, Kichiro Tazawa, told reporters today
he hopes to reach agreement with the United States before Prime
Minister Noboru Takeshita leaves office. Takeshita's announcement
Tuesday that he will resign soon because of a stock and bribery
scandal brought new uncertainty to already troubled plans for the
FSX, U.S. officials said.
   The Asahi Shimbun newspaper said the director of the Defense
Agency's equipment bureau returned Thursday from talks in
Washington, and his agency consulted today with the Foreign
Ministry, the Ministry of International Trade and Industry, and the
prime minister's office to work out a unified policy.
   The FSX project has been criticized by some U.S. congressmen who
charge it is a giveaway of U.S. technology that Japanese companies
could use to compete with the U.S. aviation industry.
   Supporters say the project is a way to add fighters to Japan's
inventory in strategic northeast Asia at Tokyo's expense. It also
would provide jobs for the United States, and give Washington
access to sophisticated radar technology developed by Japan, they
say.
   The Bush administration says it wants clarification of a joint
production agreement reached last year.
   Japan reportedly demanded 50 percent of engine production work
in exchange for giving the United States a 40 percent share of the
production work for the entire aircraft.
   The United States reportedly wants assurances any new technology
developed from the project will be available to the United States,
along with protection for U.S.-developed computer codes that help
fly and control the plane.
</TEXT>
