<FIRST>u a PM-BabyDeath-Euthanasia 1stLd-Writethru a0489 04-28 0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baby Death-Euthanasia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0489,0789</SECOND>
<HEAD>Father's Removal of Baby From Life Support Renews Ethical Questions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `Cook County...' with 3 grafs to UPDATE with
agreement today on subpoenas. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `Partee said...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who kept hospital workers at bay with a gun
while tearfully removing his comatose son from life support systems
and letting him die dramatized an ethical ``issue waiting to
happen,'' a law professor says.
   Rudy Linares, 23, is charged with first-degree murder and on
Thursday was ordered to undergo a psychiatric examination by a
judge who called his case ``an extraordinary situation surrounded
by extraordinary circumstances.''
   ``I want to know if he is any danger to himself or anyone
else,'' said Cook County Judge Robert Bastone, before setting
another hearing for May 18.
   Linares, free on $75,000 personal recognizance bond, refused to
talk to reporters.
   Defense lawyer Richard Scholz said Linares, who told police, ``I
did it because I love my son,'' will plead innocent.
   Scholz met briefly with prosecutors today in the chambers of
Chief Criminal Court Judge Thomas Fitzgerald and worked out an
agreement to delay until May 3 the appearance dates for those
subpoenaed, said Lisa Howard, spokeswoman for Cook County State's
Attorney Cecil Partee.
   Ms. Howard would not comment further because of the
confidentiality surrounding grand jury proceedings. But a
law-enforcement source with knowledge of the case said Linares'
wife and several other family members had received subpoenas to
appear before the grand jury, possibly as early as today.
   Partee on Thursday confirmed his intention to prosecute Linares,
but suggested there could be ``a compassionate kind of justice.''
   Partee said he could understand the emotions that a parent feels
at seeing the suffering of an incurably ill child.
   ``But we must be reasonable and say, I think, that under no
circumstances does any person have the right to take the life of
another,'' he said during the Thursday taping of a radio show to be
aired Sunday.
   Richard Epstein, a University of Chicago law professor and
fellow at the school's Center for Medical Ethics, said that
charging Linares with murder was wrong and called the case an
``issue waiting to happen.''
   ``Doctors have an exaggerated sense of the sacred nature of
life,'' Epstein said. ``It seems to me he should have been able to
write a letter to the hospital saying, `Please turn off the
respirator. Very truly yours.'''
   Other ethicists also expressed sympathy for the father of two
other children, who along with his wife had asked months ago for
life support to be withdrawn from their 16-month old son, Samuel.
The parents had been refused.
   The boy had been unconscious and not expected to recover since
August, when he swallowed a balloon at a birthday party, said his
physician, Dr. Gilbert Goldman, director of pediatric intensive
care at Rush-Presbyterian-St. Luke's Medical Center, where
Wednesday's incident occurred.
   Goldman said, ``I was personally and professionally
sympathetic'' with the Linares' request to withdraw life support,
but ``I didn't believe there was a legal option to allow me to act
on the basis of their request.''
   Max Brown, legal counsel for the hospital, said that because of
Illinois' child-abuse laws, the only way the institution could have
complied would have been if Samuel had been determined totally
brain-dead or his heart and lungs had stopped functioning.
   Arthur Caplan, director of the Center for Biomedical Ethics at
the University of Minnesota, said, ``I have sympathy for this
father, because it seems to me he felt he had no choice but to act
on what he felt was best for this child at the point of a gun.
   ``I still think he should be prosecuted. I don't think you can
use weapons to direct medical treatment,'' Caplan said in a
telephone interview from Minneapolis.
   ``But I have sympathy because I think society has not made it
possible for parents to be heard about when medical treatment
should be stopped _ when it is futile _ for very young children,''
Caplan said.
   Police said Linares entered the hospital intensive care unit at
about 1 a.m. Wednesday and unhooked the respirator of his son while
holding hospital workers off with a .357-caliber Magnum handgun.
   Linares, a house painter in Cicero, surrendered the gun as soon
as he was sure the boy was dead, authorities said. His wife,
Tamara, was out of the room at the time.
   Authorities said Linares also disconnected the respirator in
December, but it was quickly replaced and he was not charged
because the hospital did not call police.
</TEXT>
