<HEAD>Iraqi Air Force Downs Egyptian Plane By Mistake</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 5th graf, `The Washington...' to UPDATE with Egypt saying
pilots parachuted to safety. Pickup 6th graf, `The diplomats...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iraqi soldier shot down an Egyptian
jet fighter by mistake as it prepared to land in Baghdad for an air
show, and there were several casualties as the plane crashed in
pieces, Arab diplomats said today.
   The diplomats, speaking by telephone from Baghdad, the Iraqi
capital, said the incident occurred April 20.
   The plane, an Egyptian-built version of the Alpha fighter-bomber
produced by France and West Germany, apparently was hit by a
Soviet-designed, shoulder-fired SAM-7 missile.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said a man on
the ground was killed when the plane fell to the ground, hurling
debris over a wide area. They could not provide details on the
other casualties.
   Egypt's government-run Middle East News Agency said the two
pilots parachuted to safety.
   The diplomats refused to say where exactly the plane crashed.
   There was no imediate comment from the Iraqi or Egyptian
governments. The diplomats suggested the two agreed to keep the
incident under wraps to avoid disrupting Iraq's first International
Defense Fair, inaugurated today.
   Egypt is one of 28 countries participating in the five-day
exhibition, which includes an air show on Saturday.
   The Egyptian plane was to participate in the show, but word of
the invitation had not reached the soldier who downed the jet, The
Washington Post reported today. It cited secret intelligence
reports making the rounds of U.S. government offices.
   Egypt, which was Iraq's main backer in the war with Iran, has
purchased Alpha kits from France and assembles the fighter-bomber
in a plant south of Cairo. The jet has a top speed of 600 mph.
