<HEAD>Panama's Foreign Minister Assails U.S. `Destabilization'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs with more on Panama's charges, U.S. reply.
Pickup 5th graf pvs, ``Two vice...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Panamanian official today accused the
United States of trying to provoke chaos in his country prior to
national elections as an excuse for U.S. military intervention.
   Jorge Ritter, Panama's foreign minister, said Washington has
given millions of dollars to opposition candidates and said the
U.S. Army has sent special urban warfare units to its bases in the
Canal Zone.
   ``American plans to interfere in the Panamanian electoral
process have entered a phase of direct participation by the United
States with the goal of disturbing the public order and propagating
chaos, prompting general destabilization in the country around the
time of the elections to create an excuse for military
intervention,'' he told the Security Council.
   Ritter implied that if the opposition did not defeat the
pro-government candidates, U.S. armed forces would foment disorder
and back a coup attempt.
   U.S. Ambassador Thomas Pickering replied that Panama was
concocting claims of U.S. interference to conceal ``its lack of
freedom and its apparent intention to conduct fraudulent
elections'' on May 7. Pickering said the government of Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega is doctoring voting lists and restricting the entry
of journalists and independent election observers.
   Noriega, the armed forces commander and de facto ruler of
Panama, is backing Carlos Alberto Duque for the presidency against
opposition candidate Guillermo Endara. Endara has denied that his
Democratic Alliance campaign has received any U.S. money.
   Two vice presidents, 67 assembly representatives and 510 local
representatives also will be chosen.
   Noriega was indicted on federal drug charges in Florida in
February 1988. Panamanian President Eric Arturo Delvalle then tried
to fire him, and Noriega had the National Assembly oust Delvalle.
   Noriega has blamed the United States for all Panama's problems,
and accused Washington of trying to renege on a treaty to transfer
control of the Panama Canal to Panama by the end of the century.
