<FIRST>r a AM-BridgeClosed     04-28 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bridge Closed,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Closes Another Bridge Pending Further Inspections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A four-lane bridge on a major city
thoroughfare was closed after inspectors discovered one of its
footings had eroded, transportation officials said.
   Authorities closed the U.S. 51 bridge over the Wolf River in
north Memphis on Thursday night, said Ken Renner, spokesman for
Gov. Ned McWherter.
   The closure, ordered by state Transportation Commissioner Jimmy
Evans, was temporary, pending a full inspection, Renner said.
   Inspectors, engineers and divers were expected to determine
Friday if the bridge could be reopened or should remain closed
until the problems are corrected, Renner said.
   The decision comes in the wake of a mass inspection following
two fatal bridge collapses in Tennessee this month.
   ``We've had crews of inspectors out over the last several weeks
inspecting well over a hundred bridges in west Tennessee looking
for any additional erosion problems,'' Renner said.
   Inspectors looking at the Wolf River bridge discovered
``considerable scouring'' on one end of one of the span's footings,
he said.
   Eight people died when a two-lane span of U.S. Highway 51
collapsed into the Hatchie River near Covington on April 1. Another
bridge collapsed April 15 in Anderson County in East Tennessee,
killing a motorist and injuring two companions.
</TEXT>
