<FIRST>r i AM-Virtuoso     04-28 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Virtuoso,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York Teen Steps in for Perlman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gil Shaham was at his New York City high school
reciting Chaucer when he received a summons that seemed straight
out of the storybooks.
   Israeli violin virtuoso Itzhak Perlman had an ear infection and
couldn't perform at two London concerts, and Shaham was asked to
stand in on two days' notice.
   The first of the concerts ended Thursday night with cheers and
flowers for the 18-year-old violinist after his performance of the
difficult Violin Concerto No. 1 by Max Bruch.
   ``This is something I've never had before,'' said Shaham,
perspiring in his dressing room at the Royal Festival Hall
afterward, as he stared at the basket of flowers.
   Shaham, from the Bronx, was reciting the prologue from Chaucer's
``The Canterbury Ttales'' in an English examination at Horace Mann
High School on Tuesday when he was called out and asked to fly to
London next day.
   Shaham promptly took three days off school.
   Eleanor Hope, his London agent, said telephone consultations
with Shaham's general manager in New York and conductor Michael
Tilson-Thomas of the London Symphony Orchestra decided on the Bruch
concerto, followed by Jean Sibelius' Violin Concerto on Friday.
   Asked how well he knew the works, the tall, chubby-faced
musician grinned and said: ``I was nervous because I felt I could
not fill in for Perlman. I last played the Bruch in December and
the Sibelius in the summer.''
   ``But the funny thing is,'' he added, ``I had some bizarre
premonition about this. On Monday, I changed the strings on my
Guadagnini (violin), which I always do before a concert, although I
wasn't booked for any concert this week.''
   ``I'm always nervous when he plays but I wasn't tonight,'' said
his astrophysicist father, Jacob Shaham. ``I knew that nothing
could go wrong.''
   ``I didn't know that,'' his son chimed in. ``But with an
orchestra like that and Tilson-Thomas I felt completely
comfortable.''
   Shaham said he began playing violin when he was seven and wants
to be a professional. He said he had never been so rushed before.
   ``I once had to stand in for Yehudi Menuhin who had flu in
Norfolk, Va.,'' he said. ``But I had a week's notice of that.''
   Shaham is practically unknown in London although he was here
once before in debut with the London Symphony in May 1987 and again
in March 1988.
   Concertgoers Nicola Constable and Helen Munro of The Strad, a
London music magazine, praised Shaham's performance.
   ``I thought he was brilliant. It must have been dreadful for him
to know he was replacing Perlman but nobody could have been
disappointed and it's difficult to play Bruch well,'' Miss
Constable said.
   ``I thought he was incredibly mature for 18,'' said Miss Munro.
``I wonder where he can go now if he can play like this after only
10 years. That's not long for any instrument but the violin in
particular is so technically difficult.''
   Shaham studies music at the Juilliard School in New York and has
important bookings with European orchestras this season. He also is
scheduled for tours of Japan and the Soviet Union.
   Ms. Hope said Shaham practiced at his London hotel until past
midnight on Wednesday, taking over a deserted banqueting room
because the acoustics were better there than in his bedroom.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
