<HEAD>Americans Abandon Himalayan Expedition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American expedition has abandoned its
attempt to climb Mount Ama Dablam because of dangerous conditions,
according to a message received Friday.
   After leaving for the summit from their second camp at 20,000
feet, the team had to turn back April 20 because of falling rocks
along the way, the message said.
   It did not specify the altitude where the team turned back.
   The expedition, led by Wendy L. Ostgaard, 38, of Longmont,
Colo., made the attempt on the 22,343-foot mountain via its
southwest ridge.
