<FIRST>u w PM-US-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0441 04-28 0751</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0441,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panama Accuses U.S. of Interfering in Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 5 grafs new to show Panama condemning U.S. in United Nations.
Picks up 5th graf pvs, I believe. Also edits penultimate graf to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has accused the Panamanian
government of setting up ``systematic fraud'' for an upcoming
election, but that country's foreign minister today accused the
United States of interfering in Panama's electoral process.
   The United States would ``not recognize fraudulent election
results engineered by (Panamanian strongman Manuel Antonio)
Noriega,'' Bush said in a statement released during his visit
Thursday to Clearwater, Fla.
   ``In recent weeks, the Noriega regime has taken steps to commit
systematic fraud,'' Bush said.
   But Jorge Ritter, Panama's foreign minister, told the United
Nations Security Council today, ``American plans to interfere in
the Panamanian electoral process have entered a phase of direct
participation by the United States with the goal of disturbing the
public order and propagating chaos, prompting general
destabilization in the country around the time of the elections to
create an excuse for military intervention.''
   Ousted Panamanian President Eric Arturo Delvalle met Thursday in
Washington with Secretary of State James A. Baker III to discuss
the May 7 balloting. He told reporters that opposition parties in
his country did not receive any covert aid from the United States
and branded such reports as a cover-up by Noriega.
   ``I believe Noriega has looked for an excuse to take away from
the people's attention what is going on in Panama,'' Delvalle said
in response to a question.
   Reports published last week in U.S. media said President Bush
had signed a secret intelligence directive, called a ``finding,''
to provide $10 million to the general's opponents in the
presidential elections. The White House has said it will not
comment on intelligence matters.
   Earlier Thursday, the acting Panamanian ambassador, Juan B.
Sosa, called those reports of covert aid the centerpiece of a
misinformation campaign by Noriega.
   ``There is absolutely no truth to that,'' Sosa said. ``The
opposition has run a meager campaign because they have no money.''
   Delvalle and Sosa are exiles who still are recognized by the
United States as legitimate leaders. Noriega ousted Delvalle in
February 1988 after the president called for the general's ouster.
The move came a few weeks after Noriega was indicted by a federal
grand jury in Miami on drug trafficking charges.
   ``As long as Gen. Noriega remains in power there cannot be and
will not be any improvement in relations with Panama,'' Baker said,
repeating the official U.S. stance taken since shortly after the
drug indictment.
   The secretary of state also said former U.S. presidents Gerald
R. Ford and Jimmy Carter would be among a group of international
observers for the May 7 presidential elections.
   ``It will be interesting if he refuses to admit them as
observers,'' Baker said.
   The May 7 elections pits Noriega's candidate, Carlos Alberto
Duque, against Guillermo David Endara, running on an
anti-government coalition ticket. The United States has been
forecasting Noriega will rig the elections, issuing statements
claiming the Panamanian leaders manipulated voter lists and
intimidated opposition figures.
   ``Up till now Gen. Noriega has not shown any reason to believe
they (the elections) will be fair and free,'' Delvalle said after
the meeting with Baker, which ended with them both being trapped
briefly in a State Department elevator.
   Sosa said earlier the observers should watch the setting up of
the polls, the actual balloting and the counting. The acting
Panamanian ambassador said Noriega was attempting to steal the
elections.
   He said recent Noriega maneuvers included the detention of an
American journalist, mandatory visas ``to keep people away,'' and
limited access by the opposition to the media.
   Newsweek reporter Charles Lane was detained Wednesday for
several hours by the Panamanian Defense Forces for allegedly
possessing a dollar bill bearing anti-Noriega slogans. State
Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler called it ``a typical
instance of an absence of political freedom and basic civil
liberties in Panama.''
   Sosa said the Panamanian regime's appearance before the Security
Council today to ``denounce aggression by the United States'' was
to ``deviate from the real issue: the country is held hostage by a
dictator.''
   The internal problems in Panama broke out in June 1987 when a
former military officer linked Noriega to drug trafficking, money
laundering and election fraud. The United States cut off economic
and military aid in 1987. Sanctions were imposed last year, shortly
after the indictment in Miami.
</TEXT>
