<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 1354EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Gorbachev     04-28 0763</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev,0784</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Will Have an Opponent in Election for President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev will have at
least one opponent when parliament elects the country's new
president next month, the head of the Tass news agency said Friday.
   Leonid Kravchenko, director general of the official Soviet news
agency, said a group of Moscow deputies plans to present an
alternative candidate to Gorbachev. He did not identify the
deputies and said he did not know who their candidate was.
   ``I know from the sentiment of Moscow there are a group of
Moscow deputies who are going to present an alternative candidate.
They didn't tell me who it was. This is not to express distrust of
Gorbachev, but to stress the commitment to democracy,'' he told a
news conference.
   The new 2,250-seat Congress of People's Deputies will choose the
Soviet president and elect 542 of its members to a new full-time
legislature, the Supreme Soviet. The president also will be
chairman of the Supreme Soviet.
   The congress will meet May 25-June 1, the Tass executive said.
   Gorbachev, who replaced Andrei A. Gromyko as president on Oct.
1, is expected to be chosen. Kravchenko was the first Soviet
official to state publicly that the election would be contested.
   Kravchenko, one of 1,500 deputies elected by voters to the
congress, said the president would be chosen in the early days of
the meeting and ``one thing is certain, the procedure will be
conducted by secret ballot.''
   He said any deputy could propose a candidate ``and the congress
will decide whether to accept the nomination.''
   Asked whether Gorbachev's opponent might be former Moscow party
boss Boris N. Yeltsin, the political maverick elected to the
congress in a landslide following an anti-establishment campaign,
Kravchenko replied: ``To stand as an alternative candidate against
Gorbachev, I don't think he would want to do that.''
   Ten days before the March 26 election, the Communist Party
Central Committee started an investigation of charges that Yeltsin
opposed some party policies.
   Kravchenko said none of the speakers at Tuesday's Central
Committee meeting, which he attended, brought up Yeltsin because
they realized that a discussion ``would be untimely and hopeless.''
   ``In all probability, he (Yeltsin) will be nominated to the
Supreme Soviet and he stands a good chance to be elected'' by the
congress, Kravchenko said.
   Kravchenko indicated deputies from different regions would
decide among themselves on slates of nominees for the Supreme
Soviet.
   It has been suggested, he said, that all deputies to the
congress from Moscow _ those elected by the public as well as those
chosen from the party and social and professional organizations _
meet May 3. At the meeting, he said, they would decide on a slate
for the Supreme Soviet, choosing one nominee from every five
deputies.
   Kravchenko said he expected the same thing to be done in other
areas in order to get a ``consolidated list.''
   Speaking of the inaugural meeting of the Congress of People's
Deputies, Kravchenko said, ``My prediction is there will be a very,
very sharp debate.''
   He said he expected the selection of the new Supreme Soviet to
take the first two days, after which there would be a short recess.
The first session of the Supreme Soviet probably will be held about
June 12, he said.
   Asked about the criticism of Gorbachev at Tuesday's Central
Committee meeting, he said the ``very critical'' speeches were the
result of two major changes in the Soviet Union which haven't kept
pace with each other, social-economic development and political
reform.
   ``We hoped there would be some harmony between the two but
unfortunately this has not come to pass. In the new political
structure, there is no doubt great success. Unfortunately, success
in the social-economic sphere leaves much to be desired,'' he said.
   Kravchenko mentioned shortages of consumer goods, higher
inflation, social tensions and corruption. He cited proposed
reforms including a reduction in state expenditures, a curtailment
of capital investment projects and a reduction in defense spending,
including the diversion of $9.7 million to the health sector.
   Vladimir Popov, the deputy director of Soviet radio and
television, when asked how the Soviets assessed the criticism,
replied: ``Our assessment is pretty good. We regard them as
realistic in today's life. Instead of complacency and good words,
we would rather have serious criticism about serious matters.''
   Kravchenko and Popov met reporters at the 35-nation East-West
conference, which is meeting in London to monitor an accord on
media and information signed in Vienna in January. Both are Soviet
delegates.
</TEXT>
