<HEAD>Jackpot Tops $115 Million, Prize Claimants Step Forward</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 17 grafs to UPDATE with holders of four more tickets
arriving, CORRECT spelling of Kathy sted Cathy Davis, one of group of Erie-area
winners. Picks up 14th graf pvs, `Just fine...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH KIRKPATRICK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIDDLETOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fantastic dreams of taking home all of a
record $115 million jackpot from Pennsylvania's Super 7 lottery
slipped away as 14 winning tickets turned up in an initial computer
scan of wagers.
   Lottery Executive Director Jim Scroggins said each of the 14
tickets will be worth $317,524.67 in annual payments over the next
26 years. If one person had won the jackpot, it would have been
worth $4.4 million a year.
   Still, the first winners to step forward were happy Thursday to
claim just a share, even if the money won't bring early retirements.
   ``It's better than nothing,'' said Gregory G. Samsa, of Warren,
Ohio, who served as spokesman for a group of 14 workers from the
Harbison-Walker brick factory in Windham, Ohio.
   If their ticket is validated, possibly early next week, each of
the 14 will get $22,680 a year before taxes for 26 years.
   Alverto Handel, 65, of Portage, Pa.; her son, Jim, 39, a coal
miner from Summerhill, Pa.; and daughter, Nancy Williams, 34, a
library technician at the U.S. Military Academy at West Point,
N.Y., also presented a ticket for validation.
   Holders of four more winning tickets checked in this morning,
lottery officials said, brining the number of claimings to step
forward to six families or groups.
   Two couples from the Erie area put in a claim for a ticket they
shared. They are Charles J. and Kathy Davis of McKean Township and
John and Rose White of Harborcreek Township. Asked how he felt,
Davis, 32, said, ``I can't even remember. I haven't slept.''
   A family from East Windsor, N.J., arrived early this afternoon.
Members of the Arthur Rosen family said the group had bought $80
worth of tickets after waiting one hour in line.
   Another winner, Sylvia Trapuzzano of Washington, Pa., said she
had spent Thursday in a Harrisburg-area motel pondering her good
fortune before putting in her claim.
   ``I was shocked and I couldn't believe it,'' she said as she was
led into lottery headquarters past a crowd of reporters and
photographers.
   Miss Trapuzzano said her father, Ben, had bought five tickets
for her and her two brothers and sister after she was unable to get
her own because of long lines.
   Also claiming tickets was a group from West Virginia: James
Evans; John Gardner; Lionel Herndon and his wife, Connie.
   Coincidentally, it was a year ago today that a bogus winning
ticket for a $15.2 million jackpot was turned in and a check for
nearly $470,000 was issued by lottery officials.
   An employee of the lottery's computer contractor who had access
to the system produced the fake ticket and an accomplice turned it
in. Lottery officials discovered the scheme several days later and
recovered the money. Both men received jail terms after pleading
guilty. The lottery has since beefed up its validation process,
which can take days to complete.
   A second set of computers must also validate the jackpot and the
number of winning tickets before both become official, Scroggins
said.
   Reports circulated Thursday about winners who were set to claim
shares of this week's jackpot.
   ``Just fine, no problem,'' Mrs. Williams said when asked about
having to share the jackpot.
   Mrs. Williams came up with six of the numbers from a computer
palm reader she had tried in an open air market during a Bahamas
vacation with her husband, Charles, in March. Her mother provided
the seventh number.
   She was at a bowling alley near her Fort Montgomery, N.Y., home
when her mother called her.
   ``It was a total shock ... I dropped the phone,'' Mrs. Williams
said.
   Mrs. Handel said she was so excited she nearly put the pencil
through the paper she was working on as she checked the lottery
numbers shotly after Wednesday's drawing. The winner was the first
ticket she checked.
   ``Tears came to my eyes,'' she said. ``I was so dumbfounded, I
couldn't even look at the other tickets.''
   Each of their shares will be worth $105,841 a year for 26 years.
They said they had no plans for the money yet.
   Besides getting less than they may have hoped for, members of
the Ohio group couldn't even get the detailed and lengthy
validation process started.
   The lottery usually tells winning groups who call in ahead of
time that they need a formal legal agreement spelling out how the
money will be disbursed. The group said they tried to call first,
but couldn't get through.
   ``They got excited ... and headed on down,'' Scroggins said
after the group drove six hours in a four-vehicle caravan.
   The group, which had bought $140 in tickets, contacted an Ohio
lawyer, who promised to have a contract delivered to lottery
headquarters today.
   Samsa called the legal holdup ``a slight disappointment, but
it's nothing we can't overcome.''
</TEXT>
