<FIRST>r w AM-US-Romania     04-28 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Romania,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Protests Detention Of Diplomat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romanian authorities briefly detained a U.S.
Embassy official who met with a critic of the Communist government
and the United States has filed a protest, State Department
officials said Friday.
   While under international law, contacts between diplomats and
local citizens are permissible, the incident is being played down
by the department and the U.S. Embassy in Bucharest out of concern
that additional strictures might be imposed on Romanians.
   Despite the economic and political reform movement sweeping the
Soviet Union, Poland and Hungary, the government of Prime Minister
Nicolae Ceausescu remains hard-line in its policies.
   The diplomat's identify was withheld. Margaret Tutwiler, the
department spokeswoman, said the diplomat was detained for 10
minutes on Tuesday and was not accused of any specific infraction.
She and other officials declined to disclose the name of the
Romanian.
   Sources in Bucharest speculated that the Romanian was one of six
Communist Party veterans who had written a letter to Ceausescu
earlier in the year sharply critical of his policies.
   The letter called for more human rights at home, an immediate
halt to food exports and the revocation of plans to destroy
thousands of villages as part of a plan to create agricultural and
industrial centers.
   The signers included former Foreign Minister Corneliu Manescu
and Silviu Brucan, a former ambassador to Washington.
   Despite its hard-line domestic policies, Romania for years has
operated with considerable independence from Moscow in foreign
affairs. It does not permit Soviet troops on its territory and did
not support Soviet military intervention in Czechoslovakia in 1968.
   Romania has maintained diplomatic relations with Israel and
permitted massive Jewish emigration for which it was rewarded with
special U.S. trade privileges. But Romania revoked its ``most
favored nation status'' last year in anticipation that Congress
would order a suspension because of Romania's domestic policies.
</TEXT>
