<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge permitted soul singer James Brown,
who is serving a six-year prison term, to leave jail to sign
autographs at a courthouse, much to the dismay of corrections
officials.
   ``Somebody asked me if I could get him up here to get his
autograph and I said I would try,'' Circuit Judge Frank Eppes said
after Thursday's signing session.
   ``I was flabbergasted,'' said Parker Evatt, commissioner of the
Department of Corrections. ``What happened is totally irregular.''
   If prison officials had known Brown was to sign autographs, they
would not have allowed him to leave the prison, Evatt said. They
assumed the sheriff's department's request to release Brown briefly
was connected to court business.
   Brown, 55, was sentenced in December to six years in jail for
leading police on a two-state car chase from Augusta, Ga., to North
Augusta, S.C. He was convicted of aggravated assault and failure to
stop for an officer.
   At Eppes' request, a sheriff's department van on Thursday drove
the ``Godfather of Soul'' from the State Park Correctional Center,
north of Columbia, to the Richland County Courthouse in downtown
Columbia.
   Brown signed autographs at the courthouse for more than 40
people, including Eppes, and then returned to prison.
   Eppes said he saw no harm in the autograph session.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First lady Barbara Bush says she has given her
son a bit of motherly advice: Stick to running the Texas Rangers
baseball team and don't run for governor of Texas.
   Mrs. Bush said Thursday she believes George W. Bush may take her
advice.
   ``I'm rather hoping he won't because everything that happens bad
with the administration is (going to be) young George's fault,''
Mrs. Bush said during a luncheon with eight reporters in the family
dining room of the White House.
   ``I'm hoping, having bought the Rangers, he'll get so involved
that he won't do it,'' she said. ``When you make a major commitment
like that ... I think maybe you won't be running for governor.''
   Bush conceded that his mother had expressed her opinion about
his possible bid for the Republican gubernatorial nomination in
1990, but said he is not sure he'll take the advice.
   ``For 42 years, she has given me her opinion,'' Bush said. ``I
have listened to it _ sometimes. I still love my mother, and I
appreciate her advice, but that's all it is, advice.''
   The first lady also said she is now a Rangers fan and plans to
throw out the first ball at a game May 4.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All but two of crime writer Elmore Leonard's
27 books have been made into movies, but until now he has never
written about the nation's movie capital, Hollywood.
   But all that is soon to change, says the master of the suspense
novel.
   Leonard, who is promoting his current novel, ``Killshot,'' said
this week he is about 150 pages into a new book about a film
producer, and the setting will be Tinseltown, instead of his most
often used Detroit.
   ``I'm going to bring in my kind of guys, drop them into the
picture and see what happens,'' says the author of ``Glitz,''
``Freaky Deaky,'' ``Stick,'' ``Hombre'' and other best sellers.
   Leonard fans know that the guys in his hair-raising thrillers
are usually tough and violent Midwesterners on both sides of the
law.
   The story-in-progress involves a man with a dark background who
comes to Hollywood ``just to help a guy trying to get a picture
made,'' said Leonard.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country-western star Waylon Jennings, who got his
start as a club singer in Phoenix in the 1960s also remembers
kicking his cocaine habit here five years ago.
   Jennings said he no idea of ``the dangers'' when he first
started taking the drug. Now, he wants to keep others, particulary
kids, from taking the same path.
   ``I think education is the only hope,'' said Jennings. ``The war
on drugs is the biggest bunch of bull in the world. But they are
teaching them now as they go through school and that's good.''
   Despite his triple-bypass heart surgery late last year, Jennings
is on the road again and headlines a ``Country Jam '89'' festival
here this weekend with Willie Nelson. He also said he and singer
Johnny Cash are thinking of buying a winter home together in
Phoenix.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Malcolm Forbes says he will vroom through Spain
for 10 days next month and spread cheer with a giant balloon
modeled on the Santa Maria, the flagship of Christopher Columbus.
   The tour of the millionaire publisher of Forbes business
magazine starts May 1 in Seville and combines his enthusiasm for
motorcycling and ballooning.
   From there he and seven other bikers will visit Granada,
Cordoba, Toledo, Madrid, Zaragosa and Barcelona.
   At each stop, the Santa Maria balloon and Forbes' own Forbes
magazine balloon will be either free-flown or exhibited on a tether.
   Spain will be the 12th nation Forbes has visited since beginning
a series of good will tours in 1979 in the Soviet Union.
