<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 1704EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DonorBoy     04-28 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Donor Boy,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ailing Boy Offers Own Heart If He Dies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SOLOMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five-year-old Eddy Hains surprised doctors when
he offered to donate his own heart if he dies, but his mother said
Friday she's used to the boy's courage as he waits for a heart-lung
transplant.
   ``It didn't really surprise me. I'm proud of him,'' said Terry
Hains in a telephone interview from Roseville, Minn., where she
awaits word from University of Minnesota Hospital and Clinics about
a transplant for Eddy.
   ``He actually thinks it's funny that he's still alive, really,''
she said. ``He says `I guess I fooled them.' He loves life and
loves people and I guess he's just not ready to go.''
   Eddy suffers from cystic fibrosis, a fatal genetic disease in
which lungs become clogged with mucus because of malfunctioning
gland secretions.
   The boy has been on a national donor list since March 1988 when
pneumonia weakened his lungs. Doctors say they want to do a
heart-lung transplant because it would reduce chances of his body
rejecting the lungs. His heart is healthy.
   On March 2, a donor was found. Eddy was prepared for the
transplant and was moments away from the operating room when
doctors determined the donor's lungs were too full of fluid.
   Mrs. Hains said before the transplant was canceled, doctors
asked Eddy if he realized that he might die during the operation
and the boy responded calmly, ``of course.''
   She said Eddy even surprised his doctors more by telling them he
wanted them to donate his heart should he die on the operating
table.
   ``You can't throw out a good heart,'' he told them. ``It's from
Wisconsin.'' The family's home is in Cudahy, a Milwaukee suburb,
but Mrs. Hains and Eddy have taken an apartment in Minnesota to be
near the hospital.
   Eddy has grown weaker this week, she said, but his enthusiasm
for life and his interest in the Milwaukee Brewers baseball team
hasn't waned.
   ``I tell him the Brewers win and he smiles,'' she said. ``He has
me wake him up (every night) to let him know what the score is.''
   Mrs. Hains and her husband, Edward, have three other children,
ages 11, 8 and 7. A bank in South Milwaukee is handling an account
for donations to the family to help with medical bills.
</TEXT>
