<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 1708EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ForbiddenBlessing     04-28 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Forbidden Blessing,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Biship Directs Boston Parish Not to Bless Same-Sex Couples</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Episcopal parishioners are upset by a bishop's
directive forbidding the formal blessing of same-sex relationships,
a priest said Friday.
   ``The disappointment is that once again it seems that the church
just doesn't seem to be able to extricate itself from cultural
mores,'' said the Rev. Richard Valantasis, co-rector of St. John
the Evangelist Parish. He estimated that about one-third of the
congregation is homosexual.
   The Episcopal Church accepts homosexuals as members, but is
still studying the issues of ordination and blessing, said the Rev.
Bruce G.C. Bayne, chairman of a Massachusetts diocesan commission
on sexuality.
   ``The church's mind is not determined,'' he said.
   The blessing generally is used as a form of church recognition
of an outside marriage, such as a civil ceremony. St. John's clergy
proposed blessing the 15-year relationship of two women, but the
ceremony would have made no reference to marriage, Valantasis said.
   Some Episcopalians have trouble with the concept of endorsing
homosexual unions, said the Rev. Sam Abbott, of St. James's
Episcopal Church in Cambridge.
   ``The fear is that it's a very short step from blessing
relationships to being in a position of saying this is a same-sex
marriage,'' he said.
   Some Episcopal parishes have quietly been extending their
blessing to same-sex couples in Massachusetts for years, Valantasis
said, but in the case of St. John's, rectors proposed the blessing
take place during the sacrament of Eucharist and asked for official
approval.
   David E. Johnson, bishop of the 96,000-member Episcopal diocese
of Massachusetts, responded by letter dated April 20, saying the
blessing would be inappropriate.
   ``We feel that that's another way of being abusive to gay people
... by giving the appearance that nothing is happening,'' said
Valantasis.
   Johnson declined to comment Friday, said diocesan spokesman Jim
Solheim.
   Opponents to endorsing same-sex unions cite biblical passages
condemning homosexuality.
   ``I'm one of those who feels that the church ought to offer
support and concern and compassion to people of whatever lifestyle
but it does seem to me that we can't easily get around the teaching
of the scriptures which do not condone homosexual conduct,'' Abbott
said.
   But Valantasis responded, ``If we take all of those moral
injunctions, then we should also be condemning alcoholics.''
   Parishioner Margaret Miles said most of St. John's approximately
200 members were pleased when Valantasis and co-rector the Rev.
Jennifer Phillips said they were seeking authorization. ``The
congregation, as one person, as far as I could tell, got to their
feet and cheered, which is very unusual,'' she said.
   Miles, the Bussey professor of historical theology at Harvard
Divinity School, said news that the blessing had been stopped was
crushing.
   Valantasis said he and Phillips hope to discuss the issue
further with Johnson.
   ``I think that this is a very volatile issue and it comes to the
sort of heart of our cultural fabric,'' Valantasis said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
