<DOCNO> AP890428-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 1740EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     04-28 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N., South African Officials Disagree on Number of Namibian Guerrillas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAHM VENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. and South African officials
disagree about how many nationalist guerrillas remain in Namibia
despite orders to withdraw, a South African diplomat said Friday.
   Neil van Heerden, director-general of the Foreign Affairs
Department, said South Africa believes 400 guerrillas still are in
Namibia, while officials of the U.N. monitoring force put the
figure at 200.
   Cedric Thornberry, second-in-command of the U.N. monitoring
force in Namibia, said only that ``substantial numbers'' of
guerrillas have left northern Namibia since Wednesday.
   South Africa has suggested the timetable for the entire U.N.
peace plan could be affected if it cannot verify that all
guerrillas have withdrawn after an ill-fated incursion that
threatened to derail Namibia's transition to independence.
   Van Heerden said between 850 and 1,000 guerrillas of the
South-West Africa Peope's Organization have returned to Angola on
orders of their exiled leaders. South Africa, which has agreed to
end its 74-year rule over Namibia, says about 1,600 guerrillas
infiltrated from Angola starting April 1, and that 305 guerrillas
and 27 security forces were killed in fighting after that.
   Under a regional peace plan signed last year by South Africa,
Angola and Cuba, the guerrillas were to remain at thir bases in
Angola until mid-May, when they were to return unarmed. The
guerrilla organization is not a signatory to the agreement and
denies it violated the accord.
   To encourage the guerrillas' withdrawal, South Africa has
confined its forces in northern Namibia to their bases for a
60-hour period ending at dawn Saturday.
   South African, Angolan and Cuban negotiators, meeting in Cape
Town with U.S. and Soviet observers, agreed Friday to a 14-day
verification period starting Saturday. During this period, South
African and U.N. officials will try to confirm that all SWAPO
guerrillas have moved at least 100 miles inside Angola.
   If a full SWAPO pullout is verified, van Heerden said, South
African forces will return to their bases May 13 and efforts will
be made to resume the transition without delays to a U.N. timetable
calling for elections in November.
   A SWAPO statement Thursday said 1,337 guerrillas had
``redeployed'' from Namibia to Angola. It did not specify the
period during which the withdrawal occurred, nor say how many
guerrillas remain in Namibia.
   SWAPO said its guerrillas ``have been running the gauntlet of
South Africa troops' ambushes.''
   All guerrillas in Namibia soon will move to Angola, provided
security forces ``do not impede their way,'' it said.
   The independence plan is part of an agreement that also calls
for Cuba to withdraw 50,000 troops from Angola, where they have
supported the Marxist government's fight against right-wing rebels
backed by the United States and South Africa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
