<FIRST>r w AM-Sununu-Rates 1stLd-Writethru a0675 04-28 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sununu-Rates, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0675,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Staff Chief Warns Against Higher Interest Rates</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts ``he'' in graf 2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House Chief of Staff John Sununu warned
on Friday that higher interest rates could ``scrunch down'' the
economy.
   ``It is a consumer issue to be worried about interest rates,''
as well as tax increases and international trade, Sununu told a
luncheon of Consumer Alert, a conservative group he once headed.
   Sununu claimed for the Bush administration the achievement of
keeping the economic recovery going, saying: ``This economy is
strong, it is robust, and it will continue to thrive as long as we
don't adopt policies to scrunch it down.''
   ``Those policies,'' he added, ``include interest rates. Those of
you who are wise consumers understand that when you go to buy a car
or a house or anything that requires you as a consumer to pay over
a long period of time, one of the most critical aspects of whether
or not it's a good deal for you is the rate of interest you will
have to pay on the purchase.''
   President Bush has said that he does not want the Federal
Reserve Board, an independent body, to concentrate so hard on
fighting inflation that it tips the economy into a recession.
   The Fed has strong influence over interest rates through its
control of the money supply, largely exercised through purchases
and sales of government bonds, through rates it charges for use of
its funds, and through other regulations.
   Fed credit policies are made public only with a time lag. The
policy-making Open Market Committee decided in February not to
increase rates further for the moment, but two weeks after that
meeting the Fed raised by one-half percentage point to 7 percent
the rate it charges member banks for funds.
   The most recent figures show the economy expanding at an annual
rate of 3 percent during the first three months of the year, and
inflation as measured by consumer prices increasing at an annual
rate of 6.1 percent during the first quarter, the highest rate in
two years.
   Sununu said the budget agreement with Congress would bring a
deficit reduction of $65 billion to $75 billion, and economic
growth if it continues at the current rate would add $85 billion a
year to federal revenue next year and the year after without new
taxes.
   ``Compare that to what alternatives that are being proposed. One
of the alternatives is a gasoline tax (increase),'' he said.
   ``I think you all remember what happened when we had significant
increases in gasoline prices in the late '70s. Our economy was
stifled. ... If you want to match what you can get out of growth
with a gasoline tax that would inhibit growth, you would have to be
looking at an 85-cent per gallon increase.
   ``I can't imagine anyone advocating such a policy and getting
away with being called a consumerist, and yet there are those who
are trying to do that.'' He did not say who he had in mind.
   ``As a consumer you certainly worry about having competitive
products in the market, and it is a consumer issue to have a strong
commitment to free trade that allows competitive products to come
in here,'' Sununu said.
   ``And I think one of the most difficult consumer issues to deal
with emotionally is the trade issue. Because sometimes the first
reaction, the emotional reaction of exclusion, is not one in the
best interests of consumer or the country,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
