<FIRST>r a AM-FossilsStolen     04-28 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fossils Stolen,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rare Ancient Fish Fossils Stolen From Bradley University</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two priceless fish fossils, estimated to be
300 million years old, are missing from a Bradley University
display case and officials said Friday they may have been stolen
for a private collector.
   Merrill Foster, chairman of the geological sciences department
at Bradley, said he discovered the theft Tuesday. Police are
investigating.
   ``We use them for educational purposes so we don't want to keep
them locked away in a vault,'' Foster said.
   Stolen were the remains of a ``jawless fish'' related to the
lamprey family, and the remains of a bony, ray-finned fish. The two
fossils were imbedded on four small pieces of rock.
   Foster said they were the rarest and most valuable specimens in
Bradley's collection, which numbers in the hundreds of thousands of
fossils.
   Jawless fish were prehistoric ancestors of contemporary fish and
are thought to have evolved from sand-dwelling filter feeders about
450 million years ago, Foster said. A similar jawless fish fossil
was stolen from the Chicago Field Museum about 10 years ago, he
said.
   Foster said the Bradley theft appeared to be the work of experts
who pried open a jewelry-type glass display case.
   ``This was not your normal snatch thief,'' he said. ``To the
average thief in Peoria, these fossils are worthless. These were
stolen by someone who really knows fossils well.''
   Dave Reinertsen, senior staff geologist for the Illinois State
Geological Survey, said collectors often buy and sell fossils
through ads in mineral supply catalogs.
   ``There's a market for it,'' Reinertsen said. ``But if it's that
rare, I suspect (it) was snagged for a private collection.''
</TEXT>
