<FIRST>r a AM-KMartExplosion     04-28 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-K Mart Explosion,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Victim Of Pipe Bomb Explosion Happy To Be Home, Mother Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN HUDDLESTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 5-year-old girl whose hand was mutilated
in a pipe bomb explosion at a K mart store last week was glad to be
home Friday and the family was anxious to ``get on with our lives.''
   ``She's doing very well,'' Maureen Bower said shortly after her
daughter, Erin, was released from Methodist Hospital. ``She wants
to be home. She was getting restless.''
   Erin was injured April 17 when a pipe bomb concealed in a
pump-style toothpaste container exploded as she picked it up off
the store's shelf.
   Surgeons could not salvage her maimed left hand, which was
amputated the day after the explosion. On Tuesday, the lens was
removed from the child's left eye, which also was hit in the blast.
Doctors hope some sight will be regained in the eye.
   ``I'm just glad we have our little girl,'' Mrs. Bower said.
``She doesn't have a hand, but she's ours and she's got her same
personality back. She's going to be fine. I've just got to keep
telling myself that. We've got to get on with our lives.''
   Erin was expected to spend the week resting at home before
returning to her kindergarten classes.
   Meanwhile, more than 20 investigators working on the case
continued to track down leads.
   In Terre Haute, two men matching the descriptions of those
sought for questioning were interviewed by the FBI and the federal
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms. The two were released
later after questioning.
   Charles A. Petersen, agent in charge of the Indianapolis ATF
bureau, said the two were not suspects.
   ``We're just continuing the investigation in our normal
manner,'' said Petersen. ``We're just out hitting the pavement,
following up what leads we have and trying to find new ones.''
</TEXT>
