<FIRST>r w AM-HUDAudit     04-28 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD Audit,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Administrator Calls Investigative Report Misleading</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former administrator of a federal housing
program faulted for mismanagement and favoritism defended his
actions Friday and said an agency investigative report was
misleading.
   Thomas T. Demery, former assistant secretary of the Department
of Housing and Urban Development and former federal housing
commissioner, acknowledged documentation was lacking from the
process that awarded HUD contracts for rehabilitation of low-income
housing projects.
   But Demery said no favoritism was used to select winners, and
that he and then-Secretary Samuel R. Pierce Jr. instituted more
formal and documented procedures for awarding contracts beginning
this year, shortly before both left the department.
   HUD Secretary Jack Kemp, meanwhile, told a group of state
legislators Friday that the program ``was being abused by
consultants and some folks who were making a phone call and getting
a federal grant.''
   Kemp shut down the program temporarily this week following
release of an investigative report by the HUD inspector general and
blocked some $100 million in pending contracts, subject to a new
review of the program.
   The report charged no criminal activity, but the HUD inspector
general turned it over to the Justice Department for review.
   The report described how former Reagan administration figures,
including former top HUD officials, and other Republicans collected
big fees as consultants and in some cases became developers on
projects to rehabilitate subsidized apartments for the poor.
   Kemp said the report showed the program's selections were
``based on the perception and reality of favoritism and abuse of
non-public information.''
   Demery, in a telephone interview, said the large number of
former HUD officials revealed to be involved in projects as
developers or consultants after leaving government could be
explained because they had developed special knowledge in a narrow,
highly technical program.
   ``If they won those contracts, it wasn't because of inside
information,'' Demery said.
   Demery handled applications for contracts under the program and
was a member of a three-person selection committee that awarded
winning projects.
   The investigative report by HUD Inspector General Paul Adams
questioned the role of Demery, who was responsible for the program
beginning in October 1986. It said a non-profit charity, FOOD for
Africa, which Demery headed before joining HUD, received $290,000
from individuals and firms involved with HUD programs administered
by Demery.
   Demery said there was no connection between the charity and his
administration of the program. He said $50,000 of the contributions
came before he assumed responsibility for the program. And he
charged the inspector general had included contributions from
people and companies involved in HUD programs other than the
renovation program.
   ``It is a totally inappropriate presentation of facts,'' Demery
said. ``It's unconscionable the way he's tried to mix apples and
oranges and call them something else. ... What's the point except
to mislead?''
   Adams declined to respond to Demery's comments. ``The report
speaks for itself,'' Adams said.
   Pierce, HUD secretary throughout the Reagan administration, did
not return a reporter's call.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
