<FIRST>r w AM-Stealth-Fighter     04-28 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stealth-Fighter,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trade Magazine Says Stealth Fighter Flying During Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force, which last November
acknowledged that it had been flying the stealth fighter at night
for five years, has started operating the F-117A jets during the
day, said a report published Friday.
   Aviation Week and Space Technology reported in its May 1 edition
that over the past two weeks, as many as 20 stealth fighters have
been spotted over Mojave, Calif., near Edwards Air Force Base.
   The weekly magazine published a grainy color photograph of an
airborne F-117A, but it was far less detailed than a picture
released by the Air Force last November when it acknowledged the
existence of the airplane for the first time.
   More than 50 of the swept-wing twin engine warplanes are
stationed at the Tonopah Test Range Air Field in Nevada. They are
attached to the 4450th Tactical Air Group at Nellis Air Force Base,
the Air Force said in statement last Nov. 10.
   Capt. Susan Strednansky, an Air Force spokeswoman at the
Pentagon, said she had no information about daylight flights of the
F-117A, but noted that the November announcement signaled that such
operations were imminent.
   ``Daytime flights have been available to them since we released
their existence,'' said Strednansky. ``If you fly it only at night,
you cannot integrate it into the rest of the Air Force.''
   Fifty-nine stealth fighters are being purchased from the
Lockheed Corp. at an undisclosed price, she said.
   Aviation Week, quoting unidentified residents of Mojave, said
the fighters were flying what appeared to be training missions at
5:30 p.m. and 10:30 p.m.
   Local residents, many of whom are aerospace workers, say the
F-117A makes an unsual noise, ``a distinctive, although faint,
engine whine'' that the magazine said may be caused by an unusal
design to the air intake.
   The stealth fighter, like the B-2 stealth bomber now under
development, is triangular in shape and incorporates design
features and material intended to make it all but invisible to
enemy targeting radar. The trailing edge of the wings is sawtooth
in shape, to avoid presenting right-angles to enemy radar, Aviation
Week reported.
   When the Air Force disclosed the existence of the F-117A last
November, it said the plane was first flown in June 1981 and had
been in operation since 1983.
</TEXT>
