<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 1658EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>b w BC-JapanFighter 2ndLd-Writethru a0694 04-28 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan Fighter, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0694,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Top 6 grafs with additional details; picks up 6th graf pvs, ``Congressional
sources xxx''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush intends to go ahead with the
controversial FSX fighter deal with Japan after reaching agreement
with Tokyo on conditions to safeguard sensitive technology and
guarantee a share of production for American companies,
congressional sources said Friday.
   Bush was scheduled to make a formal announcement in the White
House briefing room before the end of the day.
   The project is controversial because critics say it would give
U.S. aviation technology to Japan and hurt America's competitive
advantage.
   Bush had deliberated for many weeks on the proposed deal for
joint U.S.-Japanese production of the new fighter plane, an
advanced version of the U.S.-built F-16. The plane would be built
by General Dynamics and Japan's Mitsubishi Heavy Industries.
   The president had said previously he wanted to go ahead with the
joint venture as long as the agreement would safeguard U.S.
technology.
   Congress will have 30 days to review the agreement before it is
finalized.
   The deal was complicated this week by Japanese Prime Minister
Noburu Takeshita's announcement that he would resign because of the
influence peddling scandal that has paralyzed his government.
   Congressional sources, who spoke on condition they not be
identified, said the Japanese government had agreed to ensure that
40 percent of the estimated $5 billion production run on the plane
will be handled in the United States.
   The Japanese had already agreed to give U.S. companies a 40
percent share of the FSX's estimated $1.2 billion development work.
   On another key point, the congressional sources said, the
Japanese agreed to U.S. requests for protection of sensitive source
codes used for computers aboard the plane.
   The Reagan administration negotiated the arrangement initially
after Japan refused to buy any U.S. F-16 fighters and indicated it
would build its own fighter plane.
   Bush said last month that he would send Congress a modified
version of the Reagan administration agreement.
   Sources have said that among the assurances U.S. officials were
insisting on were an expanded role for the Commerce Department to
monitor the project and keep track of Japanese compliance.
   Reports from Tokyo earlier Friday said the agreement was near on
the project as the Defense Agency decided to retract its demand
that more than 50 percent of engine production work be given to
Japan and that Japan receive all computer software for flight
control of the U.S. F-16, which is the basis for the FSX jet.
   Backers of the venture say the project is a way to add fighters
to Japan's inventory in strategic northeast Asia at Tokyo's
expense. It also would provide jobs for the United States, and give
Washington access to sophisticated radar technology developed by
Japan.
   Under the FSX arrangement, St. Louis-based General Dynamics is
to join forces with Japan's Mitsubishi Heavy Industries to develop
and manufacture the next-generation fighter for deployment by Japan
in the late 1990s.
   Proponents have argued that the agreement represents the best
deal the United States could negotiate in the face of Japanese
opposition to buying F-16s directly from the United States. They
say the deal will serve to promote beneficial technology transfer
in both directions while generating income and jobs for U.S.
industry.
   Critics, however, contend that the arrangement amounts to a
giveaway of advanced technology that Japan may use to help propel
the its civilian aircraft industry into head-to-head competition
with the United States in the world market. They say Tokyo should
purchase American-made planes to help offset the $50 billion U.S.
trade deficit with Japan.
   In the face of congressional opposition, the Bush administration
conducted an interagency review culminating in heated Cabinet-level
meetings that pitted the Commerce Department and U.S. Trade
Representative against the Pentagon and State Department, which had
negotiated the FSX deal.
   As a result of these meetings, Bush sought ``clarifications''
from the Japanese to help safeguard sensitive technology and ensure
a share of the plane's production for U.S. industry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
