<FIRST>r w AM-Appointments     04-28 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Appointments,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Diplomatic To Head US Foreign Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edward J. Perkins, a veteran black diplomat
now serving as U.S. ambassador to South Africa, will head the U.S.
foreign service, and Morris Busby, a specialist on Central America,
is to be the State Department's anti-terrorism chief, U.S.
officials said Friday.
   Perkins will succeed George S. Vest, 70, the department's senior
foreign service officer who is retiring next Wednesday. Perkins,
60, was sent to Pretoria by former President Reagan in 1986 in an
effort to demonstrate U.S. interest in bridging the gap between
blacks and whites in the country.
   He previously was U.S. ambassador to Liberia and director of
West African affairs at the department.
   Busby was named special envoy for Central America in 1987 and
has traveled extensively in the region to bolster U.S. ties to
Costa Rica, El Salvador, Guatemala and Honduras. He will succeed L.
Paul Bremer, who is leaving the foreign service to join a
consulting firm operated by former Secretary of State Henry A.
Kissinger.
   The appointment of Perkins, which requires Senate confirmation,
symbolizes the rise through diplomatic ranks of a new breed of
foreign service officer outside the traditional mold of white Ivy
Leaguers. The proportion of women and blacks has been on the rise
for several years.
   Perkins served in the Far East and Africa, and in the State
Department's Near East and South Asian bureau. He is a graduate of
the University of Maryland and the University of Southern
California and speaks Thai, French and Japanese.
   The job of director-general will put him in charge of all
personnel activities in the department and in the foreign service
worldwide. This includes recruiting, hiring, assignments, promotion
and discharge.
   He will report directly to Secretary of State James A. Baker III.
   Vest, who has served for 49 years, including World War II
military duty, calls it ``a wonderful job.''
   ``I deal with every human problem there is,'' he said in a brief
interview.
   Vest described Perkins as ``a fantastic professional, first and
last'' and said ``he will be a marvelous director of the foreign
service.''
   Vest is a former U.S. ambassador to the North Atlantic Treaty
Organzation and the European Community and also served as a
spokesman for Kissinger.
   Busby, whose nomination also requires Senate confirmation, will
be in charge of efforts at the department to counter terrorism.
</TEXT>
