<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Panama     04-28 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Panama,0646</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panama Tells U.N. Washington Plots Armed Intervention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama's foreign minister accused the
United States on Friday of subversion and plotting military
intervention, and the U.S. ambassador retorted that Panamanian
elections next week are rigged and a fraud.
   Foreign Minister Jorge Ritter excoriated the U.S. government at
an emergency meeting of the Security Council requested by Panama,
saying Washington was trying to bully and intimidate his nation.
   U.S. Ambassador Thomas R. Pickering, the permanent
representative, rejected the allegations and said, ``The moral
bankruptcy of the regime of Gen. Manuel Noriega for which Mr.
Ritter speaks is well known.''
   Noriega is armed forces chief and as such, de facto leader of
Panama.
   Pickering accused Panama's government of blatantly interfering
in the election process; manipulating voters' lists; muzzling the
opposition, press and TV, and restricting access by impartial
foreign monitors and journalists.
   The meeting was adjourned after the Panamanian and U.S.
speeches. No action was taken and no further meeting was scheduled.
   Ritter said the United States has supplied millions of dollars
to opposition candidates opposing Noriega and has sent commandos,
special weapons and helicopters to that Central American nation
right before elections May 7.
   He accused the United States of trying to subvert democratic
elections, set up a puppet, pro-Washington government and undermine
the Panama Canal Treaty.
   ``U.S. plans of interfering in the Panamanian electoral process
have entered a phase of direct participation,'' Ritter told the
15-member council.
   ``The objective is undermining public order, causing chaos,
promoting widespread destabilization in the country around election
time and creating a pretext for military intervention in Panama.''
   He said U.S. intervention was jeopardizing regional peace and
security.
   In February 1988, Noriega was indicted on federal drug charges
in Florida. He denied the charges. The United States imposed
economic sanctions against Panama, trying to force out Noriega.
   Ritter also complained that Pickering did not address the
specific complaint that the U.S. government was sending special
arms and making non-defensive military preparations in Panama as a
prelude to using force.
   He referred to a statement Thursday by Bush, who said the
Noriega-controlled government is committing systematic fraud and is
employing violence and coercion to intimidate Panamanian citizens
who believe in democracy.
   Pickering said, ``We are discussing Panama before the Security
Council because the regime will not permit a free and open debate
to take place among the Panamanian people. The solution to Panama's
lack of democracy does not lie here in the Security Council, but in
Panama.''
   He said Panama's crisis stemmed not from any U.S. plot to
interfere, but from ``the policies of Gen. Noriega, who has
arrogated to himself complete power over civic life and sponsored
and countenanced widescale corruption, drug trafficking and
gun-running.''
   The ambassador said the United States has grave doubts about the
honesty of Panama's election process. The human rights commission
of the Organization of American States also expressed concern about
``extensive irregularities'' interfering in free elections,
Pickering said.
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler
said Friday that through ``manipulation and intimidation the
Noriega regime is making it extremely difficult for international
observers to perform their functions.
   ``We hope that despite the many roadblocks which Noriega is
putting in their way, observers will go to Panama to see and tell
the truth about what is going on there.
   She expressed hope that Panama will let former Presidents Jimmy
Carter and Gerald Ford monitor the elections there. Panamanian
officials have said they would be welcome.
   Noriega is backing Carlos Alberto Duque for president against
Guillermo Endara of the opposition Democratic Alliance. Endara
denied that his campaign received U.S. funds.
   Voters will also choose two vice presidents, 67 asembly
representatives and 510 local representatives.
</TEXT>
