<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Taxes     04-28 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Taxes,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Touts No New Taxes for Now, But Concedes `Long Way to Go' in
1991</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Friday touted his adherence
to his ``no new taxes'' pledge for 1990 but conceded that ``we
still have a ways to go'' to bring the deficit in line with
mandated Gramm-Rudman targets for the following year.
   Bush, in comments to the American Legislative Exchange Council,
said that ``rough times lie ahead'' for his administration on the
economy.
   He praised his budget agreement with congressional leaders for
meeting the deficit-reduction target of the Gramm-Rudman law for
the 1990 fiscal year. While the agreement has $5.3 billion in
unspecified new revenues, Bush has said those won't be new taxes.
   ``And I kept that `no new taxes' pledge,'' Bush added. ``But we
still have a ways to go because we've got to go move dramatically
down in the next fiscal year to meet the Gramm-Rudman targets which
I'm determined to do. And that does mean we have to have fiscal
restraint in a lot of areas where, very candidly, I wish we could
do more.''
   Bush's no-new-taxes pledge was a campaign rallying cry that many
critics say will be impossible to live up to for another year and
still reduce the budget deficit below the ceiling set by the
Gramm-Rudman legislation.
   Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater, asked later if Bush was
hinting that he might entertain some backing away from the no-taxes
vow, said, ``I don't interpret that as any hints of any changes.''
   Asked whether the president might go along with congressional
Democrats and approve tax increases a few months down the line,
Fitzwater said Bush was looking at all future budget decisions
carefully, and that as the next Gramm-Rudman target approaches
``Clearly those decisions will be even tougher in terms of '91 and
'92.''
   ``We have brought the deficit down steadily from something like
$212 billion to $150 (billion) and now to $100 (billion), but it's
clear that the last 100 is going to be very difficult.''
   Fitzwater said, however, that Bush was vowing to keep his
non-new-taxes pledge in 1990.
   Bush also reiterated that he will not ``cave in'' on his
proposal to raise the minimum wage to $4.25 an hour and to tie it
to a lower six-month training wage. Congressional negotiators are
now working on a proposal to increase the minimum wage to $4.55 an
hour with a more restrictive two-month training wage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
