<FIRST>r w AM-Corn-Soviets     04-28 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Corn-Soviets,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Buy Additional Corn</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has bought an additional 1.05
million metric tons of U.S. corn for delivery this year under a
long-term supply agreement, the Agriculture Department said Friday.
   Officials said the latest corn sales by unidentified private
exporters pushed the total grain bought by the Soviets this year to
almost 18.3 million tons, close to the record 18.6 million tons
Moscow purchased from the United States in 1984-85. Corn makes up
about 14.3 million tons and wheat 4 million.
   The corn is scheduled for delivery by Sept. 30, the end of the
sixth year of a long-term grain supply agreement between the Soviet
Union and the United States.
   Additionally, the department said 1988-89 sales to the Soviets
include about 450,000 tons of soybeans, 1.4 million tons of soybean
meal, and 607,400 tons of grain sorghum.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 1.05 million tons
of corn would be about 41 million bushels.
   Corn prices have been averaging about $2.53 per bushel at the
farm level, according to the latest USDA five-day average, meaning
that the latest sale could have a farm value of more than $100
million.
</TEXT>
