<FIRST>u i AM-China-Newspaper     04-28 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Newspaper,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper `Reorganized' Under Propaganda Official</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's most liberal newspaper, the Shanghai
World Economic Herald, resumed publication Friday after Shanghai's
city government fired chief editor Qin Benli and replaced him with
a propagandist, Chinese sources said.
   The weekly is widely read by Chinese intellectuals and students.
The city forced it to stop distribution of its April 24 edition and
remove articles it said were likely to cause ``disturbances.''
   Liu Ji, a senior propaganda official, replaced Qin after Qin
refused to comply, saying it would constitute undue official
control of the press, the sources said.
   The original issue carried six pages of articles and speeches
honoring the late Hu Yaobang, said an editor at the newspaper's
Beijing bureau.
   ``The items the government said were likely to cause
disturbances have been taken out,'' he said.
   The excised articles apparently asked the party to revise its
assessment of Hu, who was ousted as Communist Party chief after
failing to crack down on student demonstrations in 1986-87.
   Hu's death on April 15 touched off major protests by students
demanding democratic reforms.
   Journalists at several major dailies have shown support for the
Herald.
   China's state-controlled press has moved gradually toward
independence in its reporting on economic policies and news, but
criticism of senior leaders, questioning Communist one-party rule
or delving into sensitive subjects such as unrest in Tibet are
off-limits.
</TEXT>
