<FIRST>r a AM-ForestFire 1stLd-Writethru a0664 04-28 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Forest Fire, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0664,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede TALLAHASSEE, Fla.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Forest Fires in Florida, New York</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout to include forest fire in New York. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A wildfire in Florida burned 4,000 to 6,000 acres of the Osceola
National Forest on Friday, sending smoke 45 miles to Jacksonville,
and 7,000 acres burned in a week-old fire in southeastern New York.
   ``It's still burning uncontained,'' said Scott Enos, supervisor
of the Florida Division of Forestry in Lake City. ``We don't expect
any relief from the weather before Monday.''
   Westerly winds carried the smoke and the National Weather
Service warned of dense smoke in Jacksonville over the weekend
unless the fire is brought under control. Enos said the smoke was
not blowing over major highways.
   The U.S. Forest Service said 100 firefighters were fighting the
blaze in Pinhook Swamp, 23 miles northeast of Lake City.
   Enos said no structures have been damaged, and there have been
no injuries.
   The origin of the fire, which began Thursday, was under
investigation. It began on land adjacent to the forest owned by a
subsidiary of Container Corp.
   High winds, low humidity and dry brush and trees hampered
firefighters' efforts in New York.
   Capt. Raymond Wood, regional forest ranger for the state
Depatment of Environmental Conservation in New Paltz, compared this
spring's stubborn blazes in Orange and Rockland counties to the
vast fires that burned for much of last summer in the western
United States.
   Wood said the presence of two superhighways in the region, the
New York state Thruway and Palisades Interstate Parkway, have been
key to preventing even more extensive burning.
   ``I think that if it had not been for the Parkway and the
Thruway, these things just would have kept getting bigger and
bigger,'' he said. ``It's just like out west, you do everything
humanly possible and the fire does what it wants anyway.''
   Paul Rinaldi, a DEC forest ranger in New Paltz, said the fire
had burned about 3,000 acres of timber.
   ``The burning conditions are absolutely right, just
incredible,'' Rinaldi said. ``We're not getting the humidity or the
rain so everything is very dry. ... We're seeing fires that are
jumping bulldozer lines, macadam roads _ it's beyond belief.''
</TEXT>
