<FIRST>u i AM-Senegal-Mauritania 1stLd-Writethru   04-28 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senegal-Mauritania, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0695,0560</SECOND>
<HEAD>20 Mauritanians Reported Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with plane forced to leave without
refugees. Pick up 10th pvs, `According to...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAKAR, Senegal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senegalese angered by violence against
their countrymen in neighboring Mauritania attacked Mauritanians in
Dakar on Friday, killing at least 20 people, officials said.
   Authorities in Senegal, in an order broadcast by state radio,
declared a state of emergency in the capital and a curfew from 10
p.m. to 6 a.m., to be in effect for at least six days. Under the
state of emergency, all public and private gatherings are banned.
   The violence began this month in dispute over land near the
border between the West African nations. Reports say more than 150
people have been killed.
   Several thousand Senegalese assembled Friday around the hospital
at Grand-Yoff on the outskirts of Dakar, where survivors of the
violence in Mauritania were being treated after being flown home.
   Police used tear gas to try to break up the mob, but the
officials said on condition of anonymity that at least 20
Mauritanians were killed.
   President Abdou Diouf was among the Senegalese who visited the
hospital, but reporters said he broke down in tears and cut short
his visit.
   Among the 281 people being treated, some had their sex organs or
limbs mutilated, and most of the corpses brought home had been
decapitated, the reporters with the president said.
   Word of the nature of the injuries enraged the crowd, which then
went seeking Mauritanians, many of whose homes and shops had been
burned or looted this week.
   A few hundred Mauritanians were flown home to Nouakchott after
the earlier violence, but many others had been gathered at the
Dakar fairgrounds to await repatriation. Many of the angry
Senegalese headed to the fairgrounds in search of vengeance.
   Mauritania's ambassador to Dakar, Mokhtar Ould Zamel, said a An
Air Mauritanie plane that arrived Friday afternoon to take about 80
people home was forced to leave more than half of them behind when
Senegalese attacked the passengers.
   He said airport authorities urged the plane to take off without
the others because its presence was considered a provocation.
   The French news agency Agence France-Presse quoted what it said
was a good source in Dakar as saying Senegalese planes were denied
permission to fly to Mauritania to pick up refugees, apparently in
response to the airport incident in Senegal.
   According to news reports in Dakar, between 150 and 200 people,
both Mauritanians and Senegalese, were killed by mobs on Monday and
Tuesday in Nouakchott and Nouadhibou, the second largest city in
Mauritania.
   The government in Nouakchott said it had no official casualty
report, but a source in the capital's main public hospital said 26
people died there and 675 others were treated for injuries. Others
may have died at other hospitals or clinics, he said.
   The government of Senegal declared it has the right to respond
by any measures necessary if it is established that Mauritanian
forces were responsible for killing Senegalese.
   The violence was spawned by a land dispute along the river
separating the countries. Two Senegalese, accused of farming
illegally on Mauritanian land, were shot April 9. Sporadic attacks
on Mauritanians in Senegal blew up into widespread attacks,
sparking retaliation.
</TEXT>
