<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Georgia     04-28 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Georgia,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Suggests Protesters to Blame for Georgia Deaths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Interior Ministry's political
department, A.I. Grienko, suggested Friday that Georgian
demonstrators were responsible for violence that cost lives at a
pro-independence protest on April 9.
   Grienko told Soviet journalists that troops try not to use force
to break up demonstrations, but the protest in the Georgian
capital, Tbilisi, was not peaceful.
   At least 19 people were killed when troops wielding shovels and
clubs, firing gas and riding armored personnel carriers and tanks
moved in on the demonstration outside Government House in downtown
Tbilisi. At least one more person was shot and killed later for
violating a curfew.
   Georgian activists contend the troops brutally moved in without
warning and attacked peaceful demonstrators.
   Grienko said ministry troops display ``the highest
professionalism, so there won't be victims from any of our actions.
... But that doesn't depend on us, because two sides are acting.''
   He said the soldiers try to obey the law, respect people and be
fair, but ``unfortunately, they don't always manage to do this''
because of opposing forces.
   Grienko's remarks were broadcast on Soviet television's evening
news broadcast ``Vremya.''
   Also on the program, deputy Soviet prosecutor Alexander F.
Katusev said four Georgian activists arrested shortly after the
demonstration were charged with being ``organizers of, and active
participants in group actions violating public order.''
   Katusev said military prosecutors are investigating whether use
of gases to put down the demonstration was proper, and what the 19
protesters died of. Most of those killed were women.
   Soviet officials acknowledged that soldiers used tear gas.
Members of a citizen's commission investigating the confrontation
and doctors treating victims say a second gas that paralyzes the
central nervous system was used. Georgia's Communist Party chief,
Givi Gumbaridze, said some victims died of gas poisoning.
</TEXT>
