<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua     04-28 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Frees Four Accused Of Spying For CIA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three men and a woman accused of
spying for the CIA and held for months were freed Friday after an
appeals court overturned their convictions.
   They had been given prison sentences ranging from three years to
16 years.
   International human rights groups had protested the trials held
in May and June, 1988, claiming they were political trials.
   Three were released from the La Modelo prison outside Managua,
and they were met by their lawyers and weeping relatives. All
declared again their innocence.
   ``If I had been a CIA agent they would never have released me,''
said economist Mario Alegria. He had been accused of organizing a
network among government employees to provide economic data to the
U.S. Central Intelligence Agency.
   Alegria's lawyer, Hernaldo Zuniga, said the appeals court
accepted the argument he and the other defense attorneys had
presented: that none of the laws applicable in the case defined
what a ``secret document'' is and the economic information involved
was public knowlege and not secret.
   Nora Aldana, who had been a planning specialist with the
Agriculture Ministry, told The Associated Press she found out about
the appeals court ruling about an hour before she was allowed to
leave the prison. She was met by her mother and oldest daughter.
   ``Inside, I always knew I had done nothing wrong,'' said Ms.
Aldana, 45.
   Adrian Espinales wiped tears from his eyes and hugged relatives
after leaving La Modelo.
   ``I have always said I am innocent,'' said Espinales who worked
at the Ministry of Interior. ``I did not commit any crime.''
   Pedro Pablo Su, was released from another prison near Managua.
He had been employed at the Central Bank when he was arrested.
   Alegria and Ms. Aldana had been given prison sentences of 16
years and Espinales and Su were sentenced to three years.
   Zuniga said that in its ruling the appeals court asked the
Supreme Court to ``define what is in fact a `secret document'.''
   Also on Friday a Foreign Ministry official said President Daniel
Ortega, on a 10-nation tour of Western Europe, is seeking support
for the normalization of relations between Nicaragua and the United
States.
   Manolo Cordero, director of the Foreign Ministry's North
American desk, said Ortega will ask British and West German leaders
to help persuade the Bush administration to restore normal
relations with the Sandinista government.
   Cordero told a news conference President Bush appears more
responsive to change than the Reagan administration and it is now
worthwhile to try new avenues to improve relations.
   Ortega has visited France, Belgium, Spain and Norway and plans
stops in Greece, Italy, Sweden, Ireland, West Germany and Great
Britain.
   Julio Icaza, another Foreign Ministry official, also spoke to
reporters Friday.
   He said the renewal of the U.S. trade embargo means Nicaragua
``must look for alternatives, like talks with donor governments''
at a meeting next month in Sweden.
   Last week Bush announced the embardo would be continued. He said
the left-wing Sandinista government represents ``an extraordinary
threat'' to U.S. security.
   The Reagan administration imposed the sanctions in 1985.
</TEXT>
