<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-28 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow Dusts West; Rain Drenches Much Of The Country</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow dusted much of the West on Friday and hail the size of golf
balls pummeled parts of the South while much of the nation was
drenched with rain.
   Snow was scattered over southeast and southwest Montana, central
Idaho, much of Wyoming and western South Dakota on Friday
afternoon. Cold temperatures and snow flurries were forecast in
western and north-central Nebraska through Saturday.
   Rain fell across eastern South Dakota, central and southern
Minnesota, northern Iowa and Wisconsin on Friday.
   Showers and occasional thunderstorms extended over southern
Illinois, as well as from Indiana across Ohio, West Virginia,
eastern Kentucky, eastern Tennessee, northern Georgia, the Florida
Panhandle and across the upper half of the Texas Gulf Coast.
   Hail as large as golf balls pounded areas near Ward, Ark., Trout
Creek, Texas, Lake City and Monette, Tenn.; and three-quarter inch
hail hit parts of Grand Tower, Ill.Small hail fell early Friday
afternoon at Auburn, Miss.
   The high temperature record in Huntsville, Ala., was broken
Friday with a reading of 86, two degrees above the 1981 record.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 27
degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 94 degrees at Fort
Lauderdale, Fla. The low temperature for the nation Friday morning
was 8 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   The national weather forecast for Saturday called for rain from
Montana across Wyoming, South Dakota, Minnesota, Wisconsin and
Illinois; and showers and occasional thunderstorms from lower
Michigan across the lower Great Lakes, from much of New York across
Virginia, the Ohio Valley, the Tennessee Valley, western North
Carolina, much of inland Georgia, Alabama, the Florida Panhandle,
Mississippi and Louisiana.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 40s from Montana across
northern Colorado, the northern half of the Plains, much of
Minnesota, northern Wisconsin and upper Michigan; in the 50s and
60s from New England across New Jersey, over the rest of the Great
Lakes, southeast Minnesota, Iowa, northwest Missouri, Kansas,
Oklahoma, the remainder of the Rockies, the Great Plains, the
northern Plateau and portions of the California coast; near 90 over
the Florida Peninsula; in the 90s through the desert Southwest; and
in the the 70s and 80s throughout the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
