<FIRST>u i AM-Chile     04-28 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pinochet Says He Won't Run For President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Right-wing military President Augusto
Pinochet said Friday he definitely will not run in the Dec. 14
presidential election, but he said he will stay on as commander of
the army.
   Gen. Pinochet, speaking at a news conference after swearing in
two new ministers to his 16-member Cabinet, also proposed limited
changes to the constitution written by the military.
   ``I feel a deep attachment to the constitution,'' Pinochet said,
explaining why he will not run for president.
   The constitution prohibits him from seeking re-election, but
several right-wing groups have insisted in recent months that a
formula be found to allow him to run.
   Pinochet himself previously hinted that he could agree. On
Tuesday, he told a group of labor leaders who asked him to run
again: ``That does not depend on me, but on you. I am prepared for
anything.''
   He stressed that he will hand power to the winner in the
December election, which he was obliged to call after voters in a
referendum last October rejected a military proposal to extend his
term until 1997.
   Pinochet said Friday that after leaving the presidency, he will
remain as commander of the army, which the constitution allows him
to do.
   ``Under the present circumstances, I think that's the position
where I can serve my country best,'' Pinochet said.
   Opposition parties and even some government supporters
repeatedly have criticized Pinochet's decision to remain head of
the army, which has been his power base since he seized power in a
violent 1973 coup.
   Critics said his continuation in the nation's top military
position would threaten the stability of the future civilian
government.
   Pinochet's decision this week to keep Interior Minister Carlos
Caceres was seen by some opposition leaders as an indication that
he was finally accepting the constitutional changes sought by
opposition and pro-government parties.
   But on Friday, he made clear that he is offering only limited
changes. At the news conference, he listed six possible amendments,
far less that those sought by the opposition.
   He said he is prepared to change an article banning Marxism, to
ease the mechanism for future constitutional changes, to drop the
presidential power to disband the lower house of Congress and to
send citizens into exile; to shorten the eight-year presidential
term, and to change the makeup of a powerful military dominated
National Security Council.
   He rejected changes sought by the opposition, including a clause
that makes nine members of the 26-member Senate appointed instead
of elected, and another that prevents the future civilian
government from firing the heads of the three branches of the armed
forces and the national police.
   Pinochet appointed Rene Salame, a chemistry teacher, to replace
Juan Guzman as education minister; and Jorge Lopez, a mining
engineer, to replace Pablo Baraona as minister of mines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
