<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia     04-28 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sihanouk In Thaliand for Talks On Cambodian Conflict</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodian resistance leader Prince
Norodom Sihanouk called Friday for the dissolution of the
Vietnamese-backed government in Cambodia and said the resistance
coalition also would be dissolved.
   Sihanouk arrived in Thailand Friday to hold talks with
representatives of the three-party resistance coalition and is to
go next week to Indonesia, where he may meet with Vice President
Dan Quayle.
   Sihanouk gave no time frame for the dissolution of what he
called the ``illegal'' Cambodian government of Premier Hun Sen but
said the resistance coalition would be dissolved at the same time
``in order to let our people make all decisions on Cambodia.''
   Sihanouk is to spend three days in Thailand and then go to
Indonesia for a meeting with Hun Sen.
   Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas said Thursday that while
in Indonesia, Sihanouk also would meet with Quayle, who is on a
12-day tour of Australia and Southeast Asia.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in December 1978, ousted the radical
Khmer Rouge regime and set up another communist government.
   Vietnam has announced it will withdraw all of its troops from
Cambodia by Sept. 30, and that has added pressure for the Hun Sen
government and resistance leaders to reach an agreement to avoid
further bloodshed.
   The coalition includes Sihanouk supporters, an anti-communist
group and the Khmer Rouge. The strongest of the three, the Khmer
Rouge came to power in the spring of 1975 by defeating the
U.S.-backed Cambodian government and killed more than a million
Cambodians in a purge that continued until the Vitnamese invaded.
   Vietnamese Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach, also in Bangkok,
said Friday that a Chinese official has declared China will halt
its military aid to the resistance groups after Vietnam completes
the troop withdrawal. Thach identified the official only as a vice
minister.
   The Soviet Union has backed Vietnam in the conflict, and China
supported the Khmer Rouge.
   Vietnam has an estimated 50,000-70,000 military personnel in
Cambodia.
   Hun Sen's government has rejected demands that it be dissolved
and has said general elections should be held after the Vietnamese
are out of the country.
   Sihanouk, who went to China after being ousted in a 1970 coup,
said in a written statement released before he arrived in Bangkok
that the Hun Sen government is ``nothing but a creation and
creature of Vietnam'' and ``has no right to organize `general
elections'.''
</TEXT>
