<DOCNO> AP890428-0175 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 2111EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Peru 1stLd-Writethru a0756 04-28 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0756,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>77 Guerillas Killed in Clashes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with more guerrilla deaths, details.
Pick up 7th pvs, `In related...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces killed 77 leftist guerrillas
Friday in two separate attacks in the Andes Mountains and the
jungle, the government said. It was the heaviest day of fighting in
Peru's nine-year insurgency.
   Six soldiers and three university students also were killed,
officials said.
   Also Friday, the officials said more than 6,000 people were
detained in Lima in massive sweeps by police seeking the killers of
leftist congressman Eriberto Arroyo, who was slain Thursday.
   At dawn, troops spotted a column of leftist guerrillas in
uniforms near Molinos, a tiny village 35 miles north of Huancayo,
the government said in a communique.
   In fighting that followed, 62 leftist guerrillas and six
soldiers were killed and 23 soldiers were wounded, it said.
   President Alan Garcia said in a brief radio statement that the
rebels were from the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement, which
endorses a Cuba styled Marxism and has been active since 1984.
   Police also killed 15 Maoist Shining Path guerrillas in fighting
near Santa Rosa, a village in Peru's cocaine-producing jungle 260
miles northeast of Lima.
   The government said drug traffickers supported the rebels in the
clash, but it did not provide further details.
   The casualties Friday marked the highest number of guerrilla
deaths in any single day of fighting during the nine-year
insurgency. Thirty-four Shining Path guerrillas died earlier this
month in two battles with troops in the Amazon jungle.
   More than 900 people have died this year in political violence.
   In related violence, police said the bodies of three students
shot to death Friday by Shining Path guerrillas were found at the
University of Huancayo.
   The region around Huancayo, one of Peru's richest agricultural
zones 140 miles east of Lima, has been a growing focus of rebel
activity for the past three years.
   Both the Mao-inspired Shining Path and the smaller Tupac Amaru
Revolutionary Movement are active in the region. The groups are not
linked.
   Analysts said the guerrillas are seeking to disrupt farming and
isolate the zone to prevent food from reaching coastal Lima,
further agravating an severe economic recession that has already
sparked temporary food shortages.
   Police said 6,407 people were arrested and 1,135 automobiles
were stopped and searched on city streets late Thursday as police
sought the killers of Arroyo, a member of the United Left Party,
the second strongest party in Congress.
   Police have blamed the Shining Path for the killing, but some
members of the United Left, a Marxist coalition, blamed the murder
on on anti-rebel death squad called the Rodrigo Franco Command.
   During previous sweeps, the vast majority of those detained have
been released after proving their identities.
   Analysts said the spreading violence, coupled with Peru's
deepest economic recession of the century, has fomented political
instability and social chaos that have become a threat to Peru's
democracy.
   The Shining Path has been fighting since 1980 to topple the
government.
   The violence has claimed more than 14,000 lives, including
soldiers, police, guerrillas and non-combantants. But most of the
dead have been highland peasants caught in the cross-fire between
government forces and guerrillas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
