<HEAD>Infant Dies From Bomb Blast At American Cultural Institute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUDDY L. GONZALEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 18-month-old girl
died Friday from wounds suffered in the bombing of the
Dominican-American Cultural Institute. Left-wing activists
demonstrated outside the U.S. Embassy.
   Police said Hayde Sanchez Rodriguez was in the institute's
nursery and suffered head wounds in the pipe-bomb explosion
Thursday.
   They said no individual or group has asserted responsiblity for
the bombing of the center, operated jointly by the U.S. and
Dominican governments.
   Groups from five left-wing political groups, led by the
Communist Party, organized the demonstration at the U.S. Embassy on
the 24th anniverasy of the U.S. military intervention in the
Dominican Republic.
   About 50 demonstrators were barred from approaching the embassy
gate by an equal number of riot police. Some demonstrators trampled
on a U.S. flag but there was no violence.
   A statement issued by the demonstration organizers said, ``On
the occasion of another anniversary of the American military
intervention as Dominicans we have the obligation to protest
against this aggression against our sovereignty.''
   Police and military units were assigned to guard the U.S.
Embassy and Consulate and residences of U.S. diplomats. Officials
said 4,000 policemen were reinforcing regular street patrols.
   The elected government of President Juan Bosch was ousted by a
military coup in September 1963, and the armed forces established a
governing junta that ruled until April 1965 when civil war broke
out.
   The United States sent troops into the Caribbean Island on April
28, 1965. Those units were incorporated later into an
inter-American peace force sponsored by the Organization of
American States, and it imposed a truce.
   Elections were held in June 1966, and Joaquin Balaguer defeated
Bosch.
