<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Chandler     04-28 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Chandler,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Services Set Saturday For Federal Judge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Funeral services are scheduled Saturday for
controversial U.S. District Judge Stephen S. Chandler, who went
into semi-retirement 14 years ago after a stormy 32-year career on
the bench.
   Chandler died Thursday at age 89 after a short bout with
pneumonia and a long battle with a bleeding ulcer, his family said.
He had been hospitalized about two weeks.
   Chandler was born Sept. 13, 1899, in Tennessee. He received his
law degree from the University of Kansas in 1922 and was a private
attorney in Oklahoma City when President Franklin Roosevelt put him
on the federal bench in 1943.
   Chandler often feuded with other federal judges. In 1962, he
testified before a U.S. Senate subcommittee that he was afraid of
being poisoned, that his telephone was tapped and that his fellow
judges sometimes cursed him.
   Twice he was removed from hearing multi-million-dollar lawsuits
because of alleged personal interest or alleged bias and prejudice.
He was indicted by a state grand jury in 1965 for allegedly
conspiring to have a road on property he owned paved by the county.
The criminal charge later was dismissed.
   In 1965, the 10th Circuit Judicial Council stripped him of his
powers for a month, contending he was ``unable or unwilling to
discharge efficiently the duties of his office.''
   He was embroiled in a libel suit with one attorney and once
disbarred the U.S. attorney and five other federal attorneys in
Oklahoma City from practicing in the federal court.
   A state court once ordered Chandler to pay a $50,000 libel
judgment to an attorney the judge accused of a $1 million fraud in
a bankruptcy case. The verdict was overturned in federal appeals
courts.
   In 1974, Chandler disbarred U.S. Attorney William Burkett, four
of Burkett's assistants and an Internal Revenue Service lawyer from
practicing in the federal courts of western Oklahoma. The judge
contended the attorneys were illegally hiding a witness in a case
involving then Gov. David Hall.
   The 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals overturned Chandler's
order eight months later.
   Chandler offered to retire in 1973, but only if he could name
his successor.
   When Chandler announced in May 1975 that he would take senior
status at age 75, President Gerald Ford accepted his letter of
retirement in a matter of hours. Judicial retirement formalities
usually take up to a month.
   As a senior judge, Chandler was still eligible to hear cases,
but his caseload was greatly reduced.
   Chandler was chairman of the Judicial Administration of the
American Bar Association in 1959-60, and was on the governing
council of the Inter-American Bar Association, 1956-1973.
   In 1960 he was inducted into the Oklahoma Hall of Fame. From
1960-63 he was professor of law at Oklahoma City University.
   He married Margaret Patterson, now deceased, in 1922. He is
survived by a daughter and two sons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890428-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 2242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BabyDeath     04-28 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baby Death,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Young Father's Desperate Act Draws Sympathy, Compassion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEGGY ANDERSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cards, calls and compassion were pouring in
Friday for the desperate young father who held hospital workers at
gunpoint as he removed his comatose baby son from life-support
systems and held him till he died.
   Rudy Linares, 23, a house painter from west suburban Cicero,
faces first-degree murder charges in the death early Wednesday of
his 16-month-old son, Samuel.
   ``I would fly to Chicago tomorrow .... and do anything I could
to help this guy because I feel that there but for the grace of God
go I,'' Michael Killigrew, parent of a brain-damaged child, said
from Nevada City, Calif.
   Samuel had been in a coma, partially brain dead, since he
swallowed a balloon at an Aug. 2 birthday party, blocking the flow
of oxygen to his brain.
   The toddler was considered to be in a ``irreversible vegetative
coma,'' says Dr. Gilbert Goldman, Samuel's physician at pediatric
intensive care at Rush-Presbyterian-St. Luke's Medical Center.
   Goldman has said he did not believe he could legally comply with
the family's request months ago for withdrawal of life support
though he was ``personally and professionally sympathetic.''
   Under state child-abuse laws, support could be withdrawn only if
Samuel had been found to be totally brain-dead or his heart and
lungs had stopped functioning, said Max Brown, a lawyer for the
hospital.
   The family had planned to see a lawyer Friday to discuss their
options.
   ``This is something that should not be the choice of government,
it's a private individual's choice,'' Killigrew said in a telephone
interview with The Associated Press.
   When his 17-month-old daughter, Claudia, suffered severe brain
damage from a 1970 case of spinal meningitis, Killigrew said a
sympathetic doctor allowed him ``agonizing choice'' of letting her
go, rather than prolonging treatment.
   Linares told reporters: ``I did it because I love my son.''
Assistant Public Defender Richard Scholz has said his client will
plead innocent.
   Linares is free on a $75,000 recognizance bond but was ordered
Thursday by Cook County Judge Robert Bastone to undergo a
psychiatric examination to determine whether he ``is any danger to
himself or anyone else.''
   Public defender Philip Mullane told the court Linares took
matters in his own hands after a nurse left a message on the
family's answering machine that said Samuel was to be moved ``to a
long-care residential facility to die.''
   Hospital officials, however, said the message made no reference
to the child's being ``transferred to die'' and was left only after
repeated attempts to reach the Linares and his 21-year-old wife,
Tamara, had failed.
   Mullane said the baby's funeral is scheduled Monday at an
undisclosed location.
   Residents of the Linares' working-class neighborhood said they
had received so many calls offering financial help for the family
that they plan to set up a fund at a Cicero bank to help cover
medical bills and other expenses.
</TEXT>
