<FIRST>r i AM-China-Stalin     04-28 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Stalin,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stalin To Disappear From China's Central Square</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A huge portrait of Soviet dictator Josef Stalin
is to be banished from China's main square this May Day, just two
weeks before Soviet president Mikhail Gorbachev's ceremonial
welcome on the same square.
   Communist Party spokeswoman Yue Yanghua said Saturday that for
the first time in three decades, portraits of Stalin, Lenin, Marx
and Engels will not appear for May Day, a major labor holiday in
China and other socialist nations.
   Yue said the only portrait to appear on Tiananmen Square this
year and in the future will be that of Sun Yatsen, founder of the
first Chinese republic.
   She said authorities decided only pictures of Chinese historical
figures should be shown on the square. Mao Tse-tung's portrait
hangs permanently from atop Tiananmen Gate, at the entrance to the
Forbidden City.
   Yue denied the decision was linked to a reappraisal of Stalin's
historical role as Soviet historians acknowledge Stalin was
responsible for political repression, murderous purges and economic
disasters.
   In the past decade of economic reforms, China rejected Stalinist
state planning and one-man rule, but still recognizes Stalin's role
in the early history of the Chinese Communist Party.
   Portraits of Marx, Engels, Lenin and Sun have decorated the
square every May Day and on China's Oct. 1 National Day since the
1950s.
   Stalin's picture was added in the late 1950s, several years
after his death and at a time when Chinese-Soviet relations were
deteriorating because of differences between Mao and Nikita
Khrushchev.
   Gorbachev's May 15-18 visit will be the first since Khrushchev
was in Beijing in 1959 and will normalize political relations after
30 years of hostility.
</TEXT>
