<FIRST>r w AM-Cheney-Gorbachev     04-28 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cheney-Gorbachev,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Secretary Says Gorbachev Reforms Will ``Ultimately Fail''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney said in an
interview Friday he expects Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev's
reforms to ``ultimately fail'' and that Gorbachev will be replaced
by anti-Western leader.
   ``My personal view is that the task he set for himself to trying
to fundamentally reform the Soviet system is incapable of
occuring,'' Cheney said in the interview taped for broadcast
Saturday on CNN's ``Evans &amp; Novak'' program.
   ``If I had to guess today, I would guess that he would
ultimately fail,'' Cheney said.
   Cheney suggested in the interview that the Soviet leader's
political survival hinges on the success of the economic and
political reforms he has instigated.
   ``That is to say, that he will not be able to reform the Soviet
economy ... And when that happens, he's likely to be replaced by
somebody who will be far more hostile than he's been in terms of
his attitude towards the West,'' Cheney said.
   His comments followed closely the answers he gave a
congressional committee earlier this week when asked about the Bush
administration's proposed reductions in the Pentagon budget. Cheney
told the House Armed Services Committee on Tuesday there is ``a
very real likelihood'' Gorbachev's reforms would fail and that he
would either have to change course or hand over power.
   He said in the interview that the Pentagon cutbacks announced
Tuesday, which included delays in several weapons programs, are not
part of an overall plan to scale back Western defenses because of
Gorbachev's peaceful overtures.
   ``He could modify his policies and have to accomodate a more
conservative line,'' he said of Gorbachev. ``He could conceivably
be replaced. The point is, we don't know.''
