<FIRST>r a AM-FamilyPoisoning     04-28 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Family Poisoning,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Freed Florida Inmate Visits King Grave, Vows To Work To Help Kids</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted murderer freed from a Florida prison
after asserting his innocence for 21 years, visited the tomb of
Martin Luther King Jr. on Friday and vowed to work to help troubled
young people.
   James Richardson, sentenced to death in 1968 in the poisoning
deaths of his seven children, won his freedom Tuesday after a judge
ruled that his murder trial was tainted by prosecutorial misconduct.
   He has insisted he did not kill the children, who ate a prepared
lunch tainted with the pesticide parathion, and sworn affidavits
implicated the family's baby sitter as a suspect.
   Richardson, flanked by civil rights activists, spoke to
reporters at the King Center in Atlanta, telling the dramatic tale
of his near-execution and his years in prison.
   ``I've seen things you never thought in your whole life,'' he
said, describing how he saw young inmates raped and brutalized by
other prisoners.
   ``I want to get started on things I've wanted to do to help,''
he said, adding that he hopes to work with alcoholics and young
people. ``So many of our young people are going to prison. ... They
don't need this. I want to tell our young generation to get
themselves together.''
   Activist Dick Gregory said Richardson, who underwent open-heart
surgery in prison, will join the staff of the Dick Gregory Diet and
Health Resort at Fort Walton Beach, Fla., encouraging other heart
patients to stay healthy.
   Friday evening, Richardson and Gregory arrived in Fort Walton
Beach.
   ``I feel pretty good so far,'' Richardson told reporters. ``I
haven't made any plans at this time but to be with Mr. Dick
Gregory. I think it's going to be wonderful.''
   Richardson is to spend the weekend at the clinic. Gregory has
offered a $100,000-a-year job at the diet clinic to the 53-year-old
former orange picker, who has until June 1 to decide on a contract,
said Richardson attorney Ellis Rubin.
   Richardson also will work with the Southern Christian Leadership
Conference in its programs against drug and alcohol abuse and will
counsel prison inmates, Gregory said, praising Richardson for his
loving attitude.
   ``I cannot believe that this man ... is not bitter,'' Gregory
said. ``If he was bitter, I could sympathize with him, but I
wouldn't hire him.''
   Richardson sat before King's tomb and sang out the words on the
slain civil rights leader's crypt: ``Free at last, free at last,
thank God almighty, I'm free.'' Richardson used the same words on
the first full day of his release.
   SCLC President Joseph Lowery said Richardson's case
``underscores and affirms, again and again, the argument against
the death penalty. One of the damnable things about the death
penalty is you cannot correct a mistake. He would be dead.''
   Richardson's death sentence was commuted to a life term in 1972
after the U.S. Supreme Court struck down the nation's capital
punishment laws.
   Rubin said Richardson, his wife and daughter have authorized him
to seek compensation from those responsible for imprisoning
Richardson, a step that must be taken before the state Legislature
could consider a relief bill to award damages.
</TEXT>
