<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     04-28 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Korean Students, Workers Hurl Firebombs, Shout Anti-U.S. Slogans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of students screaming
``Yankee go home!'' fought riot police at five universities in
Seoul Friday after authorities banned them from marching to the
border with communist North Korea to press for national unification.
   Police officials said injuries occurred, but they had no figures.
   In the southeastern industrial cities of Changwon and Masan,
about 6,000 striking workers hurling rocks and firebombs tangled
with police for a fifth day, police said.
   Strikers in Changwon poured oil on streets and set them afire,
and protesters in Masan used slingshots to pelt police with pieces
of scrap metal, they said. About 20 workers were arrested.
   Student and dissident groups are trying to unite with workers to
build an anti-government alliance.
   Government leaders are concerned about the growing labor unrest
and a wave of increasingly violent strikes for more pay and
improved working conditions.
   Police arrested 20 student delegates as they tried to reach the
border to meet with North Korean counterparts. The students wanted
to discuss taking part in an international youth festival in the
north's capital of Pyongyang in July, and ways to unite the two
Korean states.
   At Seoul National University, black police vans armed with
multiple launchers fired hundreds of tear gas rounds into the ranks
of 4,000 students fighting officers with wooden clubs, pipes and
firebombs while trying to march out of the campus. Fighting flared
around the sprawling campus in southern Seoul, with about 3,000
riot police surrounding the school.
   Hundreds of students fought police on at least four other Seoul
campuses.
   Student clashes also broke out in the southern port of Pusan and
radicals seized a government prosecutors' office in Taegu,
according to Yonhap, the South Korean news agency.
   Student leaders lashed out at South Korean President Roh Tae-woo
and the United States in rallies before the clashes, accusing them
of perpetuating the division of the Korean peninsula, split into
communist north and capitalist south after World War II.
   Also Friday, about 3,400 police officers tendered resignations
en masse to protest an alleged assault on a police superintendent
by an opposition lawmaker in Changwon the previous day. National
Assemblyman Sim Wan-koo was reported to have slapped the
suprintendent in the face during a labor protest.
   National Police Director Jo Chong-suk appealed for restraint and
returned the resignations.
   Reports said Sim and four other opposition lawmakers, in
Changwon to look into labor unrest, became infuriated when police
arrested a union leader they escorted. The man had been sought by
police for unlawful labor activity.
</TEXT>
