<FIRST>r i AM-France-Blowpipe     04-28 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Blowpipe,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>France Expels Three South Africans In Blowpipe Affair</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three South African officials implicated in
secretly acquiring British Blowpipe missile parts from Northern
Ireland extremists were ordered to leave France by May 2, the
Foreign Ministry said Friday.
   The official announcement did not identify the three but said
they were attached to the South African Embassy in Paris, with
partial diplomatic immunity.
   Ambassador Hendrik Geldenhuys was summoned and told the
officials were expelled because of ``activities contrary to their
status,'' it said.
   A French official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
three included Daniel Storm, the man caught receiving British-made
ground-to-air missile parts from three Protestant extremists of the
Ulster Resistance.
   Police arrested Storm, the three extremists and an American
businessman on April 21 after an investigation by French
counterespionage agents and British secret services.
   Storm was released because of his embassy role, but the other
four were held on gun-running and conspiracy charges, police said.
   In Britain, Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe accused South
Africa of trying to steal British missile secrets in exchange for
arms to Northern Ireland.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher expressed ``grave concern'' to
visiting South African Finance Minister Barend Du Plessis, the
Foreign Office said.
