<FIRST>r a AM-Super7 2ndLd-Writethru a0778 04-28 0741</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Super 7, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0778,0762</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight of 14 Winners Claim Jackpot Shares</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: INSERTS 1 graf after 14th, `Lottery Executive...,' to UPDATE
with total payout of lottery.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH KIRKPATRICK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIDDLETOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Only eight of the 14 winners in the
record $115 million Pennsylvania Super 7 lottery had put in claims
by Friday, one of whom said she spent a day in a motel because she
``just needed some time to sit.''
   By Friday afternoon, the holders of the eight tickets had
checked in at lottery headquarters, and officials said two other
claimants had contacted them. Four winning tickets were not
accounted for.
   The lucky few, meanwhile, savored their fortune and spun
fantasies about the future that no longer seemed so fantastic.
   Arthur and Judy Rosen arrived from East Windsor, N.J., with
their sons, Jay, 25, and Paul, 23, and a daughter, Deborah, 20.
They bought 80 tickets for the Wednesday night drawing.
   Arthur Rosen, 50, said he tried something Friday he had never
done before: ``I lit a cigarette with a dollar bill.''
   Paul Rosen, a former magician who is now a restaurant manager in
Lawrenceville, N.J., said he wants to spend some of the winnings on
the grave of magician Harry Houdini in New York City.
   ``I've had a dream for a long time to refurbish his grave and
fix it up,'' he said.
   Sylvia Trapuzzano, 35, of Washington, Pa., arrived Friday with
her fiance, father, two brothers and a sister and brother-in-law
after waiting a day at a Harrisburg area motel.
   ``I just needed some time to sit there,'' she told reporters.
``I was shocked and I couldn't believe it.''
   Trapuzzano, a sales representative, said she had kept the
winning ticket ``in a little baggie. I carried it around with me.''
   Miss Trapuzzano said her father, Ben, had bought five tickets
each for his children after she was unable to buy her own because
of long lines.
   James and Jalinda Whittle Jr. of New Brighton, Pa., and Mary
Jane Hicks, 74, of Lebanon, Pa., reached lottery headquarters
within five minutes of each other shortly before 4 p.m. EDT.
   Mrs. Hicks, a widow, said she talked to her dog when she learned
she had a big winner in her stack of 15 tickets. ``He smiled,'' she
said.
   Lottery Executive Director Jim Scroggins said the individual
ticket validation will take until next week and the first checks
will be presented then.
   The 14 jackpot tickets, each with seven winning numbers, are
worth $8.3 million over 26 years, or $317,524.67 a year before
taxes. Tickets with six winning numbers pay $4,842.50 and five
winning numbers, $274.50. Tickets with four winning numbers pay $7.
   Also claiming a jackpot ticket were three West Virginia
University maintenance workers: James Evans, 40; John Gardner, 38;
and Lionel Herndon, 40, along with Herndon's wife, Connie, 39.
   In 1984, Herndon was electrically shocked on the job and was on
disability before returning to a lower level job at half pay. He
said his first reaction to winning was fear.
   ``If you got $100 million, you'd better be worried. We got the
kids out of the house. Basically, we just left,'' Herndon said.
   He said he was relieved to share the prize. His ticket,
potentially worth $317,524 a year for 26 years, will be split three
ways.
   Two couples from the Erie area also put in a claim for a single
ticket. They were Charles J. and Kathy Davis of McKean Township and
John and Rose White of Wesleyville.
   Davis, 34, and White, 42, learned of their potential win at
their $35,000-a-year jobs at General Electric. They said they did a
victory dance.
   White said he called his wife at Alliance Plastics, telling her:
```Walk out, quit, you're done! We hit the big one! We're
millionaires!' She didn't believe me. She found out when she got
home.''
   Mrs. White, 41, said she usually worked seven days a week for
about $6 an hour at what is now her former job. She said she wants
a new car to replace the 1979 model her husband gave away to a
friend after he learned of the big win.
   The Whites said they will take their daughter, son and four
grandchildren for a trip to Disney World.
   A group of 14 workers from the Windham, Ohio, area and three
family members from western Pennsylvania and New York also claimed
single tickets Thursday.
</TEXT>
