<FIRST>r i AM-Gulf-Deflagging     04-28 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gulf-Deflagging,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Kuwaiti Tankers Deflagged by United States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Kuwait agreed to
remove the American flag from six Kuwait-owned oil tankers that
sailed under U.S. protection during the Iraq-Iran war in the
Persian Gulf, officials said Friday.
   The decision, announced by the U.S. Maritime Administration in
Washington, ended two months of deadlock between U.S. and Kuwaiti
officials over what had been assumed to be a routine matter when
first announced last February.
   According to official sources in the gulf and in Washington, the
Kuwaitis objected to a U.S. legal provision stipulating that even
after the vessels reverted to Kuwaiti registry, the United States
would retain the right to requisition them for use in a national
emergency.
   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Kuwaiti
officials rejected such a condition as infringing on Kuwaiti
sovereignty.
   They said the two sides finally agreed that the tankers would be
returned to Kuwait's Finance Ministry rather than to the Kuwait Oil
Tanker Co., which actually operates them.
   Although the tanker company is wholly government-owned, the
sources said, U.S. officials deemed the distinction sufficient for
a waiver of Kuwait's obligation to make the ships available to
America.
   Walter Oates, a spokesman for the U.S. Maritime Administration,
said he could not comment other than to say the agreement became
effective as of Thursday. Kuwaiti officials were not available to
comment.
   The six ships include two petrolem product tankers and four
identical liquefied gas carriers. They were among 11 Kuwait-owned
tankers reflagged by the United States in mid-1987, entitling them
to U.S. naval escort.
   Iran at that time was attacking Kuwaiti shipping because of
Kuwait's support for Iraq in the war. Hostilities ended last Aug.
20 with a U.N.-mediated cease-fire.
   Kuwait had set up a new company, the Chesapeake Shipping Co., of
Dover, Del., as ostensible U.S. owners of the tankers. Chesapeake
will ``sell'' the six ships back to Kuwait in a transaction
existing only on paper, the sources said.
   The other five tankers will continue to fly the Stars and
Stripes, at least until next February, on condition that
all-American crews replace the regular crews during that period.
   At the time of the reflagging in 1987, the Reagan administration
waived a U.S. law requiring U.S.-flagged ships to have all-American
crews.
</TEXT>
