<FIRST>r i AM-Ecuador-Drugs     04-28 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ecuador-Drugs,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Seize Drugs After Plane Crash Lands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUITO, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested five suspected drug
traffickers and seized 609 pounds of semi-processed cocaine after a
light plane crash-landed near the Colombian border, Interpol
spokesman Efrain Ramirez said Friday.
   He said the aircraft, bound from Peru to Colombia, ran out of
fuel and came down in the jungle near Francisco de Orellana, 100
miles east of Quito.
   No one was hurt, he said, adding that two other men were held
after they flew in on a second small plane to aid the stricken
craft.
   The incident occurred April 17 but was not reported until Friday
to permit an investigation, Ramirez said. All those arrested are
Colombians, he said.
   In another incident, the newspaper El Comercio of Lima, Peru,
said a small plane carrying 440 pounds of semi-processed cocaine
crashed Tuesday in Peru's isolated Amazon jungle.
   Two suspected Colombian drug traffickers were killed, El
Comercio reported Friday.
   Officials say Peru is the source of about 60 percent of the
world's coca leaf, the raw material of cocaine. The plant is
semi-processed and flown from jungle airstrips to Colombia, where
it is processed into pure cocaine for sale in the United States and
Europe.
   Ramirez's organization, Interpol, is an international police
organization with headquarters in Paris.
</TEXT>
