<FIRST>a i PM-Philippines-AIDS Adv04   04-28 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-AIDS, Adv 04,0646</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>Adv for Thu PMs May 4 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Government Fights Misconceptions as Concern About AIDS Grows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By YASMIN ARQUIZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widely publicized death of a
prostitute has increased concern about AIDS, and officials are
trying to dispel false ideas about the disease in a nation where
sex is a flourishing trade.
   Officials say at least 22 people in the Philippines have
developed active AIDS cases and 100 have been identified as
carriers of the virus that causes acquired immune deficiency
syndrome.
   Sixty-one of the 100 carriers are female prostitutes and 50 of
them work near Clark Air Base and the Subic Bay naval base, the two
huge U.S. military installations in the Philippines.
   Dr. Erlinda Guerrero, the national AIDS registrar, believes the
true figures are higher. She says inadequate testing and reporting
methods may be missing 90 percent of the carriers.
   Since 30 per cent of carriers develop symptoms of the disease in
five years, She fears AIDS cases could reach 300 by then.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome, for which there is no cure,
weakens the body's ability to resist infection and makes the victim
vulnerable to a range of fatal illnesses. It is spread by sexual
contact, use of infected needles and contaminated blood products.
   Officials say all but three of the 22 AIDS patients acquired the
disease abroad.
   Two of the three who contracted it in the Philippines have died.
   A male homosexual died last year and the second victim was a
24-year-old bar girl from Angeles, home of Clark Air Base. Her
death last month was widely publicized.
   She died at the time of newspaper reports that a young Brazilian
woman, who claimed to have had sex with many prominent Filipinos,
tested positive for the AIDS virus. The Brazilian has left the
country and, because of privacy regulations, health officials
refuse to confirm whether she was infected.
   Officials say AIDS could spread rapidly in the Philippines
because of prostitution and public misconceptions of the disease.
   Peter Resurrecion of the national AIDS control program, said a
Gallup survey of 35 nations had the Philippines among the countries
whose people believe the disease can be contracted by working
beside infected people or sharing drinking glasses with them, or
from insect bites.
   A survey by the Health Department found that many male
prostitutes thought exercise prevents AIDS, he said.
   Officials say 94 percent of men who contracted AIDS or carried
the virus had not used condoms.
   Health Department workers are studying ways to combat AIDS myths
and are instructing the public on effective precautions. Officials
plan to spend most of the $467,290 allocated for AIDS control on
print and broadcast advertising.
   ``Our basic goal is to change the behavior of people,
considering that each individual has the responsibility to protect
himself,'' Dr. Guerrero said.
   In Angeles, city health officer Proceso Mejia said posters
saying ``Prevent AIDS, Use Condoms'' and ``No Condom, No Sex'' were
placed in the bar district.
   The high percentage of AIDS carriers among prostitutes working
near U.S. bases has led some women's groups to urge that the
installations be closed to keep the disease from spreading.
   ``We think AIDS is coming to the Philippines through the U.S.
bases,'' said Adul de Leon, an official of the militant feminist
organization Gabriela, which demands that the United States finance
AIDS control programs.
   Dr. Guerrero said the high incidence around the bases may be
traceable to the fact that, since U.S. authorities paid for the
program, 67 per cent of the 108,000 screened were from those areas.
   U.S. officials have promised that any American service member
found to carry the virus will not be assigned to the Philippines.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Adv Thu PMs May 4</NOTE>
</DOC>
