<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 1416EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-BlackFarmers Adv07-2Takes   04-28 1183</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Black Farmers, Adv 07-2 Takes,1214</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, May 7, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Black Farmers Battle Odds To Survive</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Story is complete in one take; optional add for editors desiring
more detail</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STRAT DOUTHAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spring has kissed central Alabama, and
L.C. Crosby once again is busy planting corn, peas, butter beans
and okra. He's also hoping for a bumper watermelon crop this summer.
   ``I've got a plan,'' he says as he leans against his old Ford
tractor. ``If it works out, I'm going to get my watermelons on the
market two or three weeks earlier than anybody else and I'll clean
up.''
   Crosby, a friendly man with a wiry build, becomes excited as he
talks about his crops and the 43-acre ``dream farm'' where he and
his family once worked as field hands. However, this could be the
last spring for his dream, and for a lot of other dreams like his.
   At 33, L.C. Crosby is a young, black farmer. And, as such he's
twice as likely to lose his land as his white counterpart.
   In 1910, the nation's 950,000 black farmers comprised 14 percent
of all farmers in this country. Now, the remaining 35,000 make up
just 1.6 percent of the 2.3 million farmers in the United States.
   According to the U.S. Census Bureau, the number of black farms
declined by 42 percent between 1978 and 1982. White farms fell by
only 2.4 percent during the same period.
   ``Unless this trend is reversed, there will be no more black
farmers in America by the year 2,000.'' This dire prediction is
contained in the U.S. Civil Rights Commission's 1982 report on the
``Decline of Black Farmers in America.''
   Yet, while there's just a relative handful of young, black
farmers still operating _ the current, median age for U.S. black
farmers is 60 _ the federal government is trying to force L.C.
Crosby off his land.
   ``The FHA (Farmer's Home Administration) has given him notice to
vacate the premises because he's behind on his loan. But we're
telling him to stay put and fight,'' says George Paris, Jr., a
field coordinator for the private, non-profit Federation of
Southern Cooperatives.
   Crosby bought his farm, which includes a large pond and
five-acre pecan orchard, at an FHA auction in 1985. He bid $36,500,
borrowing $31,000 from the government.
   ``My annual payment is $3,800,'' he said. ``I fell behind the
second year. Now, I've got the money to make the payment but the
FHA wants the whole $30,000.''
   Paris said he's heard that a wealthy white landowner, whose bid
was $10,000 lower than Crosby's, covets the property.
   ``It's the same old story,'' he said. ``The FHA is slowly
changing but basically, at the local level, quite often its still a
bunch of good ol' white boys who look after each other.''
   Paris' father, who worked for the FHA for nearly 30 years and
was one of the first black men ever to serve as an assistant county
supervisor, agrees with this assessment.
   ``It was tragic. Blacks always got the last and the least,''
said the elder Paris, adding that he saw hundreds of black
Alabamians lose their farms during the 30 years he workd for the
FHA.
   ``I remember one time back, in the '60s, I was told, outright,
by a white FHA committee member in Bullock County, Ala., that a
black farmer had been denied a loan because he was `shooting off
his mouth about civil rights.'''
   Under the FHA's loan procedure, a county supervisor makes a
recommendation to a three-member county loan committee, which then
either approves or denies the loan. Fred Bennett, a 73-year-old
farmer in the Mt. Zion community, near Greenville, was the first
black ever to serve on an FHA county committee.
   In this country, the average black-owned farm contains fewer
than 100 acres, compared with an average of 440 acres for all U.S.
farms. Bennett and his wife Lena own 500 acres, which they slowly
acquired over the past 40 years, parcel by parcel.
   ``My grandfather came to this area at age 12, shortly after he
was freed from slavery,'' Bennett said. ``He never owned land,
being a cash renter, but I've found that, for a black man in this
country, there is no greater security, nor better avenue to
independence, than farming.''
   Bennett, who said he and his four brothers pooled their
resources and ``pulled together toward a common objective,''
acknowledged he is worried and saddened that this generation of
young blacks isn't going into agriculture.
   ``After the Civil War, the federal government promised the freed
blacks 40 acres and a mule but hardly any of them got it,'' he
said. ``Our people should realize by now that they've got to help
themselves; nobody's going to do it for them.
   ``I'm very concerned that young blacks are turning their backs
on farming, at a time when life in the cities is getting worse
every day.''
   The United Farmers Organization, a non-profit advocacy group
based in Charlotte, N.C., estimates there now are fewer than 200
full-time black farmers, aged 25 or under, in the entire country.
   Officials at North Carolina A&amp;T State University, who say they
are getting 25 percent fewer agriculture students than they did 20
years ago, blame farming's poor image and the enormous difficulty
young blacks face in amassing capital.
   The continuing phenomenon of black land loss was the topic at a
recent meeting sponsored by the university and the United Church of
Christ.
   ``Greed and institutional racism'' are the major reasons blacks
have been forced out of farming said the Rev. Charles Shelby Rooks,
director of the church's Board of Homeland Ministries, in his
keynote address at the conference in Greensboro, N.C.
   In its report, the U.S. Civil Rights Commission found that
blacks were being ill-served by the FHA, the U.S. Department of
Agriculture's agency designed specifically to help poor farmers.
   The commission, noting that black farmers _ 90 percent of whom
are in the South _ often are unable to deal with the ever more
complex federal loan programs. The commission called for serious
government intervention.
   Last July, as part of an omnibus farm bill passed by Congress in
1987, the FHA launched its ``Socially Disadvantaged Outreach Farm
Ownership Program.''
   ``So far,'' said FHA spokesman Nolan Kegley, ``we have made 58
loans to minority farmers under the program.'' He said the loans,
totalling $4.6 million, are to finance farm purchases for poor
blacks and other minorities.
   ``We recognize the problems of the past and we're working on
them at all levels,'' Kegley said. ``Since 1984 the percentage of
FHA loans to blacks has been steadily increasing.''
   He acknowledged, when asked, however, that only 91 of the FHA's
1,849 county supervisors are black. In Mississippi, the state with
the most black farmers, eight of the 82 county supervisors are
black. In North Carolina, it's only three of 79.
   FHA officials in those states say they have had little luck
recruiting qualified blacks because the goverment pay scale isn't
competitive.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
