<DOCNO> AP890428-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 1416EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-BlackFarmers Adv07-1stAdd   04-28 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Black Farmers, Adv 07-1st Add,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, May 7, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>GREENVILLE, Ala.: isn't competitive.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In Alabama, however, eight of 57 county supervisors are black,
two of seven district supervisors are black and 49 of 203 county
committee members are black.
   George Paris says the FHA must make such across-the-board
efforts in every state if black farmers are to have an equal chance
to survive.
   The new FHA minority funding outreach program does little, he
said, to help many of those black farmers already indebted to the
federal government.
   ``If they really want to help black farmers they should forgive
their past debts and let them start over,'' he added. ``Lord knows
the FHA has done little enough in the past to help small farmers.''
   Paris' organization is in the forefront of the effort to help
black farmers stay on the land. The federation offers counseling in
crop planning and farm management. It also helps poor farmers,
black and white, wade through the intracacies of the FHA loan and
appeal procedures.
   Jerry Pennick, who heads the federation's Land Assistance Fund,
has helped draft a proposed ``Minority Farmer's Act'' that would
provide emergency aid. Among other things, it would create a
special agency within the USDA to deal with concerns of minority
farmers and develop a special debt restructuring program for
farmers who are less than $100,000 in hock to the FHA.
   ``We hope to get the bill introduced this fall or early next
year,'' Pinnock said. ``The black congressional caucus is planning
to push it. We also have assurances of support support from some
white congressmen.''
   Black farmers such as L.C. Crosby, meanwhile, are hanging on by
a slender thread.
   For others, such as Tim Pigford, a ruined third-generation
farmer from Arcadia, N.C., the thread has snapped.
   ``I haven't farmed since 1984, the year the hurricane blew
through here,'' said Pigford, who now works in a factory. ``The FHA
never would loan me enough money to buy a farm, just enough to rent
out land to farm. But the hurricane ruined me and now the
government is trying to take my house.''
   Pigford, who testified in 1984 before a congressional committee
investigating the FHA's lending practices, added that he thinks his
chances are slim of ever getting back onto a tractor seat.
   Another young farmer, George Ammans, who raises turkeys at
Kenansville, N.C., says whites shouldn't think that black farmers
are just looking for free handouts.
   ``Like bald eagles I'm a member of an endangered species,'' he
said. ``If the government is willing to help eagles, it oughta be
willing to help me. All I want is a chance to survive.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Strat Douthat is the AP Southeast regional
reporter, based in Atlanta.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 7</NOTE>
