<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     04-28 0846</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0883</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said consumer spending rose a
slim 0.2 percent in March, its weakest performance in six months
and a sign, analysts said, that consumers are contributing to an
economic slowdown.
   The sluggish spending came even as personal income rose a strong
0.8 percent. That combination boosted the personal savings rate to
its highest level in nearly four years, the Commerce Department
said Thursday.
   The government also reported that the prices Americans paid for
imported goods rose 1.7 percent in the first quarter, largely
reflecting a surge in the cost of crude oil from abroad.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Banking Committee voted to make
savings and loan owners put nearly $13 billion more of their own
money at risk as the price for a $90 billion federal bailout but
gave them 3{ more years than President Bush wants to do it.
   Eleven Republicans on Thursday joined all but four Democrats in
a 36-15 vote to delay until January 1995 the June 1991 deadline
that Bush had proposed for S&amp;Ls to come up with 3 percent ``hard
cash'' capital _ or $3 for every $100 they lend.
   Separately, federal regulators took over four more insolvent
S&amp;Ls in three states, bringing the total under government control
to 220 in 32 states.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Commerce Commissioner Michael Hatch
blocked oil billionaire Marvin Davis' $2.7 billion tender offer for
Northwest Airlines' parent company in Minnesota.
   Thursday's suspension order blocks the estimated 1,900
shareholders in the state from selling their 1.3 million shares to
Davis.
   Separately, NWA Inc. Chairman Steven Rothmeier said a
management-led buyout of Northwest is not in the works, but there
are as many as four friendly suitors interested in buying the
airline.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strikebound Eastern Airlines, three days after
outlining a plan for cutting $1.8 billion in assets, announced a
deal to lease 14 Boeing 727-200 planes to rival Pan American World
Airways.
   The $96.6 million, 5-year lease announced Thursday gives Pan Am
an option to extend the lease or buy the planes at a price to be
negotiated.
   The agreement must be approved by the U.S. Bankruptcy Court in
New York, which has had oversight of such deals since Eastern filed
March 9 for Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   RJR Nabisco Inc. will move its headquarters to
the metropolitan New York area from Atlanta, the food and tobacco
giant announced shortly after shareholders approved the record
$24.53 billion buyout of the company by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp;
Co.
   RJR Nabisco said Thursday its new chairman, Louis Gerstner Jr.,
sent a letter to employees saying relocations could begin by early
summer and would be completed by the end of the year.
   Some existing corporate functions may be reassigned to RJR
Nabisco's operating companies.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond dealer Matthews &amp; Wright Group Inc. will
surrender its license in order to settle civil fraud and other
charges stemming from the underwriting of more than $1 billion in
municipal bonds, the government said.
   The settlement with the Securities and Exchange Commission
announced Thursday caps an intense federal investigation into the
bond-peddling practices of Matthews &amp; Wright that stem from
municipal issues it sold as long as four years ago.
   Without admitting or denying guilt, Matthews &amp; Wright and its
top executives agreed to settle civil charges brought by the SEC
that they violated anti-fraud and false-reporting provisions of
federal securities laws.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sony Corp. will research high-definition
television at a Silicon Valley site as part of a ``long-term
commitment to building an extensive U.S. engineering and
manufacturing base,'' the company said.
   ``Today HDTV is being held hostage as a symbol of the need for
improving American competitiveness. This is in our opinion most
unfortunate,'' Neil Vander Dussen, president of Sony Corp. of
America, said Thursday.
   Sony is hoping its Advanced Video Technology Center in San Jose,
Calif., will help it localize products for the U.S. market while
defusing political tensions over the next generation of television.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aunt Jemima, the robust matriarch of pancake
products, is getting a new hairdo in her first makeover in 20
years, but her reassuring smile will stay the same, officials at
Quaker Oats Co. said.
   Quaker said Thursday it is trading her headband for soft, curly,
gray-streaked hair and pearl earrings in a bid to update the
100-year-old trademark. Aunt Jemima also was given a new lace
collar.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rallied Thursday in buying ascribed to hopes
for favorable news on inflation. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrials climbed 29.88 points to 2,418.99, a new high since the
crash in October 1987.
   The dollar finished at varied levels against key foreign
currencies. Gold prices declined in the United States following
modest rises on foreign markets. Bond prices advanced broadly.
   Silver futures prices dropped sharply; gasoline and crude oil
futures fell; cattle prices lost ground while hog futures rallied;
and wheat and soybean futures slipped while corn rose.
