<HEAD>Panhandle Eastern Complete Tender Offer For Texas Eastern</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Preliminary results ...,' to CORRECT day of
week to Wednesday sted Thursday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panhandle Eastern Corp. said Thursday it had
completed its $3.2 billion tender offer for Texas Eastern Corp. and
has accepted payment for about 81 percent of outstanding Texas
Eastern shares.
   The buyout puts an end to a rival bid from Coastal Corp. All the
natural gas companies are based in Houston.
   Preliminary results indicate that about 57 million Texas Eastern
shares were validly tendered and not withdrawn prior to the
midnight Wednesday expiration of Panhandle Eastern's offer.
   Panhandle Eastern's offer included provisions to buy up to 80
percent of Texas Eastern's 60.8 million outstanding shares and a
stock exchange at the same $53-per-share value for the remaining
shares.
   The combination of the two companies will create a 27,000-mile
system _ one of the nation's largest pipeline companies in terms of
miles.
   The battle for Texas Eastern began Jan. 16 when Coastal
announced its surprise takeover bid. But the Texas Eastern board
rejected the $2.6 billion offer as too low, signing the merger
agreement with Panhandle Eastern instead on Feb. 21.
   Coastal spokesman Robert W. Wells said the company would tender
its 2.5 million shares of Texas Eastern common stock.
   During Panhandle Eastern's stockholder meeting Wednesday,
Chairman Robert D. Hunsucker said about 500 corporate staff and
other headquarters office jobs would be eliminated after the merger.
   The cutbacks are needed to reduce operating costs of the
combined organization, and affect more than 20 percent of both
companies' work forces, Hunsucker said.
   Panhandle Eastern began buying shares of Texas Eastern stock
Thursday after the Federal Trade Commission cleared the way for the
two companies to proceed with their merger.
