<HEAD>Prime Reports $5 Million Loss in First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NATICK, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Computer Inc. reported a $5 million
loss for the first quarter and blamed it on costly efforts
associated with blocking a hostile takeover bid by MAI Basic Four
Inc.
   The Natick-based computer manufacturer said Thursday it spent
$6.3 million before taxes in battling the California company's
tender offer. Prime also claimed that some customers have been
delaying purchases due to speculation over Prime's plight.
   Other factors associated with the loss, the company said, were
organizational changes and layoffs following the integration of the
Calma Co., acquired from General Electric Co. in 1988, and a Prime
division in a joint venture.
   For the quarter, the net loss was $5 million on revenue of $387
million, compared with earnings of $14.5 million, or 30 cents a
share, on revenue of $363.7 million in the same period a year ago.
