<FIRST>r f PM-ChannelOne Bjt   04-28 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Channel One, Bjt,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Channel One Schools Wait To See Ad-Free Turner Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of the principals whose schools were part of
Whittle Communications' test of a commercially-sponsored news show
for teens are taking a wait-and-see approach to the prospect of a
rival, ad-free service.
   The comments Thursday followed cable executive Ted Turner's
announcement that he planned to launch a daily news show for
schools in August.
   The service resembles Whittle's Channel One program, which
recently completed a test run at six schools. But Turner's program
will contain no advertising while Channel One does.
   ``I don't know anything about the quality of the (Turner)
programming,'' said Principal Stan Jasinskas at Eisenhower Middle
School in Kansas City, Kan.
   John ``Rex'' Stooksbury, principal at Central High School in
Whittle's hometown of Knoxville, Tenn., also said he didn't want to
take a position on the Turner proposal before seeing the program.
   ``I don't want to close the door on any innovations that might
enhance our students' education, but I can't compare the two
because I haven't seen his program yet,'' he said.
   Channel One, a daily 12-minute news show aimed at teens, was
tested at Eisenhower, Central and four other schools over a
seven-week period ended last Friday. Each program contained two
minutes of commercials for jeans, sneakers, candy and other
products.
   The advertising sparked complaints from national education
groups, which said Whittle should not be allowed to sell a captive
student audience to big business.
   Whittle said the ads are needed to pay for the video recorders,
TV monitors in every classroom and satellite dishes that it gave
each of the participating schools so they could show the program
schoolwide every day.
   The company is evaluating the test results to determine whether
to expand the program nationally in the fall of 1990.
   But Turner, who heads Turner Broadcasting System Inc., said he
would start producing a 15-minute news show for schools on Aug. 14
and run it on his Cable News Network in the early morning hours
each school day so teachers could record it for later use in class.
   He said the program, CNN Newsroom, would carry no advertising, a
move that some cable industry insiders said could undercut support
for Whittle's ad-supported show and reassert Turner's prominence in
cable programming.
   Turner said he expected local cable operators would support his
program by making free cable connections to high schools and help
see that every school got a chance to receive the show.
   Eisenhower's Jasinskas said Turner's approach ``sounds like a
very interesting idea'' and said he would be open-minded about it.
   But he said the importance of giving schools equipment on the
scale of the Channel One program should not be underestimated when
comparing the Whittle and Turner offerings.
   Eisenhower High was given 40 television sets and Central High
got 70 from Channel One, and the principals said the schools might
not have otherwise obtained them.
   Central High's Stooksbury said his school had no problems with
the Channel One commercials anyway, and teachers and students miss
having the program.
</TEXT>
