<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0256EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Northwest     04-28 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northwest,0651</SECOND>
<HEAD>Davis To Ask Court To Vacate State Order Blocking Northwest Offer</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA WILKINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Another court battle involving Northwest
Airlines shaped up when state Commerce Commissioner Michael Hatch
ordered Minnesota shareholders of the airline's parent not to sell
their shares to hostile suitor Marvin Davis.
   Minneapolis attorney Thomas A. Keller, who is representing Davis
in Minnesota, said he planned to file a lawsuit today in U.S.
District Court asking a judge to vacate the order issued Thursday
by Hatch.
   In a related development, a vote on a state anti-takeover bill
aimed at placing roadblocks in the way of Northwest suitors was
delayed by legislators' questions about the constitutionality of
the measure.
   Under Minnesota's existing anti-takeover law, Hatch can block a
securities offer within the state under certain conditions. His
order prevents the estimated 1,900 shareholders of NWA Inc. in the
state from selling their 1.3 million shares to Davis, whose offer
of $2.7 billion, or $90 a share, has been rejected by the NWA board.
   NWA Chairman Steven Rothmeier said Thursday the airline holding
company is aware of or four friendly potential suitors, but would
not identify them. He said a management-led buyout of Northwest,
the nation's fourth-largest carrier, is not in the works.
   Davis Acquisition Inc., the company Davis set up to bid for NWA,
said Hatch's suspension of its bid in Minnesota ``will only serve
to disadvantage and inconvenience'' Minnesota stockholders, who can
sell their shares only in the open market at a discount.
   But Hatch said the order could hamper Davis' ability to
negotiate loans to finance the purchase.
   ``The practical effect is that lenders don't like to make loans
to people who are in violation of securities laws,'' he said.
   Hatch said he would consider lifting the suspension at any time
if the billionaire oilman disclosed more details of his plan for
running the airline. The additional details which Davis supplied
Thursday did not satisfy his request, he said.
   Hatch is asking Davis to explain how he will operate the
carrier, based in suburban Eagan, without layoffs or cutbacks in
light of the major debt load he would incur through the takeover.
Davis has denied he would make such cutbacks.
   Keller maintained that Davis Acquisition's original financial
disclosure statement was sufficient under the state's anti-takeover
law. With additional information supplied at a Tuesday hearing and
on Thursday, Keller said, Davis more than fully satisfied the law's
disclosure requirements.
   No more disclosures will be made because that ``would require
getting into confidential, proprietary information that would put
us at a severe disadvantage vis-a-vis other bidders,'' Keller said.
   The information submitted Thursday concerned Davis' intention to
substantially increase the capacity of passenger-seat miles over
the next six years, Keller said. Additionally, the information said
Davis intends to enhance the utilization of the aircraft's fleet by
improving scheduling, he said.
   On another front Thursday, the chairman of the state Senate
Judiciary Committee, Sen. Allan Spear of Minneapolis, said he would
give the anti-takeover bill another hearing due to the concerns
about constitutionality.
   The bill includes provisions that would:
   _Prevent a corporate raider from financing a takeover of a
company with a substantial connection to Minnesota by selling the
company's assets.
   _Give the Metropolitan Airports Commission power to approve an
acquisition of a major tenant of Minneapolis-St. Paul International
Airport, such as Northwest.
   _Impose a state excise tax on ``golden parachutes,'' the large
severance payments corporate executives receive if they are fired
or leave their jobs after their company is bought.
   Also Thursday, Northwest said U.S. District Judge Harry
MacLaughlin extended until May 11 his temporary restraining order
prohibiting Davis from ``disrupting'' contracts or contract
negotiations at Northwest. The order had been scheduled to expire
Thursday.
</TEXT>
