<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-PanAm     04-28 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Pan Am,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Wants To Lease 14 Jets To Pan Am</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines wants to lease 14 planes to rival
Pan American World Airways as it begins its newly announced
restructuring plan.
   The $96.6 million, five-year lease would give Pan Am an option
to extend the lease or to buy the 727-200 planes at a price to be
negotiated, Eastern spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak said Thursday.
   The agreement must be approved by the U.S. Bankruptcy Court in
New York, which has had oversight of such deals since strike-torn
Eastern filed March 9 for Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization.
   ``We had indicated we would be raising about $1.8 billion
through assets sales,'' Ms. Ceremsak said. ``This is certainly the
first step in this direction for the new, reduced-size airline.''
   Eastern President Phil Bakes described the planned restructuring
of Eastern on Monday, after parent Texas Air Corp. ruled out a sale
of Eastern. Bakes said Eastern would rebuild with a smaller airline
and address its debts by slashing service by 29 percent and selling
$1.8 billion worth of assets.
   Eastern's unions, on strike since March 4, continue to hope the
bankruptcy court and Eastern's creditors will call for sale of the
airline. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland has set a Wednesday
hearing on why Eastern shouldn't be sold in its entirety to the
highest bidder.
   Ms. Ceremsak said there was considerable industry interest in
Eastern assets such as planes, gates and routes and that the
beleaguered company was receiving good offers.
   ``There's a tremendous demand right now for airplanes by other
carriers that are expanding,'' she said. ``The delivery positions
and orders are backed up in the factories.''
   She said she didn't have any information on other assets sales
in the works, but added: ``... there have been many interested
parties. Obviously, there are going to be other transactions.''
   Eastern's restructuring plan calls for a fleet of 157 aircraft.
If the 14 149-seat 727 planes are leased to Pan Am at $115,000 a
month and another 21 of the 727 planes are sold to New York
developer Donald Trump in the planned Northeast shuttle sale, that
would leave Eastern with 60 other ``excess aircraft for sale or
long-term lease,'' Ms. Ceremsak said.
   Pilots union spokesman J.B. Stokes said the unions oppose any
transfer of Eastern assets while hoping the bankruptcy court will
approve a buyout of the company.
   ``They can make all the plans they want,'' Stokes said. ``I
think they neglect to tell the people they must get approval from
the bankruptcy court. That's a fairly lengthy process and it's not
going to happen overnight.''
   The $365 million shuttle service sale also awaits approval by
the court, Stokes said.
</TEXT>
