<FIRST>r f PM-PilotSeniority     04-28 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pilot Seniority,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Deals Defeat To Texas Air On Pilot Seniority</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has dealt a defeat to Texas
Air Corp., ordering arbitration in a dispute over seniority between
pilots for subsidiaries Continental Airlines and now-defunct People
Express Airlines.
   Texas Air bought People Express in early 1987 and merged it into
Continental, creating the problem of how to combine pilot seniority
lists.
   Pilots for People Express, which had been based in Newark, sued
Texas Air in U.S. District Court here, alleging that the
Houston-based airline company reneged on its promise to fairly
combine the lists or turn to arbitration. The promise had been a
key part of the labor protection agreement included in the Texas
Air-People Express deal.
   U.S. District Judge Nicholas H. Politan heard three days of
testimony, including that of People Express founder and former
chairman Donald Burr, before ruling Monday.
   Politan found that Texas Air had ``decimated'' its own case
through vague and inconclusive testimony. The judge rejected an
argument by Texas Air that the labor protection agreement submitted
to the federal Department of Transportation was unsigned and
therefore not in force.
   He ordered both sides to submit court papers next week outlining
how the arbitration should be conducted.
   The issue of seniority is crucial to the 750 former People
Express pilots still with Texas Air and the 3,500 other Continental
pilots. It determines pay, flight schedules, vacation schedules,
where the pilots fly out of and the types of planes they fly, among
other factors.
</TEXT>
