<FIRST>r f PM-S&amp;LTakeovers     04-28 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;L Takeovers,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four More Taken Over: 2 in Calif., 1 in N.J., 1 in S.C.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-S&amp;Ls, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators have taken over four more
insolvent savings and loan associations in three states, bringing
the total under government control to 220 in 32 states.
   The institutions _ two in California, one in New Jersey and one
in South Carolina _ were the latest to be taken over in a program
being administered by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
   The institutions will maintain normal operations and all
deposits continue to be protected up to the $100,000 insurance
limit, regulators said Thursday. Government regulatory teams will
work to minimize operating losses and ensure that the institutions
are operated in a sound manner, the FDIC said.
   The FDIC, which began the takeover program at the direction of
President Bush on Feb. 7, is assuming control of the sickest S&amp;Ls
in an effort to reduce losses while Congress puts together a
program to restructure and bail out the troubled industry.
   The four institutions involved in Thursday's action are
Southwest Savings and Loan Association, Los Angeles; Wesco Savings
Bank Federal Savings Bank, Wilmington, Calif.; Metropolitan Federal
Savings &amp; Loan Association, Denville, N.J.; and Seabank Savings
Federal Savings Bank, Myrtle Beach, S.C.
