<FIRST>r f PM-MCI-Long-Distance     04-28 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-MCI-Long-Distance,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>MCI Announces Cheaper Off-Hours Calling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MCI Communications Corp. has unveiled a plan
that allows residential phone users to make an hour of interstate
long-distance calls, beginning at 7 p.m. weeknights, anywhere in
the country for $8 a month.
   Effective May 1, subscribers to the MCI Primetime plan announced
Thursday will get to make calls from 7 p.m. until 8 a.m. the
following day, all day Saturdays and Sundays until 5 p.m. at $8 an
hour and $6.80 for each additional hour.
   After the first hour, partial hours would be billed on a
pro-rated, per-minute basis. Callers also would get a 10 percent
discount for calls made at other times.
   A companion plan, MCI Supersaver, allows customers to make
interstate calls all day Saturday at $5 an hour.
   The company said the Supersaver plan is the lowest-priced
calling plan ever offered by any major long-distance company.
Neither plan applies to calls inside one state.
   ``It's the first to package the convenience and savings of MCI
long-distance in plans designed for when most consumers make their
calls,'' MCI President Bert Roberts said.
   ``You pay for the time _ the distance is free,'' said Timothy
Price, MCI vice president for consumer sales.
   Price said MCI's plan is better than the flat-rate Reach Out
America plan offered by American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. because
prices are 10 percent to 20 percent lower, the plan is simpler,
there is no installation charge and it allows weeknight calling
four hours earlier (7 p.m. for MCI versus 11 p.m. for AT&amp;T).
   Merrill Tutton, AT&amp;T's vice president for consumer services,
said AT&amp;T will offer a promotion next week for Reach Out America
but has no plans to respond directly to MCI.
   ``Millions of customers have signed up for that plan'' and have
stayed with it because of AT&amp;T's quality of service and incentives
such as discounts to travelers calling home, Tutton said.
   AT&amp;T on April 1 dropped daytime prices by 4.2 percent, while
evening rates dropped 0.7 percent and night-weekend prices
decreased 0.3 percent.
   Reach Out America prices dropped 2.6 percent.
   Roberts said the new plan did not mean MCI was de-emphasizing
the business market. MCI's recent earnings successes has put the
company in a position ``to accelerate our efforts in the
residential area,'' he said.
   MCI reported record first quarter 1989 earnings of $128 million,
compared with $58 million a year earlier.
</TEXT>
