<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     04-28 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was stable in thin European
trading today as the market settled down before a long holiday
weekend.
   Gold prices were lower.
   Traders said they expected the dollar to stay in a narrow
trading range unless the U.S. index of leading indicators, the only
significant economic news to be announced today, turned out to be a
surprise.
   Most traders expected the index, which was scheduled for release
this afternoon, to show a drop in March of about 0.5 percent,
following a decline of 0.3 percent in February.
   They said the dollar had appeared to have found a new trading
range for the time being.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6922, more expensive for
buyers than $1.6905 late Thursday.
   Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday's
rates, included: 1.8763 West German marks, up from 1.8756; 1.6625
Swiss francs, up from 1.6585; 6.3440 French francs, down from
6.3455; 2.1155 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1150; 1,373.25 Italian
lire, down from 1,373.50; and 1.1895 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1940.
   Earlier, the dollar rose in Tokyo to 132.49 Japanese yen from
132.05 yen at Thursday's close. Later, in London, the dollar edged
up further to 132.70 yen.
   Gold fell in Zurich to $380.50 a troy ounce, from $384.25 late
Thursday.
   In London, the metal opened at $381.50 a troy ounce, down from a
$384.25 late Thursday. At mid-morning, the city's bullion dealers
fixed a recommended price of $381.30.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at $382.89, lower than
$385.71 Thursday.
   Silver bullion dipped in London to $5.63 a troy ounce, down from
$5.76 bid late Thursday.
</TEXT>
