<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0935EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-Trade     04-28 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Trade,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan's Current Account Surplus Shrinks In Fiscal 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's current account surplus shrank 8.9 percent
in 1988, the second straight year in which the surplus in the broad
trade measure has contracted, the Finance Ministry said Friday.
   Analysts said the decline, to $76.97 billion in fiscal 1988 from
1987's $84.47 billion, was an encouraging sign for Japan, which is
trying to reduce its trade imbalance to ease tensions with its
trading partners.
   The current account is a comprehensive measurement of a nation's
international trade flows and includes imports and exports of goods
and services, earnings and expenditures on tourism, financial
investments and other transactions.
   The ministry said import growth outpaced export growth in the
fiscal year, which ended March 31. Imports grew 23.3 percent to
$171.83 billion from $139.40 billion the previous year, while
exports rose 14.4 percent to $267.10 billion from $233.44 billion.
   Strong domestic demand for manufactured goods helped boost
imports, ministry officials said.
   Japan's current account surplus for March, announced at the same
time, shrank to $6.32 billion from $8.33 billion a year earlier,
the ministry said. The surplus was also smaller than February's
$7.71 billion.
   Both exports and imports in the current account balance are
measured when contracts are settled, and are different from the
customs-clearance trade statistics that the ministry announces
separately each month.
   The ministry announcement did not include breakdowns of trade
figures by country or region.
</TEXT>
