<FIRST>r f PM-MortonThiokol     04-28 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Morton Thiokol,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Garrison Chosen CEO For New Thiokol Inc.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U. Edwin Garrison has been selected president and
chief executive officer of the new Thiokol Corp., the company to be
formed when Morton Thiokol Inc.'s aerospace and specialty chemical
divisions are separated.
   Garrison, 61, will be joined at the head of the new company by
Robert T. Marsh, 64, a retired U.S. Air Force general who was named
chairman of Thiokol's new board of directors, said spokesman Nancy
Hobor.
   Marsh is now a member of Morton Thiokol's board.
   Pending stockholder approval, Morton Thiokol Inc. will split to
become Morton International Inc. and Thiokol Corp. on July 1.
Morton International will contain the commercial businesses of
specialty chemicals, air bags for auto mobiles and salt.
   The split, proposed in late March, was described by industry
analysts as a move to separate two diverse business operations.
   Thiokol will include the company's aerospace operations. Morton
Thiokol employs 8,000 people in Utah, mostly at operations west of
Brigham City and at aerospace division headquarters in Ogden.
   Morton Thiokol is based in Chicago, which will remain the
corporate home of the new Morton International Inc. Charles S.
Locke, who is now chairman of Morton Thiokol, will become chairman
and chief executive officer of Morton International.
   Garrison is now president of the Aerospace Group of Morton
Thiokol, and is the corporation's vice president, positions he
assumed in 1983.
   A graduate of Mississippi State University and a native of
Alabama, he lives in Ogden.
   Marsh retired from the Air Force in 1984. In addition to Morton
Thiokol, he serves on the boards of Cimflex Teknowledge Corp., CAE
Link Corp. and ITHACO Corp. and as a trustee of MITRE Corp. He
lives in Alexandria, Va.
</TEXT>
