<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 1032EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-FarmExports 1stLd-Writethru   04-28 0750</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Exports, 1st Ld-Writethru,0772</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ag Panel Wants to Query Administration on Idled Export Program</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs pvs grafs 9-12, Meanwhile, the ... agreement, with 5 grafs
to clarify and explain the meeting with Soviets and the sales figures for
wheat and other commodities.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress may subpoena Bush administration
officials as part of its inquiry into why a popular program that
subsidizes food exports has apparently been halted with no official
notice.
   Though the Agriculture Department denies that the Export
Enhancement Program has been stopped, no sales using it have been
completed since February. And lawmakers allege that a
just-announced grain sale to the Soviets will be unsubsidized.
   ``Since the program started there has never been a two-month
hiatus,'' said Rep. Dan Glickman, D-Kan., who heads the House
Agriculture subcommittee on wheat, soybeans and feed grains.
   The holdup appears to be with the Office of Management and
Budget, where officials say a review of the program is taking place.
   When OMB representatives failed to appear before his
subcommittee Thursday, Glickman said he may have subpoena them.
   He said the administration's budget writers first would be given
a chance to answer questions in writing, but would be expected to
``respond quickly and satisfactorily.''
   Kelly Shipp, press secretary to Agriculture Secretary Clayton
Yeutter, said the program has slowed down because of weather and
stock conditions and because there is a new administration, but it
has not been suspended.
   Thomas Scully, associate director for legislative affairs at
OMB, said director Richard Darman couldn't make the hearing because
he had another obligation and no other policymaker at the budget
office was qualified to speak.
   Meanwhile, the Agriculture Department announced Thursday that
the Soviet Union, will be allowed to purchase 24 million metric
tons of grain this year instead of the 20 million previously
negotiated. Lawmakers said the additional sales will not be
subsidized.
   Only wheat has been subsidized in the grain sales to the Soviet
Union. Huge amounts of corn have been sold to the Soviets without
subsidies.
   The USDA also said U.S. and Soviet negotiators concluded a
two-day meeting about commodity purchases under a long-term grain
agreement that specifies regular sales of grain and soybeans during
the year. The pact calls for such meetings twice a year.
   In a separate announcement, USDA said the Soviet Union has
bought an additional 150,000 tons of corn, which boosted total
Soviet purchases of U.S. corn to 13.4 million tons. Moscow also has
bought 4 million tons of wheat for delivery through Sept. 30, the
end of the agreement's sixth year.
   According to USDA, the Soviets also have bought 450,000 tons of
soybeans, nearly 1.4 million tons of soybean meal and 507,400 tons
of grain sorghum for 1988-89 delivery.
   But a member of Glickman's subcommittee said the Soviets went
away from negotiations angry.
   The Soviets wanted to expand the amount to 30 million tons under
the Export Enhancement Program, but were told their purchases would
have to be unsubsidized, said Rep. David Nagle, D-Iowa.
   Attempts to contact Soviet officials at their embassy in
Washington were unsuccessful.
   Shipp said the agreement does not stipulate whether the EEP will
be used during the sale. She said the talks were about the amount
of grain the Soviets could buy, not its price.
   The EEP was started four years ago to entice foreign buyers who
were being lured away by countries that charged cheaper prices
because of heavy government subsidies.
   Through the program, buyers are given bonus quantities of
commodities if they buy a certain amount. The commodities come from
the surplus stock purchased previously by the federal government
from American farmers through other agricultural support programs.
   The fate of the EEP has been in question since April 18 when
Thomas Kay, the foreign agriculture service administrator, told a
Senate subcommittee that the agriculture department must hold all
new EEP initiatives until the program had been reviewed by the OMB.
   The Agriculture Department says that under the program $8
billion in farm products have been sold, including wheat, wheat
flour, vegetable oil, barley, barley malt, semolina, sorghum, rice,
poultry feed, dairy cattle, eggs and frozen poultry.
   Congress considers the program vital to U.S. strength during
international trade negotiations, known as the Uruguay Round, which
have been going on in Geneva.
   The U.S. position is that countries should remove or drastically
reduce subsidies that distort world prices and Congress believes
that the EEP puts the United States in a stronger bargaining
position.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890428-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 1050EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Emhart     04-28 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Emhart,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black &amp; Decker Wins 95 Percent of Emhart Stock in Tender Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOWSON, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black &amp; Decker Corp. said today it received
95 percent of the stock of Emart Corp. in a tender offer, enough to
complete a $2.8 billion takeover of the diversified manufaturing
company.
   Black &amp; Decker offered Emart shareholders $40 a share for their
stock. Based on a preliminary count today, about 95 percent of
Emart's outstanding shares were tendered under the offer, which
expired this morning.
   Black &amp; Decker will now authorize its banks to begin paying
shareholders. Although Emhart in effect comes under Black &amp; Decker
control today, the actual merger will take about 60 days to
complete, said Barbara Lucas, a Black &amp; Decker spokeswoman.
   Emhart shareholders who do not sell their stock to Black &amp;
Decker will be able to get $40 a share once the merger is final.
   Black &amp; Decker manufactures power tools and products for the
home and commercial applications.
   Emhart manufactures industrial and consumer products and
information electronic systems. The company makes Kwik Set locks,
True Temper tools, sporting goods, faucets, staplers, commercial
hardware and footwear materials.
   Black &amp; Decker has said it plans to sell Emhart's electronics
division, estimated to be worth $500 million, to help pay for the
acquisition.
   Analysts say Black &amp; Decker should be able to handle the debt,
but the company is not expected to turn a profit for about a year
and a half.
   Emhart had been fighting an unsolicited $2.4 billion takeover
offer from Topper L.P., a New York-based investment group that
includes oil heir Gordon P. Getty and the Fisher real estate family
of New York. The Topper offer amounted to $35 a share.
   Topper sold its Emhart shares late last month, effectively
ending its bid.
   Black &amp; Decker has been searching for a means to expand its
market after failing to take over two other companies.
   Last year the company tried to take over American Standard Inc.,
a New York-based maker of plumbing, heating and air-conditioning
equipment, but dropped the hostile offer after it was outbid by the
New York investment firm Kelson &amp; Co. Black &amp; Decker offered $2.4
billion for that company.
   In February, Black &amp; Decker's attempts to acquire Oster-Sunbeam
appliances were thwarted when Oster-Sunbeam's parent company,
Allegheny International Inc., accepted another offer.
   Black &amp; Decker offered $260 million for the Oster-Sunbeam
subsidiary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
