<DOCNO> AP890428-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 1108EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru   04-28 0811</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, 1st Ld-Writethru,0836</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lorenzo Hanging Tough; Striking Eastern Employees Hanging On</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: ADDS final graf to UPDATE with Pritzker reportedly submitting
bid; No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the strike gripping Eastern Airlines
approaches the end of its second month, boss Frank Lorenzo is
hanging tough.
   After rejecting buyout proposals and producing his own plan to
shrink the airline, Lorenzo seems to be playing a waiting game with
striking employees, who after nearly two months on the picket lines
may be under increasing pressure to find jobs again.
   Lorenzo also must contend with Eastern's creditors and with a
federal bankruptcy judge, who must approve the downsizing plan and
is pushing for a sale of Eastern in its entirety.
   ``It really continues to be a game of brinksmanship,'' said
Robert Decker, an airline industry analyst with Duff &amp; Phelps Inc.
in Chicago.
   The strike has become the longest major walkout against a U.S.
airline since the industry was deregulated in October 1978.
   After a 17-month wage dispute, Eastern's militant Machinists
struck the Miami-based carrier on March 4 and were joined by pilots
and flight attendants, virtually grounding the airline.
   Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern's parent Texas Air Corp., put
Eastern into Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection from creditors on
March 9.
   Employees' hopes were stirred April 6 when a group led by
ex-baseball commissioner Peter V. Ueberroth agreed to buy Eastern
for $464 million. Hopes soared a few days later when the unions
agreed to accept $210 million in wage concessions in exchange for a
30 percent stake in the carrier under the Ueberroth deal.
   But the proposal collapsed over the unions' demand that a
powerful trustee be appointed to replace Lorenzo as head of Eastern
before Ueberroth took over _ a term the Texas Air chief flatly
rejected.
   Lorenzo now insists that a sale of Eastern in its entirety no
longer is an option _ neither side will back down from their
trustee positions _ although billionaire hotel executive Jay
Pritzker, Trans World Airlines Chairman Carl C. Icahn and others
have expressed buyout interest.
   Instead, the airline on Monday detailed plans to operate at
one-third its pre-strike size and raise $1.8 billion by selling
assets, including planes, airport gates and landing slots at
unspecified locations.
   ``I think that was (Lorenzo's) intention all along,'' said
Andrew Geller, who follows the industry for Provident National Bank
in Philadelphia.
   As a first step, Eastern announced Thursday that it plans to
lease 14 Boeing 727-200s to Pan American World Airways for $96.6
million over five years, subject to bankruptcy court approval.
   Eastern is expected to announce more deals for leasing and
selling aircraft in the coming days, according to sources close to
the company.
   The plan is reminiscent of what Lorenzo did with Eastern's
sister carrier Continental Airlines in September 1983.
   After he put Continental into Chapter 11, he slashed the number
of employees to around 4,000 from 12,500 and brought the airline
out of bankruptcy protection as a non-union carrier.
   Now, due to 1985 amendments to the bankruptcy laws, Lorenzo
would first have to negotiate further with Eastern unions and
demonstrate that he had no alternative but to cut jobs.
   Some experts say Lorenzo's downsizing strategy could be aimed at
luring back striking pilots, who would lose seniority if they took
jobs at rival carriers.
   Under the plan, which would cut Eastern jobs from the pre-strike
31,200 to around 17,000, management reckons it would need about
1,700 pilots. The airline says it is hiring and training new pilots
at the rate of around 200 a month.
   ``It's the airline version of voodoo economics,'' said Jack
Bavis, head of Eastern's pilots union. ``And it's also designed to
intimidate the 3,300 Eastern pilots into abandoning the picket line
and returning to work.''
   Some observers say it may be difficult for Lorenzo to convince
creditors and U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland that the
airline will be able to recruit 1,700 pilots in a reasonable period
of time.
   Joel Zweibel, the lead attorney for the committee representing
Eastern's creditors, told The Associated Press the panel would need
about two weeks to form a judgment on Eastern's plan.
   There are still rumblings about a possible sale of the entire
airline.
   Lifland plans to hold a twice-postponed hearing next Wednesday
on the issue of selling Eastern in its entirety, icluding its
Northeast shuttle service the company already has agreed to sell to
developer Donald Trump for $365 million.
   Union officials and financial advisers continue to screen
potential bidders for Eastern; union sources said Thursday they
have held discussions with five suitors they consider credible.
   The pilots union leadership told its members late Thursday that
Pritzker has submitted his bid for the carrier and that Icahn has
requested confidential financial information from the bankruptcy
court as a prelude to making his buyout offer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
