<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 1134EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Airlines-Future     04-28 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Airlines-Future,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>America West Chief Paints Grim Picture of U.S. Air Industry Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reregulation is a real prospect facing
the domestic airline industry if current trends continue unabated,
an airline executive warned.
   Edward Beauvais, chairman of Phoenix-based America West
Airlines, painted a generally grim picture of the industry's
future, with fewer owners meaning lessened competition and higher
fares.
   Beauvais told the Aviation-Space Writers Association's annual
news conference Thursday that deregulation initially created a
highly competitive industry with low fares and a robust growth rate.
   But he said competitive balance has been destroyed by the
concentration of ownership.
   In addition, he said, entry barriers to gaining a market share
such as sophisticated computer reservation systems, access to
restricted airports such as New York City's LaGuardia and
Washington's National, and multibillion-dollar orders for new
planes by the major airlines have made it even more difficult for
the smaller carriers.
   ``If something isn't done, you've got an oligopoly with very
high fares and little competition,'' Beauvais said.
   That could create ``a groundswell of public opinion that could
mean the industry could experience reregulation,'' he said. ``If
the barrier-to-entry problems are not resolved, that will happen.''
   Beauvais said concern over the situation is starting to register
in Washington, but that it will take such things as ``even higher
prices, and they're going to get a lot higher, and several major
failures,'' to bring concerted reform efforts.
   The ongoing problems of strikebound Eastern Airlines, including
unsuccessful sale efforts amid Chapter 11 bankruptcy
reorganization, are part of that, he added. ``It's riveting the
attention of Washington on our industry right now,'' he said.
   Beauvais said he does not think the airline will fly again.
``I'm not sure Eastern can be successful as a smaller company,'' he
said. Eastern's management recently proposed a plan to rebuild as a
smaller carrier and sell around $1.8 billion in assets.
   As for his own 5-year-old airline, Beauvais said, ``We're not a
buyer and we're not a seller. We certainly don't think a hostile
takeover would be possible. We're not a classic target.''
   America West posted a $10.07 million first-quarter profit on
Wednesday, compared with a $16.32 million loss for the same period
last year.
</TEXT>
