<HEAD>Grain Prices Drop as Rains Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened lower today on
the Chicago Board of Trade as a steady rain fell on areas of Iowa
and Illinois.
   The rain has given rise to sentiment that the drought that has
plagued the area is over.
   ``We've had the best rain in Illinois in two years,'' said John
Frazier of Balfour Maclaine Corp. in Chicago. ``A lot of people are
saying the drought is over, and that's what's been supporting us
for a long time.''
   Soybean prices also are being affected by word that a Brazilian
dock strike is breaking up. Dockworkers gave their tentative
approval to a court-ordered pay raise.
   Uncertainty over the Bush administration's position on
continuing subsidized grain sales to foreign countries is putting
pressure on wheat prices.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent to 1{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.03{ a bushel; corn was 1 cent to
1{ cents lower with May at $2.67{ a bushel; oats were { cent to 3\
cents lower with May at $1.74 a bushel; soybeans were 3 cents to 8
cents lower with May at $7.23 a bushel.
   Cattle prices were higher on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange in
early trading, while pork prices were mostly lower.
   Live cattle were .15 cent to .38 cent higher with June at 71.20
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .50 cent to .80 cent higher with
May at 76.25 cents a pound; hogs were .27 cent lower to .05 cent
higher with June at 46.80 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.02 cent to .32 cent lower with May at 32.05 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed Thursday.
