<SECOND>PM-RJR Nabisco,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kohlberg Completes RJR Nabisco Buyout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The maverick buyout firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts
&amp; Co. said today it has completed its record $24.53 billion
acquisition of RJR Nabisco Inc.
   Trading in the company's stock on the New York Stock Exchange
was to cease at the end of the day.
   The completion of the deal that stunned Wall Street came a day
after shareholders formally approved the buyout at a special
meeting in Wilmington, Del. Company officials said about 85 percent
of RJR Nabisco's shares were voted in favor of the merger.
   Separately, RJR Nabisco announced Thursday that it would move
its headquarters from Atlanta to the New York City area by the end
of the year so the food-and-tobacco giant can be in close contact
with the financial community.
   The company will decide over the next few weeks whether layoffs
are necessary, said Pauline Howes, an RJR Nabisco spokeswoman.
About 450 RJR Nabisco employees work in Atlanta, she said.
   The move would be the second for RJR Nabisco corporate
headquarters in recent years. Former RJR President F. Ross Johnson
moved the headquarters from Winston-Salem to Atlanta after he took
over following the merger of R.J. Reynolds Industries Inc. and
Nabisco Brands Inc. in 1985.
   RJR Nabisco said its new chairman, Louis Gerstner Jr., sent a
letter to employees saying the plans of the firm can ``best be
achieved by maintaining close ongoing contact with the investment
banking community and other New York-based segments of the business
community.''
   The letter said relocations could begin by early summer and
would be completed by the end of the year.
   The exact location of RJR Nabisco's headquarters was not
announced. However, the firm's Nabisco Brands division is based in
New Jersey, also near New York.
</TEXT>
