<DOCNO> AP890428-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 2244EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-DisneyStudios Adv30 1stLd-Writethru 04-28 1162</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Disney Studios, Adv 30, 1st Ld-Writethru,1197</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday April 30</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hollywood Goes East: Studio Theme Park Set to Wow Disney World Crowds</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Corrects spelling of Grauman's in 5th graf; Ridgway in 17th
graf is cq</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $400 million blend of big-league
filming and Hollywood stargazing debuts Monday when Florida's top
entertainment resort opens the Disney-MGM Studios theme park, a
135-acre playground with diversions that range from do-it-yourself
music videos to a 1950s sitcom set.
   The complex at Walt Disney World combines working movie-TV sound
studios with backstage tours for the public, a mixed-media
ride-through show and other special effects adventures.
   ``It is a theatrical environment that is very close to the
original conception by Walt Disney,'' Michael Eisner, Walt Disney
Co. chairman, said in an interview. ``It's been on the shelf since
the 1940s and is the culmination of a company dream. This
attraction is unlike anything else we have.''
   It's all themed to the golden age of Hollywood in the 1930s and
1940s, when tyrannical cigar-chomping moguls ran studios and art
deco dominated the building scape.
   Mom, dad and the kids can walk through re-creations of
palm-lined Hollywood Boulevard and Grauman's Chinese Theater, peek
at movies under production, take a role in a television show, make
their own music videos, get a screen test and rub elbows with the
stars at the Brown Derby restaurant.
   Movie and TV production began last summer with the ``Superboy''
syndicated TV series and parts of several large-screen films while
construction continued on the tourist portion.
   The event was preceded by glitzy parties and previews that
included a television special, a parade of famous Hollywood actors
and actresses on the boulevard and live tapings of a mew ``Mickey
Mouse Club'' TV series.
   Dick Nunis, president of Walt Disney Attractions, said he
believes bringing a bit of Hollywood to Florida will reinvigorate
the resort, already visited annually by an estimated 25 million
people that reportedly pump about $2 billion into the area's
economy.
   ``We talked of doing a studio tour when Walt was alive,'' said
Nunis. ``We've wanted to do this for a long, long time. It's a
dream come true.''
   Disney will get a year's jump on some formidable competition in
the high-stakes family entertainment business, in which the company
founded by the late cartoonist has emerged as one of the undisputed
leaders. Universal Studios Florida is building a rival $500 million
complex to be finished next May.
   Just a few miles away, Universal is billed as the nation's
largest working studio outside of Hollywood. Movie and TV
production already is under way at the 440-acre facility owned by
MCA Inc. and Rank Organization PLC of London.
   Universal will feature what it calls a ``total experience'' of
Hollywood-style filmmaking to the public, making the visitor a
participant in the action. It expects to attract up to 6 million
visitors a year.
   Despite their well-publicized rivalry, Disney and MCA officials
insist the competition is good for each other as well as Florida,
where family-oriented entertainment has become one of the dominant
industries.
   ``We've always had competition _ from Sea World, Busch Gardens,
Cape Canaveral, Boardwalk and Baseball and many others,'' Eisner
said. ``We welcome competition. It's good for Central Florida.
Disney does things in its own way, and we feel comfortable that we
will have our niche in the community.''
   The Disney-MGM theme park is the centerpiece of a $1
billion-plus renaissance of the 27,400-acre resort in the pine
woods and citrus groves of central Florida, once populated largely
by alligators and armadillos before it opened 18 years ago.
   Not that a rebirth is needed.
   ``We're having a phenomenal year in both (hotel) occupancy and
(theme park) attendance,'' said Disney World publicist Charlie
Ridgway.
   After achieving a record $3.4 billion in revenues and $522
million in profits in fiscal 1988, Disney has on tap a number of
``openings'' at its Florida resort this year besides the studios.
   On schedule to open this fall is part of what it calls the
largest convention-hotel complex in the Southeast. Making their
debut this summer will be Typhoon Lagoon (``the world's largest
water park'') and the Pleasure Island nighttime entertainment
district.
   Built for the teen-age crowd, Nunis says Typhoon Lagoon will
make all other water attractions as obsolete as Disneyland made
amusement parks in 1955.
   ``We're finally going to be able to make waves,'' says Nunis.
``Surfing, a 100-foot mountain, a saltwater snorkling reef,
including sharks and other live critters (in an enclosed area). I
can hardly wait to put on my bathing suit.''
   Pleasure Island is for those who still have energy left at the
end of an exhausting day at the Disney-MGM Studios park, Epcot
Center or the Magic Kingdom. The complex of restaurants, shops and
nightclubs is built on a six-acre island at the Disney Village.
   Opening this fall is the 770-room Swan Hotel, which along with
the larger Dolphin Hotel will form the lodging side of the
convention-hotel complex near Epcot Center. The 1,500-room Dolphin
is to open in July 1990.
   The more modestly priced Caribbean Beach Resort hotel opens an
additional 800 rooms this summer for a total of 2,112. The 907-room
Grand Floridian Beach Resort, a luxury Victorian-style hotel,
opened last summer.
   Also set for completion this fall will be a new Epcot pavilion,
the Wonders of Life, featuring a simulated ride through the human
bloodstream and a movie that takes a viewer from conception through
birth.
   All Disney's doings are coming together during a busy start for
Florida tourism this year. More than 3.4 million tourists visited
the state in January, an 18.6 percent increase over the first month
of 1988, the Florida Department of Commerce says.
   State tourism officials predict the number of visitors will
increase 6 percent this year. That means the state would host 38.7
million tourists, vs. 36.6 million in 1988.
   Disney's Ridgway attributes the improved season to a generally
strong U.S. economy and a larger number of foreign tourists.
   For local Floridians, Disney World's building spree is one of
the main economic engines providing jobs.
   One of Disney's most-popular spots is the employment office,
currently hiring 2,500 new workers at a minimum pay of $5 an hour
to help staff new attractions that will swell the Disney complex's
workforce to about 28,000, nearly twice the level of eight years
ago.
   The new attractions also have prompted a $1 increase in one-day
admission prices at the Magic Kingdom and Epcot Center and the
introduction of a new four-day passport good at any of the three
theme parks, effective Monday.
   The new ticket will cost $94 for adults and $77 for children 3
to 9 years old. It provides unlimited admission to the three parks
for four days. New single-day admission prices for any one park
will be $29 for adults and $23 for children.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday, April 30</NOTE>
