<FIRST>u f AM-Unilever-Faberge Bjt   04-28 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Unilever-Faberge, Bjt,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Takeover Plan Terminated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unilever, the European consumer products
conglomerate, Friday said it dropped its plan to purchase the
Faberge and Elizabeth Arden lines of toiletries, cosmetics and
fragrances for $1.55 billion from Riklis Family Corp.
   Negotiations on a definitive pact broke down because the Riklis
group sought ``significant changes in the structure and terms of
the transaction which would have involved Unilever in substantial
additional costs,'' according to an announcement from Unilever
United States Inc., the U.S. arm of the British-Dutch household and
consumer products giant.
   The proposed all-cash acquisition from New York investor
Meshulam Riklis' Riklis Family Corp. had been approved in principle
on Feb. 10.
   Details of a formal agreement had been expected to be worked out
during talks that were to be concluded within 90 days.
   ``At the agreed price the acquisition of Faberge and Elizabeth
Arden would have been an important step forward in our strategy for
personal products,'' a Unilever spokesman said. ``They now appear
to be available only with a construction and price which do not
represent reasonable value to our shareholders.''
   Unilever spokesman David Lustig declined to disclose the Riklis
demands, saying he was prohibited from doing so by a
confidentiality agreement.
   The Riklis group also refused to comment.
   Under the February agreement, Unilever was to buy all of Faberge
Inc. except for the McGregor Apparel Group, which comprises
clothing lines such as Botany 500, Wonderknit and Billy the Kid.
   Among some of the name brands of Faberge and of its independent
subsidiary Elizabeth Arden that Unilever would have gotten were
Visible Difference, Chloe, Lagerfeld, Flawless Finish, Aqua Net and
Brut.
   It had been expected that as part of the acquisition Unilever
would gain the Faberge name and Faberge Inc. would switch its name
to McGregor. It had not been specified whether the Faberge and
Elizabeth Arden lines would be folded into Uniliver's U.S. division
or its British or Dutch companies called Unilever PLC and Unilever
NV, respectively.
   Faberge was bought by the Riklis group in 1984 for about $180
million. The holding company acquired Elizabeth Arden for $700
million at the end of 1987. Other Riklis holdings include Samsonite
luggage and Culligan water softeners.
   Through acquisitions and internal growth, Unilever for several
years has been building its personal products operations around the
world. It has targeted several segments of the market for further
expansion, among them the prestige end of the fragrance and beauty
aid business.
   Two years ago, Unilever bought Chesebrough-Pond's Inc. for $3.1
billion, thereby acquiring many widely known personal-care
products, including several prestige, or expensive, lines such as
the Prince Matchabelli fragrance collection. Unilever also owns
Elizabeth Taylor's Passion scents.
   Lustig said the prestige portion of the personal products
business appeals to Unilever because it has been growing strongly
and has not been fully exploited, particularly in the Far East and
other parts of the world.
   Prestige items account for an estimated $8 billion, or 20
percent, of the overall personal products market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
