<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   04-28 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0262</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices closed sharply higher Friday
on the Chicago Board of Trade as speculation continued on what
position the Bush administration will take on whether to continue
subsidized grain sales to foreign countries.
   Corn futures were lower, oat futures rose and soybeans fell as
rains continued in Illinois and Iowa.
   Wheat prices climbed as word spread of a second U.S. economic
policy committee meeting in Washington on the issue of subsidized
grain sales.
   ``Everyone is waiting to hear a final decision,'' said Ted Mao,
an analyst for Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York. ``Wheat is
more a political market than a drought market.''
   The Export Enhancement Program was begun several years ago as a
means of reducing U.S. grain stockpiles, but stocks were drained to
such low levels last year that some officials want to end the
program.
   Soybeans were pushed lower by word that the Brazilian dock
strike was breaking up after dockworkers gave their tentative
approval to a court-ordered pay raise.
   Corn prices were affected by heavy rains in the Corn Belt.
   At the close, wheat was 4{ cents to 12{ cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.17{ cents a bushel; corn was 1{
cents lower to } cent higher with May at $2.69{ a bushel; oats were
} cent to 3 cents higher with May at $1.78 a bushel; soybeans were
2} cents to 7 cents lower with May at $7.22{ a bushel.
