<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Kellogg     04-28 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Kellogg,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earnings Down 8 Percent Without Accounting Change</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATTLE CREEK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kellogg Co. said Friday its
first-quarter profit rose 31.7 percent, but would have fallen 8
percent if not for a one-time gain from an accounting change.
   The cereal company reported earning $111.4 million, or 91 cents
a share, during the first three months of this year, without the
effects of the accounting change, compared with first-quarter
earnings of $121.1 million, or 98 cents a share, during the same
time last year.
   The change in how the company accounted for its income taxes
boosted first-quarter 1989 earnings to $159.5 million, or $1.30 a
share.
   Sales during the first three months of this year rose 10.1
percent to $1.13 billion this year compared with $1.03 billion last
year.
   ``Market conditions were extremely competitive and investments
in developing new products and marketing our products around the
world were at record levels,'' Chairman William LaMothe said. ``We
remain optimistic that our business will continue to experience
strong growth, particularly in international markets.''
   LaMothe also said the board of directors had authorized
management to buy up to $100 million worth of Kellogg stock during
the next 12 months. It was the third straight year that the board
gave management authority to repurchase the stock.
</TEXT>
