<DOCNO> AP890428-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 1605EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-ColtSale     04-28 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colt Sale,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colt Firearms Up For Sale</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colt Firearms, maker of the gun that won
the West, was put on the auction block Friday, but the company's
parent denied a three-year struggle with striking workers prompted
the decision.
   ``It's a going business and it's profitable, and, of course, it
has a history of quality products,'' said Michael G. Dunn, a
spokesman for Colt Firearms' parent, Colt Industries Inc.
   Dunn said senior officials at New York-based Colt Industries
decided to sell the firearms division so they could concentrate on
the company's aerospace, automotive and industrial service
operations.
   A continuing strike and the recent loss of a contract to produce
M-16 rifles for the military didn't prompt the action, he added.
   Dunn declined to say whether privately held Colt Industries had
received any bids or how much the company is asking for the unit.
Morgan Stanley Group Inc. has been hired to evaluate any offers.
   Analysts said proceeds from the sale could be used to help
retire debt incurred when Colt Industries' management mounted a
$660 million leveraged buyout a year ago.
   Maeda Klein, a vice president with Donaldson Lufkin &amp; Jenrette,
estimated Colt's outstanding debt at $1.8 billion.
   The 1,100 employees at Colt Firearms' two plants in Hartford and
West Hartford were informed of the decision Friday morning.
   ``I think it might be a good omen,'' said Robert Madore,
president of United Auto Workers Local 376. The union represented
about 1,000 blue-collar workers who walked off their jobs on Jan.
24, 1986, in a dispute over wages and benefits.
   ``I think maybe a new face, a new owner might turn it around,''
Madore said. He said the union could make an offer to buy the
company, but he cautioned that such a move hasn't yet been
discussed with the membership.
   Colt has managed to keep its plants operating by hiring
replacement workers and using about 200 strikers who crossed picket
lines.
   The dispute is now before the National Labor Relations Board,
where the union is seeking about $40 million in back wages and job
reinstatement.
   Klein said a change in management could help end the walkout.
``Maybe there's an easy way out if you bring in a new company
culture,'' she said.
   But State Rep. Joseph A. Adamo, D-West Haven, said the sale
could ``very well leave those (striking) workers in the lurch. It
could be devastating.''
   The Colt company was founded in Hartford in 1836 by Samuel Colt,
the inventor of the first successful repeating pistol. The pistol
had a cylinder of several chambers that could be discharged in
succession by the same locking and firing mechanism.
   It was after the entrepreneur's death in 1862 that his company
manufactered the six-shooter that every cowboy carried in his
holster and was said to have won the West.
   In addition to the M-16 rifle, the standard Army-issue rifle
still used today, Colt manufactures the Colt 45 handgun, the King
Cobra magnum revolver and the AR-15 rifle.
   Colt had produced the M-16 rifle for the Army since 1964. But in
October 1988, the Army announced that it was dropping Colt after it
was underbid for a contract to produce about one million rifles by
FN Manufacturing Inc. of Columbia, S.C. FN manufacturing is owned
by the Belgian firm, Fabrique Nationale S.A.
   Colt gained national attention in March when it voluntarily
decided to halt the sale of its semi-automatic rifles in response
to public outcry to the murder of California school-children by a
man using a similar assault weapon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
