<FIRST>r f AM-Knight-Ridder     04-28 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Knight-Ridder,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shareholders Adopt Anti-Takeover Measures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Knight-Ridder Inc. shareholders adopted measures
Friday to fend off unwanted takeover bids and major stock
acquisitions by foreigners, the company said.
   Mergers and other major stock purchases would have to be
approved by holders of 80 percent of the media company's common
stock, not including shares owned by the prospective buyer.
   An exemption could be made if the company's board, acting on a
recommendation from a panel of independent journalism experts,
backed the transaction.
   An 80 percent vote also would be needed to approve any stock
purchase that would result in foreign ownership of more than 20
percent of the company.
   Actions by shareholders at the annual meeting weren't triggered
by any actual efforts to buy company stock, said Knight-Ridder
spokeswoman Lee Ann Schlatter.
   ``There have been no rumors and no activity whatsoever that
we're aware of,'' she said. ``This really just has to do with the
business climate that we exist in, in which business takeovers are
becoming a part of our way of life.''
   Shareholders also agreed to reserve an additional 3.5 million
shares of common stock for the company's employee stock-option plan.
   Knight-Ridder is an international communications company that
publishes 30 daily newspapers and six suburban weeklies.
   The company has contracts to sell its eight television stations,
the Pasadena, Calif., Star-News and four smaller papers in the
area. Negotiations also are under way to sell the Post-Tribune in
Gary, Ind.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
