<DOCNO> AP890428-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 2048EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CampeauRestructures     04-28 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Campeau Restructures,0681</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parent Of Bloomingdale's and Other Chain Stores Restructures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Campeau Corp.'s board of directors Friday announced a
realignment that establishes Campeau as a holding company for its
real estate and retailing operations in the United States and
Canada.
   The restructuring of the Toronto-based corporation came as the
result of a process that has been in the works since Campeau
acquired Federated Department Stores Inc. in a $6.7 billion hostile
takeover last May.
   Robert Campeau will continue as chairman and chief executive.
Ronald W. Tysoe, formerly executive vice president and president of
Campeau (U.S.), will take over as president and chief operating
officer of the newly restructured company.
   Tysoe replaces James T. Roddy, whose resignation was disclosed
Thursday.
   Roddy, 45, and a veteran of the retail business, worked closely
on the takeover of Federated. There was no word on Roddy's plans
and an announcement Friday from Campeau said only that he was
leaving to pursue other career interests.
   Carolyn Buck Luce, a Campeau senior vice president who had been
involved with financial nuts and bolts of the Federated purchase,
also submitted her resignation.
   Retail industry analysts said the changes in the corporate
parent should have little direct bearing on Campeau's department
store businesses.
   Federated operates Abraham and Straus, Bloomingdale's, Burdines
and other chain stores. Also under Campeau's corporate umbrella is
Allied Stores Corp., which Campeau acquired in 1986 for $3.4
billion. Allied and Federated have headquarters in Cincinnati.
   Pamela Stubing, an analyst with Moody's Investors Service Inc.,
said the changes at Campeau could end up being beneficial for
Allied and Federated.
   ``I'm told that ... the people at the Allied-Federated level
will have more say in day-to-day operations and strategies going
forward,'' said Stubing. ``I think that's good. There's always a
danger when there are decisions being made one level removed.''
   She said Moody's doesn't intend to initiate a review of the
ratings it has assigned to Allied and Federated debt on account of
Campeau's restructuring. Moody's is a leading credit rating agency
and its opinions can influence the interest rates corporations are
charged to borrow money.
   ``I'm just waiting for the second half of the year to see how
that transpires,'' she said, noting that the second six months of
the calendar year is the most important time for retailers.
   Campeau said the reorganization ``reflects the evolution'' that
began in 1985 with ``our decision to grow beyond our Canadian real
estate roots and to acquire certain prime U.S. retail interests.''
   ``We have made tremendous progress in the last year in
accomplishing our strategies for asset acquisition and
restructuring, as well as debt reduction and corporate financing,''
the company stated.
   Under the restructuring, separate subsidiaries will report to
the Campeau holding company. These are: Federated and Allied, which
together form the department store group; Ralphs Grocery Co., the
California supermarket unit; Campeau Development Corp., the U.S.
real estate group; and Campeau Canada, the Canadian real estate
development concern.
   Two additional executive changes were announced.
   Paul Campbell, currently senior vice president for the Eastern
region of Campeau Corp., has been named president of the
restructured Campeau Canada, which comprises all of the company's
commercial real estate and shopping center interests in Canada.
   Russell S. Davis, executive vice president and chief financial
officer of Federated and Allied, will expand his responsibilities
and also become chief financial officer for the Campeau holding
company. He succeeds Roger Ashton who resigned to return to a
partnership position at a Toronto accounting firm.
   In a separate announcement, Campeau reported its financial
results for the year ended Jan. 31, 1989.
   Campeau said its net loss came to $34 million in the latest
period, an improvement from a loss of $196 million in the 13 months
ended Jan. 31, 1988.
   Revenue from continuing operations rose to $8.67 billion,
boosted by the acquisition of Federated and Ralphs, compared to
$3.53 billion in the 13-month period a year earlier.
</TEXT>
