<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     04-28 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises Despite Intervention</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede: LONDON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose sharply against all major
currencies except the Canadian dollar Friday despite central bank
intervention and further indications that the U.S. economy is
losing steam.
   Gold prices took a tumble. Republic National Bank of New York
quoted a bid price for gold of $377.50 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m.
EDT, down from Thursday's late bid of $382.30.
   A Commerce Department report showing the government's chief
economic forecasting gauge slipped 0.7 percent in March failed to
halt the dollar's rise both at home and abroad.
   The drop in the index of leading indicators, which marked the
first back-to-back declines in more than a year, was interpreted as
another sign the economy is cooling, and analysts predicted the
slowdown will become more pronounced later this year.
   Dealers also noted that coordinated central bank intervention,
begun by the Swiss central bank and followed by the central banks
of the United States, Britain, West Germany, Italy and France,
failed to stem the dollar's rise.
   ``The dollar has been firm all day; it's just ignoring the
numbers,'' said Earl Johnson, a vice president at Harris Trust and
Savings Bank in Chicago.
   Even though the Federal Reserve appears unlikely to tighten
credit by hiking interest rates, Johnson said investors still feel
U.S. interest rates are attractive. Higher interest rates make
dollar-denominated securities more attractive.
   Jack Barbanel, a senior vice president at Gruntal &amp; Co., also
noted that foreign investors continue to view the U.S. economy as
relatively strong.
   ``Possibly they feel that even if we have a slowdown that leads
to a recession, they're much better off with dollars because if the
U.S. goes into a recession, we will really have a global
recession,'' he said.
   Earlier in Tokyo, the dollar closed at 132.49 Japanese yen, up
from 132.05 late Thursday. Later in London, the dollar traded
higher at 133.00 yen. In New York the dollar rose to 133.05 yen,
from 132.12 yen on Thursday.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6845 late Friday, cheaper
for buyers than Thursday's late $1.6905. In New York the pound cost
$1.6855, less expensive than $1.6910 late Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday's rates, included: 1.8810 West German marks, up from
1.8760; 1.6755 Swiss francs, up from 1.6586; 6.3580 French francs,
up from 6.3475; 1,377.00 Italian lire, up from 1,374.25, and 1.1853
Canadian dollars, down from 1.1920.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with Thursday's late
rates, included: 1.8805 West German marks, up from 1.8756; 1.6742
Swiss francs, up from 1.6585; 6.3650 French francs, up from 6.3455;
2.1220 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1150; 1,377.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,373.50, and 1.1835 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1940.
   Gold prices slumped worldwide. On the Commodity Exchange in New
York, gold bullion for current delivery fell to $377.90 a troy
ounce, from Wednesday's $383.30.
   The late bid gold price in London was $378.25 a troy ounce, down
from $384.25. The Zurich, late bid price was $377.75, down from
$384.25. Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $381.85 bid, down
from $385.15.
   Silver bullion prices also slipped. On the New York Comex,
silver bullion for current delivery settled at $5.601 a troy ounce,
down from Thursday's close of $5.645. In London, silver traded at a
late bid price of $5.63 a troy ounce, down from $5.76.
</TEXT>
