<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 1827EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     04-28 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices fell Friday despite economic
statistics indicating that the economy is cooling and interest
rates may ease.
   The credit market's bellwether 30-year Treasury issue was down [
point, or $1.25 for every $1,000 face amount. Its yield, which
moves inversely to price, rose to 8.92 percent from 8.90 percent
late Thursday.
   The Commerce Department said its chief economic forecasting
gauge plunged 0.7 percent in March, the second straight decline and
the biggest drop in eight months.
   It was the first time the Index of Leading Economic Indicators,
which dropped 0.3 percent in February, posted back-to-back declines
since it fell for five straight months from September 1987 through
January 1988.
   Analysts said the 30-year bond gained slightly after the
economic data was announced, but the gains dwindled throughout the
day.
   ``After the run we've had this week, I think investors were
saying perhaps it's time to take a breather,'' said Harold Nathan,
a portfolio manager with Wells Fargo &amp; Co. in San Francisco.
   ``I think we will need some further signs of moderating
inflation and economic growth before we get any further significant
rally,'' he said.
   Bond traders used the opportunity to take profits following a
runup in the previous session, analysts said. The 30-year bond rose
{ point Thursday.
   Analysts said the latest negative signals are in line with signs
that the U.S. economy is losing steam. The prospects of slower
growth ``is appeasing the market for now,'' said Mitchell Held,
chief financial economist at Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co.
   In the secondary market for Treasury securities, prices of
short-term securities were down from 1-16 point to 5-32 point,
intermediate governments fell 3-32 point to 7-32 point and
long-term maturities slumped from [ point to 3-16 point, according
to Telerate Inc., a financial information service.
   The movement of a point equals a change of $10 in the price of a
bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, fell 2.06 to 1,132.74.
   Corporate issues advanced. Moody's Investment Grade Corporate
Bond Index, which measures total return on a portfolio of 80
corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, rose 0.41
to 304.49.
   The Bond Buyer index was unavailable.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills leaped to 8.78 percent as
the discount rose 13 basis points to 8.49 percent. Yields on
six-month bills rose to 9.05 percent as the discount rose 9 basis
points to 8.55 percent. Yields on one-year bills rose to 9.19
percent as the discount gained 10 basis points to 8.51 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, traded at 913-16 percent, unchanged from late Thursday.
</TEXT>
