<FIRST>r f AM-IGA-Japan     04-28 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IGA-Japan,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>IGA Makes Move into Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   IGA Inc., the country's fourth-largest retail
food operation, says it will move into the Japanese market by
offering chain-style services to independent grocers there.
   The Chicago-based cooperative, which includes about 3,000
independent U.S. grocers and six of the seven largest U.S.
wholesale food distributors, expects to have 1,000 stores in Japan
within the next five years, said Chairman Thomas S. Haggai.
   IGA, which stands for Independent Grocers Alliance, is the first
U.S. supermarket retailer to enter the Japanese market, Haggai said
Thursday.
   IGA said small, independent grocers in Japan have been losing
their market share to newly emerging supermarket chains.
   IGA and its Japanese partner, C. Itoh Food Systems, a division
of C. Itoh &amp; Co. Ltd., will offer marketing, training and
operations services to independent grocers in return for a
percentage of their sales.
   But even more significant to IGA is the opportunity to sell IGA
brand merchandise, which includes more than 2,500 products, on
Japanese store shelves.
   ``If IGA products become 10 percent of a (Japanese) store's
sales, that could mean as much as $100 million a year to us,'' said
Karl Sheffield, a food-industry consultant with Chandler, Leigh &amp;
Co. who is advising IGA on the Japanese venture.
</TEXT>
