<FIRST>u f AM-Heileman-Stroh     04-28 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Heileman-Stroh,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Is There A Stroh-Heileman Beer In The Future?</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   G. Heileman Brewing Co. officials have
discussed buying a minority interest in the Stroh Brewery Co.,
touching off speculation about a possible merger between two of the
nation's largest beer companies.
   But analysts question whether such a deal could clear federal
antitrust laws.
   Stroh officials several weeks ago announced their willingness to
sell a minority interest in the Detroit-based company, the
third-largest brewer in the United States.
   The speculation about a merger was touched off when Murray
Cutbush, president and chief executive officer of La Crosse-based
Heileman, disclosed Thursday that representatives from his company
were in Detroit to meet with Stroh officials.
   Heileman, which was bought by Australia's Bond Corp. in 1987, is
the nation's No. 5 brewer, with a 1988 estimate of 15.4 million
barrels.
   Lacey Logan, a Stroh spokeswoman, said Friday that Stroh ``is in
the process of finding an international minority investment partner
or partners'' for ``opportunities available to Stroh outside of the
United States.''
   She said that Stroh ``has been having ongoing meetings with a
number of international brewers.''
   Stroh shipped an estimated 20.6 million barrels in 1988, far
behind the 40.5 million shipped by the Miller Brewing Co., which is
the country's second largest brewer.
   Anheuser-Busch Cos. Inc. was No. 1 with a 1988 estimate of 78.5
million barrels.
   Industry analysts have predicted competitors of Anheuser and
Miller might need to consolidate in order to challenge the
companies on a national level.
   ``Stroh and Heileman would be a sensible merger,'' said Robert
Weinberg, an industry analyst and professor of marketing management
at Washington University in St. Louis.
   ``Heileman has a lot of volume, but not good infrastructure,''
he said. ``Stroh has good infrastructure, but they don't have a lot
of volume.''
   ``You're looking at creating a brewer the approximate size of
Miller,'' he said.
   One major obstacle, however, could be antitrust laws, which
blocked earlier attempts by Heileman to buy both the Jos. Schlitz
Brewing Co. and Pabst Brewing Co. Schlitz was later bought by Stroh.
   ``If I were a smaller company, I would be squealing like a
pig,'' Weinberg said.
   If such a merger were proposed, he said, a critical issue would
be whether the combination of Stroh and Heileman would increase
competition within the industry or reduce it.
   In his remarks Thursday to the Wisconsin Wholesale Beer
Distributors Association, Cutbush predicted that a third major
player would emerge in the U.S. brewing industry within five years,
and he said Heileman intended to be that player.
   ``It's a long way between the beginning of negotiations and the
completion of negotiations,'' said Jerry Steinman, publisher of the
industry newletter, Beer Marketer's Insights. ``And a lot of
negotiations never bear fruit.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
