<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     04-28 0669</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0693</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precious Metals Prices Drop On Signs Of Slowing Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Precious metals prices dropped sharply Friday as evidence of a
slowing U.S. economy continued to mount.
   The decline was led by gold, which tumbled on New York's
Commodity Exchange to a new low for the May contract.
   On other markets, wheat prices rose while corn and soybean
prices fell; cattle prices rallied but hog prices retreated; and
energy prices were mixed.
   Gold settled $5.40 to $6.20 lower with the contract for delivery
in May at $377.90 a troy ounce; silver was 4.4 cents to 7 cents
lower with May at $5.601 a troy ounce; platinum settled at $21.70
to $17.70 lower with July at $534.50 a troy ounce .
   The sell-off was largely a response to the Commerce Department's
report Friday that the index of leading economic indicators plunged
0.7 percent in March. It was the second consecutive decline in the
index and the sharpest in eight months.
   Precious metals, especially gold, are traditionally seen as safe
investments during periods of rising inflation. An economic
slowdown would likely result in less inflation.
   Platinum prices had risen sharply earlier in the week and
although supply factors are bullish, ``there is a lot of
uncertainty in the amount of demand,'' said George Anagnos of
Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc.
   Analysts attributed the drop in silver prices to the Commodity
Exchange's report of a relatively large amount of the metal _ 200
million ounces _ in exchange-approved warehouses. The stockpile
equals about 20 months of demand, Anagnos said.
   Wheat closed sharply higher on the Chicago Board of Trade as
speculation continued on what position the Bush administration will
take on whether to continue subsidized grain sales to foreign
countries.
   Corn futures were lower, oat futures rose and soybeans fell as
rains continued in Illinois and Iowa.
   Soybeans also were pressured by word that the Brazilian dock
strike was breaking up after dockworkers gave their tentative
approval to a court-ordered pay raise.
   Corn for May delivery was boosted by rumors of a major sale to
the Soviet Union. After the close, the Agriculture Department
announced the sale of 1.05 million metric tons of corn to the
Soviets.
   Wheat settled 5{ cents to 12{ cents higher, with the contract
for delivery in May at $4.17{ cents a bushel; corn was 1{ cents
lower to { cent higher with May at $2.69\ a bushel; oats were }
cent to 3 cents higher with May at $1.78 a bushel; soybeans were 3
cents to 7 cents lower with May at $7.22{ a bushel.
   Cattle prices were up while hogs and pork bellies fell on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Cattle futures tried to go lower early in the session, but
rallied late, an indication that cattle prices may have found a
long-awaited bottom, said Dale Durchholz, an analyst with
Agri-Visor Services Inc. in Bloomington, Ill.
   Hog prices were pushed lower by commercial selling and ideas
that wholesale pork-product prices would decrease next week.
   Cattle settled .35 cent lower to .63 higher with June at 71.45
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to .70 cent higher with
May at 76.52 cents a pound; hogs were .03 cent to .45 cent lower
with June at 46.62 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .47 cent
to 1 cent lower with May at 31.37 cents a pound.
   Petroleum futures settled mixed on the New York Mercantile
Exchange as traders sold before the expiration of gasoline and
heating-oil contracts.
   Crude prices were weak in anticipation of the restart of
production at the Brent oil field in the North Sea. Production was
cut by a platform accident last week.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 49 cents lower to 57
cents higher with June at $20.43 a barrel; heating oil was .10 cent
lower to .50 cent higher with May at 51.70 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .13 cent to 3.91 cents lower with May at 74.21 cents a
gallon.
</TEXT>
