<FIRST>r f AM-Hewlett-Packard-Brazil     04-28 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hewlett-Packard-Brazil,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hewlett Packard to Expand Market with New Partnership</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hewlett-Packard Co. will expand
operations in the Brazilian market under a new strategic
partnership with a major company there, company officials announced
Friday.
   Under the agreement, a new company will be formed by combining
three existing companies. Brazil is the seventh-largest computer
market in the world and Hewlett-Packard, a manufacturer of
computers and scientific equipment, has been active in the country
since 1967.
   ``This consolidation will create the only computer company in
Brazil capable of offering customers a full range of computing
solutions, from calculators to super-minicomputers,'' said Manuel
F. Diaz, general manager of Hewlett-Packard's Latin America region,
which includes Brazil.
   Under the partnership with Companhia Iochpe de Participacoes of
Brazil, a new company called Edisa Informatica SA, will be
established.
   The three existing companies are Edisa-Electronica Digital, a
subsidiary of Iochpe; Tesis Informatica, an Iochpe company that
sells Hewlett-Packard computer products; and Hewlett-Packard Do
Brasil SA, a company jointly owned by Iochpe and Hewlett-Packard.
   Brazilian nationals will be shareholders of the new company and
Iochpe will be the controlling shareholder. Hewlett-Packard will
provide technology and support to the new company, which will have
its headquarters in Alphaville, Sao Paulo. It will have offices in
11 major Brazilian cities, and manufacturing facilities will be
established in three cities, officials said.
   Flavio Sehn, 55, has been named president of the new firm. Sehn
has been president of Edisa-Electronica Digital for four years.
   Iochpe has operations in agriculture, paper manufacturing,
machinery, electronics, data processing, banking and insurance.
</TEXT>
