<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     04-28 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Prices Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Petroleum futures finished mixed Friday, with
gasoline falling for the second straight day after the recent steep
rise in prices.
   The May gasoline contract declined sharply as it expired Friday
on the New York Mercantile Exchange. The contract closed 3.91 cents
lower than Thursday's session at 74.21 a gallon. Other contract
months lost between 1.05 and 0.13 cents.
   Crude oil finished mostly higher on the exchange, but the June
contract fell 50 cents to end the day at $20.42 a barrel. The July
contract remained flat at $19.34 a barrel.
   Heating oil was mixed with the May contract gaining 0.34 cent on
the expiration of the contract to finish at 52.20 cents a gallon.
   Gasoline has been the focus of market attention recently because
of expectations of tight supplies for the summer driving season,
largely because of new higher octane regulations scheduled to take
effect soon.
   But worries of even tighter supplies following the spill off the
Alaskan coast last month and a North Sea explosion recently have
sent prices zooming, at the wholesale and retail levels.
   Analysts have said, however, that although there might be a
tightness in the gasoline market this summer, a supply shortage is
unlikely.
</TEXT>
