<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 0039EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-FurnitureSuits     04-28 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Furniture Suits,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Office Furniture Wars Heat Up As Steelcase Files Suit Against Haworth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three months after a federal appeals
court ruled that Steelcase Inc. violated patents held by Haworth
Inc., the office furniture giant has turned the tables.
   Steelcase filed a lawsuit Wednesday in federal court contending
the smaller Holland-based company has infringed on two Steelcase
patents, one granted in 1980 and the second in 1984.
   Both are for panel electrical wiring systems, according to the
lawsuit.
   Steelcase insists the lawsuit is neither related to nor in
retaliation for an earlier one filed by Haworth now before the U.S.
Supreme Court.
   While both lawsuits involve the electrical system in the two
companies' panel systems, Steelcase spokesman Peter Jeff said:
``They're different patents and different issues. ... It's the same
church, but it's a different pew.''
   Haworth, the nation's third-largest office furniture maker, sued
Steelcase in 1985, claiming the industry leader was infringing on
Haworth patents when it designed, made and sold certain pre-wired
office panels.
   U.S. District Judge Richard Enslen last year ruled in favor of
Steelcase, but a federal appeals court reversed that opinion in
January, ruling for Haworth. Steelcase appealed to the nation's
highest court.
   Steelcase could end up paying hundreds of millions of dollars to
Haworth if the ruling stands.
   Haworth spokesman Richard Planck said Thursday the company would
have no comment until it receives formal notification of the
lawsuit.
</TEXT>
