<FILEID>AP-NR-04-28-89 2129EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-MAIBasic     04-28 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-MAI Basic,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>MAI Basic Earnings Drop 61.8 Percent in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUSTIN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MAI Basic Four Inc., which designs and
makes business computers, said Friday that earnings dropped nearly
62 percent in the first three months of 1989 due in part to efforts
to acquire Prime Computer.
   Other factors contributing to the decline were a slowdown in the
mid-range computer industry and a softened dollar overseas, the
company said.
   Earnings for the second quarter ended March 31 declined to $2.4
million, or 16 cents per share, from $6.3 million, or 42 cents per
share, for the same quarter last year.
   ``Although our period earnings declined compared to last year,
through prudent expense controls we were able to achieve an
operating income margin of 12.8 percent for the six months ended
March 31, 1989, an excellent result in the context of the current
industry-wide slowdown,'' said William B. Patton Jr., president and
chief executive officer.
   Revenue for the quarter declined from $105.4 million in 1988 to
$104.7 million this year, the company said.
   The company said Prime Computer's resistance to a MAI tender
offer made last year contributed to the earnings decline. It noted
that the Delaware Chancery Court has set a May 24 hearing on
company motions to invalidate Prime's takeover defense.
   ``MBF remains committed to acquiring Prime at the earliest
possible time,'' said company Chairman Bennett S. LeBow.
   Orders for company products declined 5 percent in the first six
months of the company's fiscal year, compared to the same period a
year ago, primarily because of lower European sales, Patton said.
   MAI Basic Four designs, manufacturers and markets mid-range
business computers and information processing systems for
multi-user applications worldwide. The company, which has 4,200
employees, markets products in 39 countries.
</TEXT>
